{"title_page": "Jim Croce", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name         = Jim Croce\n| background   = solo_singer\n| image        = Jim-Croce-r01.jpg\n| image_size   = 220\n| landscape    = \n| caption      = Croce in 1972, photographed by Ingrid Croce\n| birth_name   = James Joseph Croce\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1943|1|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[South Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1973|9|20|1943|1|10}}\n| death_place  = [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]]\n| genre        = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[rock music|rock]], [[soft rock]]\n| occupation   = Singer, songwriter\n| instrument   = Vocals, acoustic guitar\n| years_active = 1966\u20131973\n| label        = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]/[[EMI]], [[ABC Records|ABC]], Saja/[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| website      = {{URL|jimcroce.com}}\n}}\n\n'''James Joseph Croce''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|r|o\u028a|t\u0283|i}}; January 10, 1943 \u2013 September 20, 1973) was an American folk and rock [[singer-songwriter]]. Between 1966 and 1973, Croce released five studio albums and numerous singles.\n\nHis first two albums were commercially unsuccessful, failing to chart or produce any hit singles. During this period, Croce took a series of odd jobs to pay bills while he  continued to write, record, and perform concerts. After forming a partnership with songwriter and guitarist [[Maury Muehleisen]], his fortunes turned in the early 1970s. His breakthrough came in 1972; his third album ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' produced three charting singles, including \"[[Time in a Bottle]]\", which reached No. 1 after his death. The follow-up album, ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]'' contained the song \"[[Bad, Bad Leroy Brown]]\", which was the only No. 1 hit he had during his lifetime.\n\nOn September 20, 1973, the day before the lead single to his fifth album, ''[[I Got a Name]]'', was released, Croce, along with five others, were killed in a plane crash, at the height of his popularity. Croce's music continued to chart throughout the 1970s following his death. His wife, [[Ingrid Croce]], was his early songwriting partner and she continued to write and record after his death, and his son [[A. J. Croce]] himself became a singer-songwriter in the 1990s.\n\n==Early life==\nCroce was born January 10, 1943,<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2020/01/10/UPI-Almanac-for-Friday-Jan-10-2020/8011578535365/ |title= UPI Almanac for Friday, Jan. 10, 2020 |agency= [[United Press International]] | date= January 10, 2020|accessdate=February 1, 2020 |archivedate= January 11, 2020|archiveurl= http://archive.is/pMTJV|url-status=live|quote=\u2026 singer Jim Croce in 1943}}</ref> in [[South Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], to James Albert Croce and Flora Mary (Babusci) Croce, both [[Italian Americans]] from [[Trasacco]] and [[Balsorano]] in [[Abruzzo]] and [[Palermo]] in [[Sicily]].<ref name=\"KeningLimited1991\">{{cite book|author1=Dan Kening|author2=Publications International, Limited|author3=David O'Shea|author4=Jay Paris|title=Too Young to Die|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l_2quq0BXaoC|accessdate=August 19, 2011|date=June 1991|publisher=Publications International, Limited|page=37|isbn=978-0-88176-932-6}}</ref><ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Jim-Croce/6000000070323228958 James Joseph Croce on Geni.com] James Albert Croce son of Pasquale Anthony Croce born May 14, 1888, in Trasacco (Abruzzo) and Carmella Croce born June 24, 1894, in Palermo (Sicily). Flora Mary Croce (Babusci) daughter of Massimo Babusci born August 13, 1884, in Trasacco (Abruzzo), and Bernice Babusci (Ippolito or Ippoliti) born circa 1888 in Balsorano (Abruzzo).</ref>\n\nCroce grew up in [[Upper Darby]], Pennsylvania just outside of Philadelphia and attended [[Upper Darby High School]]. Graduating in 1960, he studied at [[Malvern Preparatory School]] for a year before enrolling at [[Villanova University]], where he majored in [[psychology]] and minored in [[German language|German]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite interview|work=89.3 KPCC|series=Take Two |url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/take-two/2012/10/08/28748/new-book-looks-at-singer-songwriter-jim-croces-too/ |title=New book looks at singer-songwriter Jim Croce's too-short life |publisher=Southern California Public Radio |date=2012-10-08 |author1=Alex Cohen |author2=A Mart\u00ednez |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/music/17053704-421/jim-croces-hit-had-roots-in-boot-camp.html |title=Jim Croce's hit had roots in boot camp |newspaper=Sun-Times |location= Chicago, IL |publisher=Sun-Times Media, LLC |date=16 December 2012 |first=Dave |last=Hoekstra |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in 1965. Croce was a member of the [[Villanova University#Music activities|Villanova Singers]] and the [[Villanova University#Music activities|Villanova Spires]]. When the Spires performed off-campus or made recordings, they were known as The Coventry Lads.<ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/inquirer-anniversary-croces-capture-time-in-a-bottle.html|title=Inquirer Anniversary: Croces capture time in a bottle|url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/local/20090810_Croces_capture_time_in_a_bottle.html|archivedate=August 10, 2009|date=August 10, 2009|accessdate=November 27, 2011|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]}}</ref> Croce was also a student disc jockey at WKVU (which has since become [[WXVU]]).<ref>Villanova ''Parents' Connection'' newsletter (Spring 2007).</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Grottini | first = Kyle J. | url = http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Croce__Jim.html | title = Croce, James Joseph (Jim) | publisher = Pennsylvania Center for the Book | accessdate = May 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611020306/http://www.pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Croce__Jim.html | archivedate = June 11, 2010 }}</ref><ref>Stevens, Candace. [http://www.villanovan.com/2.7322/time-to-tune-in-to-villanova-s-own-wxvu-1.1023038 \"Time to tune in to Villanova\u2019s own WXVU\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130706164433/http://www.villanovan.com/2.7322/time-to-tune-in-to-villanova-s-own-wxvu-1.1023038 |date=2013-07-06 }}, ''[[The Villanovan]]'', September 21, 2006, updated January 18, 2010. Retrieved on July 6, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\nCroce did not take music seriously until he studied at Villanova, where he formed bands and performed at [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] parties, [[coffee house]]s, and universities around [[Philadelphia]], playing \"anything that the people wanted to hear: blues, rock, [[a cappella]], railroad music ... anything.\" Croce's band was chosen for a [[Student exchange program|foreign exchange]] tour of [[Africa]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Yugoslavia]]. He later said, \"We just ate what the people ate, lived in the woods, and played our songs. Of course they didn't speak English over there but if you mean what you're singing, people understand.\" On November 29, 1963, Croce met his future wife [[Ingrid Croce|Ingrid Jacobson]] at the [[Philadelphia Convention Hall]] during a [[hootenanny]], where he was judging a contest.\n\nCroce released his first album, [[Facets (album)|''Facets'']], in 1966, with 500 copies pressed. The album had been financed with a $500 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|500|1966}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) wedding gift from Croce's parents, who set a condition that the money must be spent to make an album. They hoped that he would give up music after the album failed, and use his college education to pursue a \"respectable\" profession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/jim-croce/news/jim-croce-release-shows-him-as-young-man--12174841 |title=Jim Croce News \u2013 Yahoo! Music |publisher=Music.yahoo.com |date=2004-04-08 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> However, the album proved a success, with every copy sold.\n\n=== 1960s ===\nCroce married his wife, Ingrid, in 1966, and [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]], as his wife was Jewish. He and Ingrid were married in a [[Jewish wedding|traditional Jewish ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Elizabeth Applebaum |newspaper=[[The Detroit Jewish News]] |url=http://www.netporch.com/sa/ |title=Article: Photographs And Memories, A story of love, music and conversion |publisher=The Northern Music Group, Inc. |date=1998 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He enlisted in the [[Army National Guard]] that same year to avoid being drafted and deployed to [[Vietnam]], and served on active duty for four months, leaving for duty a week after his honeymoon.<ref>''[[The Inquirer]]'' (13 August 1967 issue)</ref> Croce, who was not good with authority, had to go through basic training twice.<ref>{{cite web|first=Carl |last=Wiser |url=http://www.songfacts.com/blog/interviews/ingrid_croce/ |title=Ingrid Croce: Songwriter Interviews |publisher=Songfacts.com |date=2007-05-01 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He said he would be prepared if \"there's ever a war where we have to defend ourselves with mops.\"\n\nFrom the mid-1960s to early 1970s, Croce performed with his wife as a duo. At first, their performances included songs by artists such as [[Ian & Sylvia]], [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Joan Baez]], and [[Arlo Guthrie]], but in time they began writing their own music. During this time, Croce got his first long-term gig at a suburban bar and [[steakhouse]] in [[Lima, Pennsylvania]], called The Riddle Paddock. His set list covered several genres, including blues, country, rock and roll, and folk.\n\nIn 1968, the Croces were encouraged by record producer [[Tommy West (producer)|Tommy West]] to move to [[New York City]]. The couple spent time in the [[Kingsbridge, Bronx|Kingsbridge]] section of the Bronx and recorded their first album with [[Capitol Records]]. During the next two years, they drove more than {{convert|300,000|mi}},<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070802142841/http://www.croces.com/croces.shtml Croce's Restaurant- San Diego]. Croces.com. Retrieved July 11, 2011.</ref> playing small clubs and concerts on the college concert circuit promoting their album ''[[Jim & Ingrid Croce]]''.\n\nBecoming disillusioned by the music business and New York City, they sold all but one guitar to pay the rent and returned to the Pennsylvania countryside, settling in an old farm in [[Lyndell, Pennsylvania|Lyndell]], where playing for $25 a night (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|25|1970}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) was not enough money to live on, and Croce was forced to take odd jobs such as [[truck driver|driving trucks]], [[construction worker|construction work]] and teaching guitar to pay the bills while continuing to write songs, often about the characters he would meet at the local bars and [[truck stops]] and his experiences at work; these provided the material for such songs as \"Big Wheel\" and \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]].\"<ref>Jim Croce Anthology (Songbook): The Stories Behind the Songs, By Ingrid Croce, Jim Croce</ref>\n\n=== 1970s ===\n[[File:Jim Croce Wide World In Concert.jpg|thumb|Croce performing]]\nThey returned to [[Philadelphia]] and Croce decided to be \"serious\" about becoming a productive member of society. \"I'd worked construction crews, and I'd been a welder while I was in college. But I'd rather do other things than get burned.\" His determination to be \"serious\" led to a job at a Philadelphia [[R&B]] AM radio station, [[WHAT (AM)|WHAT]], where he translated commercials into \"soul.\" \"I'd sell airtime to Bronco's Poolroom and then write the spot: \"You wanna be cool, and you wanna shoot pool ... ''dig it''.\"\n\nIn 1970, Croce met classically trained pianist-guitarist and singer-songwriter [[Maury Muehleisen]] from [[Trenton, New Jersey]], through producer Joe Salviuolo. Salviuolo and Croce had been friends when they studied at Villanova University, and Salviuolo had met Muehleisen when he was teaching at [[Rowan University|Glassboro State College]] in New Jersey. Salviuolo brought Croce and Muehleisen together at the [[production office]] of [[Tommy West (producer)|Tommy West]] and [[Terry Cashman]] in New York City. Croce at first backed Muehleisen on guitar,  but gradually their roles reversed, with Muehleisen adding a lead guitar to Croce's music.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nWhen Jim Croce and Ingrid discovered they were going to have a child, Jim became more determined to make music his profession. He sent a cassette of his new songs to a friend and producer in New York City in the hope that he could get a record deal. When their son [[A. J. Croce|Adrian James (A.J.)]] was born in September 1971, Ingrid became a stay-at-home mom while Jim went on the road to promote his music.\n\nIn 1972, Croce signed a three-record contract with [[ABC Records]], releasing two albums, ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' and ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]''. The singles \"[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim (song)|You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]\", \"[[Operator (That's Not the Way It Feels)]]\" and \"[[Time in a Bottle]]\" (which features in the movie, [[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]) all received airplay. Also that year, the Croce family moved to [[San Diego]], [[California]]. Croce began appearing on television, including his national debut on ''American Bandstand''<ref>americanbandstandperformerlist</ref> on August 12, ''The Tonight Show''<ref>johnnycarson.com</ref> on August 14 and ''The Dick Cavett Show'' on September 20 and 21.\n\nCroce began touring the United States with Muehleisen, performing in large coffee houses, on college campuses and at folk festivals. However, his financial situation was still bad. The record company had fronted him the money to record and much of his earnings went to pay back the advance. {{nowrap|In February 1973,}} Croce and Muehleisen travelled to [[Europe]], performing in [[London]], [[Paris]],  [[Amsterdam]], [[Monte Carlo]], [[Zurich]] and [[Dublin]] and receiving positive reviews. Croce made television appearances on ''[[The Midnight Special (TV series)|The Midnight Special]],'' which he co-hosted on {{nowrap|June 15}}, and ''The Helen Reddy Show'' on July 19. Croce's biggest single, \"[[Bad, Bad Leroy Brown]],\" reached Number 1 on the American charts in July.\n\nFrom July 16 through August 4, Croce and Muehleisen returned to London and performed on ''[[The Old Grey Whistle Test]],'' where they sang \"Lover's Cross\" and \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]]\" from their upcoming album ''[[I Got a Name]].'' Croce finished recording the album just a week before his death. While on tour, he grew increasingly homesick and decided to take a break from music and settle with Ingrid and A.J. when his ''Life and Times'' tour ended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/article-written-by-barry-weber.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807083834/http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/article-written-by-barry-weber.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-08-07 |first=Bryan |last=Weber |title=Article |publisher=Jim Croce- The Official Site |date=2014 |accessdate=2014-04-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Colin |last=Devenish |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/croces-lost-recordings-due-20030820 |title=Croce's Lost Recordings Due |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2003-08-20 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> In a letter to Ingrid which arrived after his death, Croce told her he had decided to quit music and stick to writing short stories and movie scripts as a career and withdraw from {{nowrap|public life.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>Everitt, Richard:''Falling Stars: Air Crashes that Filled Rock and Roll Heaven'' (2004)</ref>}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn Thursday, September 20, 1973, during Croce's ''Life and Times'' tour and the day before his ABC single \"[[I Got a Name (song)|I Got a Name]]\" was released, Croce and all five others on board were killed when their chartered [[Beechcraft Model 18|Beechcraft E18S]] crashed into a tree during takeoff from the [[Natchitoches Regional Airport]] in [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]]. Croce was 30 years old. Others killed in the crash were pilot Robert N. Elliott, Maury Muehleisen, comedian George Stevens, manager and booking agent Kenneth D. Cortese and road manager Dennis Rast.<ref name=rstrap>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=py1OAAAAIBAJ&pg=5658%2C2870135 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Recording star, 5 others killed in crash of plane |date=September 22, 1973 |page=9}}</ref><ref name=AP>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2706&dat=19730922&id=NxZKAAAAIBAJ&pg=2941,1273229 |newspaper=The Michigan Daily |title=Rock group killed |agency=Associated Press |date=September 22, 1973 |page=2 |location=(Ann Arbor)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.check-six.com/lib/Famous_Missing/Celebrity_Plane_Crashes.htm |title=Celebrity Plane Crashes |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |publisher=Check-Six.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714012315/http://www.check-six.com/lib/Famous_Missing/Celebrity_Plane_Crashes.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref> An hour before the crash, Croce had completed a concert at [[Northwestern State University]]'s [[Prather Coliseum]] in Natchitoches; he was flying to [[Sherman, Texas]], for a concert at [[Austin College]].\n\nAn investigation showed the twin-engine plane crashed after clipping a pecan tree at the end of the runway. The pilot had failed to gain sufficient altitude to clear the tree and had not tried to avoid it, even though it was the only tree in the area. It was well after sunset, but there was a clear sky, calm winds and over five miles of visibility with haze.\n\nThe report from the [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]]<ref name=\"ntsb_report\">{{cite report|url=http://ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.aviation/brief.aspx?ev_id=84416&key=0&print=1 |title=NTSB Identification: FTW74AF017; 14 CFR Part 135 Nonscheduled operation of Robert Airways; Aircraft: Beech E18S, registration: N50JR |date=September 20, 1973 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]].gov}}</ref> named the probable cause as the pilot's failure to see the obstruction due to physical impairment and because fog reduced his vision. The 57-year-old Elliott suffered from severe [[coronary artery disease]] and had run three miles to the airport from a motel. He had an [[Airline Transport Pilot Licence|ATP certificate]], 14,290 hours total flight time and 2,190 hours in the Beech 18 type airplane.<ref name=\"ntsb_report\" /> A later investigation placed the sole blame on [[pilot error]] due to his downwind takeoff into a \"black hole,\" severe darkness limiting his use of visual references.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://openjurist.org/623/f2d/1084/croce-v-bromley-corporation|title=Croce v. Bromley Corporation|publisher=Openjurist.org|date=August 14, 1980|volume=F2d|issue=623|pages=1084|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nCroce was buried at [[Haym Salomon]] Memorial Park in [[Frazer, Pennsylvania]].\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe album ''I Got a Name'' was released on December 1, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/croce_jim/albums.jhtml?albumId=373780|title=Jim Croce Album I Got A Name|publisher=[[VH1]].com|accessdate=November 27, 2011}}</ref> The [[List of works published posthumously|posthumous]] release included three hits: \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]],\" \"[[I'll Have to Say I Love You in a Song]],\" and the [[I Got a Name (song)|title song]], which had been used as the theme to the film ''[[The Last American Hero]]'' which was released two months prior to his death. The album reached No. 2 and \"I'll Have to Say I Love You in a Song\" reached No. 9 on the singles chart.\n\nA greatest hits album entitled ''[[Photographs & Memories]]'' was released in 1974. Later posthumous releases have included ''[[Home Recordings: Americana]]'', ''[[The Faces I've Been]]'', ''Jim Croce: Classic Hits'', ''[[Down the Highway]]'', and DVD and CD releases of Croce's television performances, ''[[Have You Heard: Jim Croce Live]]''. In 1990, Croce was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/C119|title=Songwriters Hall of Fame \u2013 Jim Croce|publisher=[[Songwriters Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 2012, Ingrid Croce published a memoir about her husband entitled ''I Got a Name: The Jim Croce Story.''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Croce, Ingrid  |author2=Rock, Jimmy|title=I Got a Name: The Jim Croce Story|year=2012|publisher=Da Capo Press|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_Vq4KZ4hUaUC |isbn=978-0-306-82123-3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Ingrid Croce opened Croce's Restaurant & Jazz Bar, a project she and Jim had jokingly discussed over a decade earlier, in the historic [[Gaslamp Quarter, San Diego|Gaslamp Quarter]] in downtown San Diego. She owned and managed it until it closed on December 31, 2013. In December 2013, she opened Croce's Park West on 5th Avenue in the Bankers Hill neighborhood near Balboa Park. She closed this restaurant in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andie |last=Adams |url=http://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/Croces-Park-West-Closes-for-Good-366499371.html |publisher=[[NBC]] San Diego |title=Croce's Park West Closes for Good |date=January 25, 2016 |accessdate=March 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCroce's music has appeared in several popular movies and television shows, such as ''[[Invincible (2006 film)|Invincible]], [[The Hangover Part II]], [[Django Unchained]], [[X-Men: Days of Future Past]], [[Logan (film)|Logan]] and [[Stranger Things]]''.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Jim Croce discography}}\n* ''[[Facets (album)|Facets]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Jim & Ingrid Croce]]'' (1969)\n* ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[I Got a Name]]'' (1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://www.jimcroce.com|Jim Croce official website}}\n*{{cite web | title = Wall of Fame| publisher = [[Upper Darby High School]]| url = http://www.udsd.k12.pa.us/alumni/wof.php| accessdate =October 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071009225810/http://www.udsd.k12.pa.us/alumni/wof.php |archivedate = October 9, 2007}}\n*{{FAG|1221}}\n\n{{Jim Croce}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croce, Jim}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Beechcraft Model 18]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:ABC Records artists]]\n[[Category:American folk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Burials in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Converts to Judaism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American pop guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:EMI Records artists]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:American acoustic guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Malvern Preparatory School alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from L'Aquila]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Jewish folk singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Malvern, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name         = Jim Croce\n| background   = solo_singer\n| image        = Jim-Croce-r01.jpg\n| image_size   = 220\n| landscape    = \n| caption      = Croce in 1972, photographed by Ingrid Croce\n| birth_name   = James Joseph Croce\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1943|1|10|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[South Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1973|9|20|1943|1|10}}\n| death_place  = [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]]\n| genre        = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[rock music|rock]], [[soft rock]]\n| occupation   = Singer, songwriter\n| instrument   = Vocals, acoustic guitar\n| years_active = 1966\u20131973\n| label        = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]/[[EMI]], [[ABC Records|ABC]], Saja/[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| website      = {{URL|jimcroce.com}}\n}}\n\n'''James Joseph Croce''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|r|o\u028a|t\u0283|i}}; January 10, 1943 \u2013 September 20, 1973) was an American folk and rock [[singer-songwriter]]. Between 1966 and 1973, Croce released five studio albums and numerous singles.\n\nHis first two albums were commercially unsuccessful, failing to chart or produce any hit singles. During this period, Croce took a series of odd jobs to pay bills while he  continued to write, record, and perform concerts. After forming a partnership with songwriter and guitarist [[Maury Muehleisen]], his fortunes turned in the early 1970s. His breakthrough came in 1972; his third album ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' produced three charting singles, including \"[[Time in a Bottle]]\", which reached No. 1 after his death. The follow-up album, ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]'' contained the song \"[[Bad, Bad Leroy Brown]]\", which was the only No. 1 hit he had during his lifetime.\n\nOn September 20, 1973, the day before the lead single to his fifth album, ''[[I Got a Name]]'', was released, Croce, along with five others, were killed in a plane crash, at the height of his popularity. Croce's music continued to chart throughout the 1970s following his death. His wife, [[Ingrid Croce]], was his early songwriting partner and she continued to write and record after his death, and his son [[A. J. Croce]] himself became a singer-songwriter in the 1990s.\n\n==Early life==\nCroce was born January 10, 1943,<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2020/01/10/UPI-Almanac-for-Friday-Jan-10-2020/8011578535365/ |title= UPI Almanac for Friday, Jan. 10, 2020 |agency= [[United Press International]] | date= January 10, 2020|accessdate=February 1, 2020 |archivedate= January 11, 2020|archiveurl= http://archive.is/pMTJV|url-status=live|quote=\u2026 singer Jim Croce in 1943}}</ref> in [[South Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], to James Albert Croce and Flora Mary (Babusci) Croce, both [[Italian Americans]] from [[Trasacco]] and [[Balsorano]] in [[Abruzzo]] and [[Palermo]] in [[Sicily]].<ref name=\"KeningLimited1991\">{{cite book|author1=Dan Kening|author2=Publications International, Limited|author3=David O'Shea|author4=Jay Paris|title=Too Young to Die|url=https://books.google.com/?id=l_2quq0BXaoC|accessdate=August 19, 2011|date=June 1991|publisher=Publications International, Limited|page=37|isbn=978-0-88176-932-6}}</ref><ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Jim-Croce/6000000070323228958 James Joseph Croce on Geni.com] James Albert Croce son of Pasquale Anthony Croce born May 14, 1888, in Trasacco (Abruzzo) and Carmella Croce born June 24, 1894, in Palermo (Sicily). Flora Mary Croce (Babusci) daughter of Massimo Babusci born August 13, 1884, in Trasacco (Abruzzo), and Bernice Babusci (Ippolito or Ippoliti) born circa 1888 in Balsorano (Abruzzo).</ref>\n\nCroce grew up in [[Upper Darby]], Pennsylvania just outside of Philadelphia and attended [[Upper Darby High School]]. Graduating in 1960, he studied at [[Malvern Preparatory School]] for a year before enrolling at [[Villanova University]], where he majored in [[psychology]] and minored in [[German language|German]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite interview|work=89.3 KPCC|series=Take Two |url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/take-two/2012/10/08/28748/new-book-looks-at-singer-songwriter-jim-croces-too/ |title=New book looks at singer-songwriter Jim Croce's too-short life |publisher=Southern California Public Radio |date=2012-10-08 |author1=Alex Cohen |author2=A Mart\u00ednez |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/music/17053704-421/jim-croces-hit-had-roots-in-boot-camp.html |title=Jim Croce's hit had roots in boot camp |newspaper=Sun-Times |location= Chicago, IL |publisher=Sun-Times Media, LLC |date=16 December 2012 |first=Dave |last=Hoekstra |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in 1965. Croce was a member of the [[Villanova University#Music activities|Villanova Singers]] and the [[Villanova University#Music activities|Villanova Spires]]. When the Spires performed off-campus or made recordings, they were known as The Coventry Lads.<ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/inquirer-anniversary-croces-capture-time-in-a-bottle.html|title=Inquirer Anniversary: Croces capture time in a bottle|url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/local/20090810_Croces_capture_time_in_a_bottle.html|archivedate=August 10, 2009|date=August 10, 2009|accessdate=November 27, 2011|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]}}</ref> Croce was also a student disc jockey at WKVU (which has since become [[WXVU]]).<ref>Villanova ''Parents' Connection'' newsletter (Spring 2007).</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Grottini | first = Kyle J. | url = http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Croce__Jim.html | title = Croce, James Joseph (Jim) | publisher = Pennsylvania Center for the Book | accessdate = May 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611020306/http://www.pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Croce__Jim.html | archivedate = June 11, 2010 }}</ref><ref>Stevens, Candace. [http://www.villanovan.com/2.7322/time-to-tune-in-to-villanova-s-own-wxvu-1.1023038 \"Time to tune in to Villanova\u2019s own WXVU\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130706164433/http://www.villanovan.com/2.7322/time-to-tune-in-to-villanova-s-own-wxvu-1.1023038 |date=2013-07-06 }}, ''[[The Villanovan]]'', September 21, 2006, updated January 18, 2010. Retrieved on July 6, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\nCroce did not take music seriously until he studied at Villanova, where he formed bands and performed at [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] parties, [[coffee house]]s, and universities around [[Philadelphia]], playing \"anything that the people wanted to hear: blues, rock, [[a cappella]], railroad music ... anything.\" Croce's band was chosen for a [[Student exchange program|foreign exchange]] tour of [[Africa]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Yugoslavia]]. He later said, \"We just ate what the people ate, lived in the woods, and played our songs. Of course they didn't speak English over there but if you mean what you're singing, people understand.\" On November 29, 1963, Croce met his future wife [[Ingrid Croce|Ingrid Jacobson]] at the [[Philadelphia Convention Hall]] during a [[hootenanny]], where he was judging a contest.\n\nCroce released his first album, [[Facets (album)|''Facets'']], in 1966, with 500 copies pressed. The album had been financed with a $500 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|500|1966}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) wedding gift from Croce's parents, who set a condition that the money must be spent to make an album. They hoped that he would give up music after the album failed, and use his college education to pursue a \"respectable\" profession.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/jim-croce/news/jim-croce-release-shows-him-as-young-man--12174841 |title=Jim Croce News \u2013 Yahoo! Music |publisher=Music.yahoo.com |date=2004-04-08 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> However, the album proved a success, with every copy sold.\n\n=== 1960s ===\nCroce married his wife, Ingrid, in 1966, and [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]], as his wife was Jewish. He and Ingrid were married in a [[Jewish wedding|traditional Jewish ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Elizabeth Applebaum |newspaper=[[The Detroit Jewish News]] |url=http://www.netporch.com/sa/ |title=Article: Photographs And Memories, A story of love, music and conversion |publisher=The Northern Music Group, Inc. |date=1998 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He enlisted in the [[Army National Guard]] that same year to avoid being drafted and deployed to [[Vietnam]], and served on active duty for four months, leaving for duty a week after his honeymoon.<ref>''[[The Inquirer]]'' (13 August 1967 issue)</ref> Croce, who was not good with authority, had to go through basic training twice.<ref>{{cite web|first=Carl |last=Wiser |url=http://www.songfacts.com/blog/interviews/ingrid_croce/ |title=Ingrid Croce: Songwriter Interviews |publisher=Songfacts.com |date=2007-05-01 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> He said he would be prepared if \"there's ever a war where we have to defend ourselves with mops.\"\n\nFrom the mid-1960s to early 1970s, Croce performed with his wife as a duo. At first, their performances included songs by artists such as [[Ian & Sylvia]], [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Joan Baez]], and [[Arlo Guthrie]], but in time they began writing their own music. During this time, Croce got his first long-term gig at a suburban bar and [[steakhouse]] in [[Lima, Pennsylvania]], called The Riddle Paddock. His set list covered several genres, including blues, country, rock and roll, and folk.\n\nIn 1968, the Croces were encouraged by record producer [[Tommy West (producer)|Tommy West]] to move to [[New York City]]. The couple spent time in the [[Kingsbridge, Bronx|Kingsbridge]] section of the Bronx and recorded their first album with [[Capitol Records]]. During the next two years, they drove more than {{convert|300,000|mi}},<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070802142841/http://www.croces.com/croces.shtml Croce's Restaurant- San Diego]. Croces.com. Retrieved July 11, 2011.</ref> playing small clubs and concerts on the college concert circuit promoting their album ''[[Jim & Ingrid Croce]]''.\n\nBecoming disillusioned by the music business and New York City, they sold all but one guitar to pay the rent and returned to the Pennsylvania countryside, settling in an old farm in [[Lyndell, Pennsylvania|Lyndell]], where playing for $25 a night (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|25|1970}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) was not enough money to live on, and Croce was forced to take odd jobs such as [[truck driver|driving trucks]], [[construction worker|construction work]] and teaching guitar to pay the bills while continuing to write songs, often about the characters he would meet at the local bars and [[truck stops]] and his experiences at work; these provided the material for such songs as \"Big Wheel\" and \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]].\"<ref>Jim Croce Anthology (Songbook): The Stories Behind the Songs, By Ingrid Croce, Jim Croce</ref>\n\n=== 1970s ===\n[[File:Jim Croce Wide World In Concert.jpg|thumb|Croce performing]]\nThey returned to [[Philadelphia]] and Croce decided to be \"serious\" about becoming a productive member of society. \"I'd worked construction crews, and I'd been a welder while I was in college. But I'd rather do other things than get burned.\" His determination to be \"serious\" led to a job at a Philadelphia [[R&B]] AM radio station, [[WHAT (AM)|WHAT]], where he translated commercials into \"soul.\" \"I'd sell airtime to Bronco's Poolroom and then write the spot: \"You wanna be cool, and you wanna shoot pool ... ''dig it''.\"\n\nIn 1970, Croce met classically trained pianist-guitarist and singer-songwriter [[Maury Muehleisen]] from [[Trenton, New Jersey]], through producer Joe Salviuolo. Salviuolo and Croce had been friends when they studied at Villanova University, and Salviuolo had met Muehleisen when he was teaching at [[Rowan University|Glassboro State College]] in New Jersey. Salviuolo brought Croce and Muehleisen together at the [[production office]] of [[Tommy West (producer)|Tommy West]] and [[Terry Cashman]] in New York City. Croce at first backed Muehleisen on guitar,  but gradually their roles reversed, with Muehleisen adding a lead guitar to Croce's music.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nWhen Jim Croce and Ingrid discovered they were going to have a child, Jim became more determined to make music his profession. He sent a cassette of his new songs to a friend and producer in New York City in the hope that he could get a record deal. When their son [[A. J. Croce|Adrian James (A.J.)]] was born in September 1971, Ingrid became a stay-at-home mom while Jim went on the road to promote his music.\n\nIn 1972, Croce signed a three-record contract with [[ABC Records]], releasing two albums, ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' and ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]''. The singles \"[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim (song)|You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]\", \"[[Operator (That's Not the Way It Feels)]]\" and \"[[Time in a Bottle]]\" (which features in the movie, [[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]) all received airplay. Also that year, the Croce family moved to [[San Diego]], [[California]]. Croce began appearing on television, including his national debut on ''American Bandstand''<ref>americanbandstandperformerlist</ref> on August 12, ''The Tonight Show''<ref>johnnycarson.com</ref> on August 14 and ''The Dick Cavett Show'' on September 20 and 21.\n\nCroce began touring the United States with Muehleisen, performing in large coffee houses, on college campuses and at folk festivals. However, his financial situation was still bad. The record company had fronted him the money to record and much of his earnings went to pay back the advance. {{nowrap|In February 1973,}} Croce and Muehleisen travelled to [[Europe]], performing in [[London]], [[Paris]],  [[Amsterdam]], [[Monte Carlo]], [[Zurich]] and [[Dublin]] and receiving positive reviews. Croce made television appearances on ''[[The Midnight Special (TV series)|The Midnight Special]],'' which he co-hosted on {{nowrap|June 15}}, and ''The Helen Reddy Show'' on July 19. Croce's biggest single, \"[[Bad, Bad Leroy Brown]],\" reached Number 1 on the American charts in July.\n\nFrom July 16 through August 4, Croce and Muehleisen returned to London and performed on ''[[The Old Grey Whistle Test]],'' where they sang \"Lover's Cross\" and \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]]\" from their upcoming album ''[[I Got a Name]].'' Croce finished recording the album just a week before his death. While on tour, he grew increasingly homesick and decided to take a break from music and settle with Ingrid and A.J. when his ''Life and Times'' tour ended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/article-written-by-barry-weber.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120807083834/http://www.jimcroce.com/articles/article-written-by-barry-weber.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-08-07 |first=Bryan |last=Weber |title=Article |publisher=Jim Croce- The Official Site |date=2014 |accessdate=2014-04-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Colin |last=Devenish |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/croces-lost-recordings-due-20030820 |title=Croce's Lost Recordings Due |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2003-08-20 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> In a letter to Ingrid which arrived after his death, Croce told her he had decided to quit music and stick to writing short stories and movie scripts as a career and withdraw from {{nowrap|public life.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref>Everitt, Richard:''Falling Stars: Air Crashes that Filled Rock and Roll Heaven'' (2004)</ref>}}\n\n== Death ==\nOn Thursday, September 20, 1973, during Croce's ''Life and Times'' tour and the day before his ABC single \"[[I Got a Name (song)|I Got a Name]]\" was released, Croce and all five others on board were killed when their chartered [[Beechcraft Model 18|Beechcraft E18S]] crashed into a tree during takeoff from the [[Natchitoches Regional Airport]] in [[Natchitoches, Louisiana]]. Croce was 30 years old. Others killed in the crash were pilot Robert N. Elliott, Maury Muehleisen, comedian George Stevens, manager and booking agent Kenneth D. Cortese and road manager Dennis Rast.<ref name=rstrap>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=py1OAAAAIBAJ&pg=5658%2C2870135 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Recording star, 5 others killed in crash of plane |date=September 22, 1973 |page=9}}</ref><ref name=AP>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2706&dat=19730922&id=NxZKAAAAIBAJ&pg=2941,1273229 |newspaper=The Michigan Daily |title=Rock group killed |agency=Associated Press |date=September 22, 1973 |page=2 |location=(Ann Arbor)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.check-six.com/lib/Famous_Missing/Celebrity_Plane_Crashes.htm |title=Celebrity Plane Crashes |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |publisher=Check-Six.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714012315/http://www.check-six.com/lib/Famous_Missing/Celebrity_Plane_Crashes.htm |archivedate=July 14, 2011 }}</ref> An hour before the crash, Croce had completed a concert at [[Northwestern State University]]'s [[Prather Coliseum]] in Natchitoches; he was flying to [[Sherman, Texas]], for a concert at [[Austin College]].\n\nAn investigation showed the twin-engine plane crashed after clipping a pecan tree at the end of the runway. The pilot had failed to gain sufficient altitude to clear the tree and had not tried to avoid it, even though it was the only tree in the area. It was well after sunset, but there was a clear sky, calm winds and over five miles of visibility with haze.\n\nThe report from the [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]]<ref name=\"ntsb_report\">{{cite report|url=http://ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.aviation/brief.aspx?ev_id=84416&key=0&print=1 |title=NTSB Identification: FTW74AF017; 14 CFR Part 135 Nonscheduled operation of Robert Airways; Aircraft: Beech E18S, registration: N50JR |date=September 20, 1973 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]].gov}}</ref> named the probable cause as the pilot's failure to see the obstruction due to physical impairment and because fog reduced his vision. The 57-year-old Elliott suffered from severe [[coronary artery disease]] and had run three miles to the airport from a motel. He had an [[Airline Transport Pilot Licence|ATP certificate]], 14,290 hours total flight time and 2,190 hours in the Beech 18 type airplane.<ref name=\"ntsb_report\" /> A later investigation placed the sole blame on [[pilot error]] due to his downwind takeoff into a \"black hole,\" severe darkness limiting his use of visual references.<ref>{{cite document|url=http://openjurist.org/623/f2d/1084/croce-v-bromley-corporation|title=Croce v. Bromley Corporation|publisher=Openjurist.org|date=August 14, 1980|volume=F2d|issue=623|pages=1084|accessdate=July 11, 2011|last2=Circuit|first2=Fifth}}</ref>\n\nCroce was buried at [[Haym Salomon]] Memorial Park in [[Frazer, Pennsylvania]].\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe album ''I Got a Name'' was released on December 1, 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/croce_jim/albums.jhtml?albumId=373780|title=Jim Croce Album I Got A Name|publisher=[[VH1]].com|accessdate=November 27, 2011}}</ref> The [[List of works published posthumously|posthumous]] release included three hits: \"[[Workin' at the Car Wash Blues]],\" \"[[I'll Have to Say I Love You in a Song]],\" and the [[I Got a Name (song)|title song]], which had been used as the theme to the film ''[[The Last American Hero]]'' which was released two months prior to his death. The album reached No. 2 and \"I'll Have to Say I Love You in a Song\" reached No. 9 on the singles chart.\n\nA greatest hits album entitled ''[[Photographs & Memories]]'' was released in 1974. Later posthumous releases have included ''[[Home Recordings: Americana]]'', ''[[The Faces I've Been]]'', ''Jim Croce: Classic Hits'', ''[[Down the Highway]]'', and DVD and CD releases of Croce's television performances, ''[[Have You Heard: Jim Croce Live]]''. In 1990, Croce was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/C119|title=Songwriters Hall of Fame \u2013 Jim Croce|publisher=[[Songwriters Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 2012, Ingrid Croce published a memoir about her husband entitled ''I Got a Name: The Jim Croce Story.''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Croce, Ingrid  |author2=Rock, Jimmy|title=I Got a Name: The Jim Croce Story|year=2012|publisher=Da Capo Press|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_Vq4KZ4hUaUC |isbn=978-0-306-82123-3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Ingrid Croce opened Croce's Restaurant & Jazz Bar, a project she and Jim had jokingly discussed over a decade earlier, in the historic [[Gaslamp Quarter, San Diego|Gaslamp Quarter]] in downtown San Diego. She owned and managed it until it closed on December 31, 2013. In December 2013, she opened Croce's Park West on 5th Avenue in the Bankers Hill neighborhood near Balboa Park. She closed this restaurant in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andie |last=Adams |url=http://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/Croces-Park-West-Closes-for-Good-366499371.html |publisher=[[NBC]] San Diego |title=Croce's Park West Closes for Good |date=January 25, 2016 |accessdate=March 11, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nCroce's music has appeared in several popular movies and television shows, such as ''[[Invincible (2006 film)|Invincible]], [[The Hangover Part II]], [[Django Unchained]], [[X-Men: Days of Future Past]], [[Logan (film)|Logan]] and [[Stranger Things]]''.\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Jim Croce discography}}\n* ''[[Facets (album)|Facets]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Jim & Ingrid Croce]]'' (1969)\n* ''[[You Don't Mess Around with Jim]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Life and Times (Jim Croce album)|Life and Times]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[I Got a Name]]'' (1973)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|http://www.jimcroce.com|Jim Croce official website}}\n*{{cite web | title = Wall of Fame| publisher = [[Upper Darby High School]]| url = http://www.udsd.k12.pa.us/alumni/wof.php| accessdate =October 17, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071009225810/http://www.udsd.k12.pa.us/alumni/wof.php |archivedate = October 9, 2007}}\n*{{FAG|1221}}\n\n{{Jim Croce}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croce, Jim}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American soft rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Beechcraft Model 18]]\n[[Category:Villanova University alumni]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:ABC Records artists]]\n[[Category:American folk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Burials in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Converts to Judaism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American pop guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:EMI Records artists]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records artists]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:American acoustic guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Malvern Preparatory School alumni]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from L'Aquila]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Jewish folk singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:People from Malvern, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Croce"}
{"title_page": "Jens Stoltenberg", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian politician, 13th Secretary-General of NATO, 27th Prime Minister of Norway}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Jens Stoltenberg\n|image          = NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg.jpg\n|office         = 13th [[Secretary General of NATO]]\n|term_start     = 1 October 2014\n|term_end       = \n|deputy         = [[Alexander Vershbow]]<br />[[Rose Gottemoeller]]<br />[[Mircea Geoan\u0103]]\n|predecessor    = [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]\n|successor      = \n|office1        = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n|monarch1       = [[Harald V of Norway|Harald V]]\n|term_start1    = 17 October 2005\n|term_end1      = 16 October 2013\n|predecessor1   = [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]\n|successor1     = [[Erna Solberg]]\n|monarch2       = Harald V\n|term_start2    = 17 March 2000\n|term_end2      = 19 October 2001\n|predecessor2   = [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]\n|successor2     = Kjell Magne Bondevik\n|office3= Leader of the Opposition \n|term_start3= 16 October 2013\n|term_end3= 14 June 2014\n|primeminister3= Erna Solberg \n|predecessor3= [[Erna Solberg]]\n|successor3= [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]] \n|term_start4= 19 October 2001\n|term_end4= 17 October 2005 \n|primeminister4= Kjell Magne Bondevik \n|predecessor4= \n|successor4= Erna Solberg \n|office5        = Leader of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]\n|term_start5    = 6 April 2002\n|term_end5      = 14 June 2014\n|predecessor5   = [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]\n|successor5     = [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]]\n|office6        = [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister6= [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]\n|term_start6    = 25 October 1996\n|term_end6      = 17 October 1997\n|predecessor6   = [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]\n|successor6     = [[Gudmund Restad]]\n|office7        = [[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry and Energy]]\n|primeminister7 = [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]]\n|term_start7    = 7 October 1993\n|term_end7      = 25 October 1996\n|predecessor7   = [[Finn Kristensen]] {{small|(Industry)}}\n|successor7     = [[Grete Faremo]] {{small|(Petroleum & Energy)}}\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1959|03|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|party          = [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour]]\n|spouse         = [[Ingrid Schulerud]] (1987&ndash;present)\n|children       = 2\n|parents        = [[Karin Stoltenberg|Karin Heiberg]]<br />[[Thorvald Stoltenberg]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Oslo]]\n|signature      = Jens Stoltenberg signature.svg\n|website        = {{url|nb-no.facebook.com/jensstoltenberg|Official Facebook}}<br />{{url|twitter.com/jensstoltenberg|Official Twitter}}\n}}\n\n'''Jens Stoltenberg''' (born 16 March 1959) is a Norwegian politician who has been serving as the [[List of NATO Secretaries General|13th]] [[Secretary General of NATO]] since 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/who_is_who_49999.htm\n|title=NATO Biography for Jens Stoltenberg, Secretary General |date=18 May 2017 |publisher=NATO Publications |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Stoltenberg-Jens.html |title=World Biography for Jens Stoltenberg of Norway\n|date=20 May 2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of World Biography |website=NotableBiographies.com |accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO Names Stoltenberg Next Chief |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26791044 |publisher=BBC, UK |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref> A member of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]], he was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 2000 to 2001 and from 2005 to 2013.\n\nIn 2011, Stoltenberg received the [[United Nations Foundation]]'s Champion of Global Change Award, chosen for his extraordinary effort toward meeting the [[Millennium Development Goals]] and bringing fresh ideas to global problems.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lbkPIsdwv_Q |title=Jens Stoltenberg: 2011 UN Foundation Global Leadership Awards Dinner |date=10 November 2011 |publisher=United Nations Foundation, New York City, USA |website=YouTube.com |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe mission of Jens Stoltenberg as secretary general of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was extended for another two years. Stoltenberg has been responsible for the past five years and is set to lead NATO until 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/nato-allies-extend-stoltenbergs-term-as-secretary-general/|title=NATO allies extend Stoltenberg\u2019s term as secretary-general|first=David M.|last=Herszenhorn|date=28 March 2019|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Early life===\nStoltenberg was born 16 March 1959 in [[Oslo]], Norway, into the [[Stoltenberg (Norwegian family)|Stoltenberg family]]. His father, [[Thorvald Stoltenberg]] (1931\u20132018), was a prominent Labour party politician who served as an ambassador, as defence minister and as foreign minister. His mother, [[Karin Stoltenberg]] (n\u00e9e Heiberg; 1931\u20132012), was a geneticist who served as [[state secretary]] in multiple governments during the 1980s.<ref name=a>{{cite news|last=Kolstad |first=Tom |title=Stoltenberg-familien i \u00e5penhjertig interview |trans-title=Stoltenberg family is having candid interview |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-familien-i-apenhjertig-intervju-6666837.html |newspaper=Aftenposten.no |date=17 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022120324/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-familien-i-apenhjertig-intervju-6666837.html |url-status=live |archivedate=22 October 2012 |language=no }}</ref> [[Marianne Heiberg]], married to former Foreign Minister [[Johan J\u00f8rgen Holst]], was his maternal aunt. Jens lived in [[SFR Yugoslavia]] from 1961 to 1964 while his father worked at the Norwegian embassy.<ref>{{cite web|author=V. N. |accessdate=4 April 2014 |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.289.html:379509-Stoltenberg-Beograd-ostao-u-srcu |title=Stoltenberg: Beograd ostao u srcu |trans-title=Stoltenberg: Belgrade remained in my heart |website=Novosti.rs |date=12 May 2012 |archivedate=22 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022120324/http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.289.html%3A379509-Stoltenberg-Beograd-ostao-u-srcu }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg.no/i/m69OVv|title=Jens Stoltenberg om barneskoletiden: - Jeg kunne ikke lese eller skrive|website=www.vg.no}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nStoltenberg attended primary school at [[Oslo Waldorf School]], and upper secondary school at [[Oslo katedralskole|Oslo Cathedral School]]. He served his mandatory military service with the Army's Infantry Training Centre at [[Evjemoen]] in [[Aust-Agder]].\n\nAfter leaving the army, Stoltenberg enrolled at the [[University of Oslo]], graduating in 1987 with the [[cand.oecon.]] degree in economics. The title of his thesis was ''Makro\u00f8konomisk planlegging under usikkerhet. En empirisk analyse'' (\"Macroeconomic planning under uncertainty. An empirical analysis\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssb.no/histstat/in/in_8516.pdf |last=Stoltenberg |first=Jens |title=Makro\u00f8konomisk planlegging under usikkerhet. En empirisk analyse |trans-title=Macroeconomic planning is uncertain; an empirical analysis |website=Ssb.no |accessdate=17 January 2013 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116071758/http://www.ssb.no/histstat/in/in_8516.pdf |archivedate=16 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Early political activity===\nStoltenberg's first steps into politics came in his early teens, when he was influenced by his sister [[Camilla Stoltenberg|Camilla]], who at the time was a member of the then [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] group [[Red Youth (Norway)|Red Youth]]. Opposition to the [[Vietnam War]] was his triggering motivation. Following heavy [[List of bombing campaigns of the Vietnam War|bombing raids]] against the North Vietnamese port city of [[Hai Phong]] at the end of the Vietnam War, he participated in [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|protest rallies]] targeting the [[Embassy of the United States in Oslo|United States Embassy in Oslo]]. On at least one occasion embassy windows were broken by stone-throwing protesters. Several of Stoltenberg's friends were arrested by the police after these events.<ref>{{cite book|author=Salvesen, Geir|title=Thorvalds verden|trans-title=Thorvald's world|year=1994|publisher=[[Schibsted]]|location=Oslo, Norway|pages=398\u2013399|isbn=82-516-1545-3}}</ref>\n\n===Family life===\nStoltenberg is married to diplomat [[Ingrid Schulerud]] and they have two children: a son, Axel Stoltenberg (born 1989) who is studying Chinese at the [[Shanghai Jiaotong University]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoltenberg til Kina |trans-title=Stoltenberg to China |newspaper=Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv |url=http://www.dn.no/talent/article2462660.ece |accessdate=17 January 2013 |date=3 September 2012 |language=no |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928032825/http://www.dn.no/talent/article2462660.ece |archivedate=28 September 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Axel Stoltenberg, styremedlem |url=http://www.ansa.no/ANSAland/Kina/Lokallag/ANSA-Shanghai/Styret-i-ANSA-Shanghai/Solveig-Hunstad-Evensen/ |website=Ansa.no |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archivedate=27 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927215514/http://www.ansa.no/ANSAland/Kina/Lokallag/ANSA-Shanghai/Styret-i-ANSA-Shanghai/Solveig-Hunstad-Evensen/ }}</ref> and daughter Anne Catharina Stoltenberg (born 1992) who is a part of Smerz, a pop music duo signed to [[XL Recordings]].<ref name=a/><ref>{{cite news|author=Helljesen, Vilde |title=\"Hopalong Cassidy\" fyller 50 \u00e5r |trans-title=\"Hopalong Cassidy\" turns 50 years |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6522229 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |location=Oslo, Norway |date=14 March 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518043207/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6522229 |archivedate=18 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/5391896|title=Smerz (2)|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\nHe has one living sister, [[Camilla Stoltenberg|Camilla]], a medical researcher and administrator who is one year older than him; and one late sister, [[Nini Stoltenberg|Nini]], four years younger, who died in 2014. Nini was a recovering heroin [[drug addiction|addict]], and the Norwegian media have covered the family's efforts to cope with this challenge.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Hvem i helvete i regjeringen er det som har bestemt det? \n |trans-title=Who the hell is the government that has decided it? \n |work=Dagbladet \n |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2008/04/07/531582.html \n |date=9 April 2008 \n |language=no \n |accessdate=25 October 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409234133/http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2008/04/07/531582.html \n |archivedate= 9 April 2008 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\nHe prefers to spend his summer vacations at his family's cottage on the idyllic [[Hvaler|Hvaler Islands]] in the [[Oslofjord]].<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Tinlund \n |first=Tore \n |title=Her er Stoltenbergs ferieparadis \n |trans-title=Here is Stoltenberg's vacation paradise \n |url=http://www.f-b.no/nyheter/her-er-stoltenbergs-ferieparadis-1.1830547 \n |date=31 August 2009 \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |language=no \n |newspaper=Fredrikstads blad \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620153558/http://www.f-b.no/nyheter/her-er-stoltenbergs-ferieparadis-1.1830547 \n |archivedate=20 June 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> An avid outdoorsman, he rides his bike often and during the winter season he is an active cross-country skier.<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Hellen \n |first=Bj\u00f8rnar \n |language=no \n |title=Stoltenberg tester VM-l\u00f8ypene \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg tested World Cup trails \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |publisher=NRK \n |url=http://www.nrk.no/sport/stoltenberg-testet-vm-loypene-1.7505838 \n |date=13 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928044328/http://www.nrk.no/sport/stoltenberg-testet-vm-loypene-1.7505838 \n |archivedate=28 September 2013 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> In December 2011, in order to mark 100 years since [[Roald Amundsen]] reached the south pole on skis, Stoltenberg journeyed to [[Antarctica]].<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Kristiansen \n |first=Bj\u00f8rn \n |title=Stoltenberg p\u00e5 S\u00f8rpolen \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg at the South Pole \n |language=no \n |date=13 December 2011 \n |accessdate=17 January 2012 \n |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/12/12/nyheter/innenriks/jens_stoltenberg/sorpolen/roald_amundsen/19382520/ \n |newspaper=Dagbladet \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109080304/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/12/12/nyheter/innenriks/jens_stoltenberg/sorpolen/roald_amundsen/19382520/ \n |archivedate= 9 January 2012 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nAlthough being portrayed as a staunch [[Atheism|atheist]] for most of his adult life, and declining membership in the formerly official [[Church of Norway]],<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Mel\u00e5 \n |first=Veronica \n |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=9086377 \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |newspaper=VG \n |title=Statsministeren m\u00e5 v\u00e6re kristen \n |language=no \n |date=14 July 2000 \n |archivedate=10 June 2011 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610153154/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=9086377 \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg has stated that he does not consider himself an atheist. He explained: \"Although I am not a member of any denomination, I do believe that there is something greater than man. Some call it God, others call it something else. For me, it's about understanding that we humans are small in relation to nature, in relation to the powers that are bigger and stronger than man can ever comprehend. I find that in a church.\"<ref name=b>{{cite news \n |title=Man m\u00e5 tro at det nytter \n |trans-title=One must believe that it is possible \n |url=http://www.bt.no/nyheter/--Man-ma-tro-at-det-nytter-2633333.html \n |author1=Erik Fossen \n |author2=H\u00e5vard Bjelland \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |date=31 December 2011 \n |newspaper=Bt.no \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927204323/http://www.bt.no/nyheter/--Man-ma-tro-at-det-nytter-2633333.html \n |archivedate=27 September 2013 \n |language=no \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career (1979\u20131990) ===\nFrom 1979 to 1981, Stoltenberg was a journalist for ''[[Arbeiderbladet]]''. From 1985 to 1989, he was the leader of the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]]. From 1989 to 1990, he worked as an Executive Officer for [[Statistics Norway]], Norway's central institution for producing official statistics. He also worked part-time as an hourly paid instructor at the University of Oslo during this period. Between 1990 and 1992, he was leader of the [[Oslo]] chapter of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/>\n\nUp to 1990, he had regular contacts with a Soviet diplomat. He ended this relationship after being informed by the [[Norwegian Police Security Service]] his contact was a [[KGB]] agent, warning him of further contact. Stoltenberg's code name within the KGB was \"Steklov\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Kodenavn \"Steklov\" |trans-title=Code Name \"Steklov\" |accessdate=3 November 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=5916647 |work=[[Verdens Gang|VG]] |date=24 October 2000 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018061834/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=5916647 |archivedate=18 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/amagasinet/article1187770.ece |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |language=no |accessdate=3 November 2011 |author=Kjetil S. |date=19 October 2011 |title=J\u00f8ss, herr Statsminister |trans-title=Gee, Mr. Prime Minister |archivedate=21 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021093145/http://www.aftenposten.no/amagasinet/article1187770.ece |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alf R. Jacobsen |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/07/06/kultur/debatt/kronikk/spionasje/arbeiderpartiet/17206163/ |title=Stortinget m\u00e5 granske |trans-title=Parliament must scrutinize |accessdate=27 March 2014 |date=6 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327234518/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/07/06/kultur/debatt/kronikk/spionasje/arbeiderpartiet/17206163/ |url-status=live |archivedate=27 March 2014 |language=no }}</ref>\n\n===Political career in Norway===\n\n==== Ministry for Environment and Minister for Trade and Energy (1990\u20131996) ====\n{{Main|Brundtland's Third Cabinet}}\nStoltenberg served as [[State Secretary (Norway)|State Secretary]] in the [[Norwegian Ministry of the Environment|Ministry of the Environment]] from 1990 to 1991. He was first elected to [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]] in 1993 for the [[Oslo]] constituency, and is a member of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]].  He served as [[Minister of Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry]] from 1993 to 1996, until Brundtland resigned.<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/>\n\n==== Minister of Finance (1996\u20132000) ====\n{{Main|Jagland's Cabinet}}\nIn 1996, [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]] became Prime Minister, and Stoltenberg became [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]].<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/> On 29 September 1997, Jagland resigned because of [[36.9 ultimatum|an ultimatum]] he had issued stating that the cabinet would resign should the party receive less than 36.9% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news |first=Herbj\u00f8rn |last=S\u00f8reb\u00f8 |authorlink=Herbj\u00f8rn S\u00f8reb\u00f8 |title=Ikkje noko mediemord |url=http://www.dagogtid.no/arkiv/2000/07/herb.html |work=[[Dag og Tid]] |date=17 February 2000 |language=no |url-status=dead |accessdate=31 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.dagogtid.no/arkiv/2000/07/herb.html |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref> Labour only received 35.0%; true to his promise, Jagland resigned as a consequence of its [[36.9 ultimatum]], and power was transferred to the [[Kjell Magne Bondevik's first term as Prime Minister of Norway|first cabinet of Kjell Magne Bondevik]].<ref name=resign>{{cite news|title=Meddelelse fra statsminister Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland om Regjeringens avskjedss\u00f8knad |first=Berit |last=Almendingen |date=29 September 1997 |work=Nettavisen |url=http://www.stortinget.no/no/Saker-og-publikasjoner/Saker/Sak/?p=1921 |language=no |accessdate=1 February 2009 |archivedate=16 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416195609/http://www.stortinget.no/no/Saker-og-publikasjoner/Saker/Sak/?p=1921 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SEATTLETIMES\">{{cite news|author=Mary Williams Walsh |title=Norway's Problem: Too Much Cash \u2013 Oil Is Flowing And Surplus Is Fat |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19971016&slug=2566475 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=2 February 2009 |date=16 October 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907230554/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19971016&slug=2566475 |archivedate= 7 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After Jagland's resignation and while in parliamentary opposition, Stoltenberg served on the standing committee on Oil and Energy Affairs in the [[Stortinget|Storting]].<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Stoltenberg-Jens.html|title=Jens Stoltenberg Biography|work=notablebiographies.com|language=no|accessdate=2 February 2009}}</ref> He became the Parliamentary Leader and Prime Minister candidate for the Labour Party in February 2000.\n\n==== First term as Prime Minister (2000\u20132001) ====\n{{Main|Stoltenberg's First Cabinet}}\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6-8 September 2000-28.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg with Russian [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in New York City, 2000]]\nIn 2000, the [[Kjell Magne Bondevik's first term as Prime Minister of Norway|first cabinet of Bondevik]] resigned following an unsuccessful [[motion of confidence]].<ref name=\"CABINETII\">{{cite news|title=Norway's new cabinet named |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/680950.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 March 2000 |accessdate=1 February 2009 |url-status=live |archivedate=20 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420211441/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/680950.stm }}</ref> Stoltenberg's first cabinet governed Norway from 17 March 2000 to 19 October 2001.<ref name=\"CABINETII\"/> Stoltenberg was the [[deputy leader]] of the labor party while Jagland was the [[party leader]]. Instead Jagland was given the post as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Foreign Minister]]. Stoltenberg's first tenure as Prime Minister (2000\u20132001) was controversial within his own party, being responsible for reforms and modernisation of the [[welfare state]] that included part-privatising several key state-owned services and corporations. In the [[2001 Norwegian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] of 10 September 2001, the party suffered one of its worst results ever, winning only 24% of the vote.\n\nThe 2001, election met with instability for the Labour Party. The Norwegian newspaper ''[[Dagbladet]]'' stated: \"We are heading for a political earthquake when the votes are counted tonight, if we believe the opinion polls.\"<ref name=\"LABORREIIC\"/> In an interview with [[The Associated Press]] Jagland stated \"It is unstable and unpredictable.\"<ref name=\"LABORREIIC\">{{cite news|accessdate=2 February 2009 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/europe/09/10/norway.ballot/index.html |title=Norway set for close polls result |agency=CNN |date=10 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014112310/http://edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/europe/09/10/norway.ballot/index.html |archivedate=14 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the election in 2001, Stoltenberg and his cabinet were forced to resign, with the Labour Party suffering from its worst election campaign results since 1924.<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/> With the 98% votes taken, the Labour Party only garnered 24%, falling from 35%.<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/> Jagland, the Labor Party leader, commented on the results saying, \"We will have to make a decision about whether to continue in government after we know the full results\".<ref name=\"LABORRE\">{{cite news|accessdate=1 February 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1536377.stm |title=Norway poll sparks power struggle |work=BBC News |date=11 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420211443/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1536377.stm |archivedate=20 April 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the election Stoltenberg said, \"What is clear is that this was a very bad election.\"<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/>\n\nSeveral analysts have pointed out that one of the reasonable causes for their loss was that with only one year in power until the next election, more time was spent initiating or trying to start reforms than telling the people why they had to be done. Such reforms included selling down in state-owned companies, re-organisation of health care and public hospitals and changes in sick pay. The changes made from the 2001 election to the 2005 election were described by Norwegian newspaper ''VG'' as an \"extreme makeover.\"<ref name=\"Extreme makeover\">{{cite news|first=Eirik |last=Mosveen |title=Ekstrem forvandling |trans-title=Extreme makeover |work=VG |date=11 August 2005 |language=no |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=106643 |access-date=12 March 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=13 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001303/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=106643 }}</ref>\n\n'''Party leader election'''\nThe bad election result in 2001 was quickly followed by a leadership battle between Jagland and Stoltenberg. Both Jagland, as leader, and Stoltenberg, as deputy leader, said they were open to be challenged for their positions at the party's congress in November 2002. Stoltenberg refused to say whether he would challenge Jagland for the leadership position, which was seen by political commentators as a sign that he probably would seek the leadership position.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marie Melg\u00e5rd, Tommy H. Brakstad |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/11/08/nyheter/jens_stoltenberg/thorbjorn_jagland/thor_viksveen/18933263/ |title=Slik var striden mellom Jens og Jagland |trans-title=Such was the battle between Jamie and Jagland |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=8 November 2011 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329215013/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/11/08/nyheter/jens_stoltenberg/thorbjorn_jagland/thor_viksveen/18933263/ |archivedate=29 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the beginning of February 2002, Jagland, who had been briefly hospitalized in January, and had a subsequent sick leave,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/sykemeldt-til-3.feb-1.503884 |title=Sykemeldt til 3.feb |trans-title=Sick leave on 3 February |language=no |publisher=[[NRK]] |date=17 January 2002 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004801/http://www.nrk.no/norge/sykemeldt-til-3.feb-1.503884 |url-status=dead }}</ref> said that he would not seek reelection as leader.<ref>{{cite news |language=no |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/article364621.ece#.UzVlsoVti8A |title=Gamle synder p\u00e5 lur i Ap |trans-title=Old sins lurking in AP |archivedate=29 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329220210/http://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/article364621.ece#.UzVlsoVti8A |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November 2002, Stoltenberg was unanimously elected new leader at the party's congress.<ref>{{cite news|language=no |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/stoltenberg-aps-nye-leder-1.507713 |title=Stoltenberg Aps nye leder |trans-title=Stoltenberg's Labor's new leader |date=10 November 2002 |publisher=[[NRK]] |accessdate=28 March 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004805/http://www.nrk.no/norge/stoltenberg-aps-nye-leder-1.507713 }}</ref>\n\n==== Second term as Prime Minister (2005\u20132013) ====\n[[File:Jens stoltenberg1.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg delivering a speech at Youngstorget, 1 May 2009.]]\n{{Main|Stoltenberg's Second Cabinet}}\nStoltenberg's second cabinet governed Norway from 17 October 2005 to 16 October 2013. The [[2005 Norwegian parliamentary election|2005 parliamentary election]] saw a vast improvement for Labour, and the party gained a majority in parliament together with the other \"Red-Green\" parties, the [[Sosialistisk Venstreparti|Socialist Left Party]] and the [[Senterpartiet|Centre Party]]. This paved the way for a historic first in Norway, with Labour joining in a coalition government, the [[Red-Green Coalition (Norway)|Red-Green Coalition]], after a [[First Declaration of Soria Moria|coalition deal]] with Stoltenberg was struck. Since the government's formation, key political issues such as [[Norwegian Armed Forces|Norwegian military]] participation in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]], petroleum activities in the [[Barents Sea]], [[LGBT]] rights, immigration and the quality of standard education were greatly debated by the public. Following [[2009 Norwegian parliamentary election|Stoltenberg's re-election in 2009]], he worked on the Swedish response to the [[Late-2000s recession|ongoing global recession]] and championed for [[environmentalism|environmentalist policies]] through private and corporate taxation.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=15 September 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8253849.stm |title=Norway's government is re-elected |work=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=14 September 2009 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914100558/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8253849.stm |archivedate=14 September 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Medvedev in Norway (img12).jpeg|thumb|left|Stoltenberg with Russian President [[Dimitry Medvedev]], 27 April 2010.]]\nA [[Norway\u2013Russia border|marine border dispute with Russia]] in the Barents Sea since 1978 was settled when Stoltenberg and [[President of Russia]] [[Dimitry Medvedev]] signed an agreement on 27 April 2010 in Oslo.<ref>{{cite web|date=27 April 2010 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/27/norway-russia-barents-idUSLDE63Q14D20100427?type=marketsNews |title=UPDATE 3-Russia and Norway strike Arctic sea border deal |first=Denis |last=Dyomkin |first2=Gwladys |last2=Fouche |agency=Reuters |accessdate=27 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728040728/https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/27/norway-russia-barents-idUSLDE63Q14D20100427?type=marketsNews |archivedate=28 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/28/world/europe/28norway.html |title=Russia and Norway Reach Accord on Barents Sea |first=Walter |last=Gibbs |work=[[New York Times]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430074409/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/28/world/europe/28norway.html |archivedate=30 April 2010 |url-status=live |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010 }}</ref> The agreement is a compromise, which divides a disputed area of around 175,000 km2 (68,000 sq mi) into two approximately equally sized parts.<ref name=dn-28april2010>{{cite news |title=Gjennombrudd i Barentshavet |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |pages=6\u201313 |language=no |trans-title=Breakthrough in Barents Sea |date=28 April 2010 |work=Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv |accessdate=9 April 2014 |archivedate=8 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408154744/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, the agreement still needs ratification by the [[State Duma]] and the [[Parliament of Norway]] in order to be implemented. Whereas Norway had previously insisted on a border in accordance with the [[equidistance principle]], which is recognized in international law, specifically the [[United Nations Convention on Law of the Sea]] Article 15 and the [[Convention on the Territorial Sea and the Contiguous Zone]] Article 6, Russia invoked a [[Stalin]]-era decree of the [[Soviet Union]] from 1926, which was not recognised by any other country. The new agreement replaced a controversial<ref>[[K\u00e5re Willoch]] (2002): ''Myter og virkelighet''. Oslo: Cappelen.{{page needed|date=June 2015}}</ref> temporary agreement negotiated by [[Jens Evensen]] and [[Arne Treholt]], who was later revealed to be a Soviet spy and who aided the Soviet Union in the negotiations.<ref>''Stein Vale'' (2009): ''Teppefall i Treholtsaken''. Oslo: Cappelen Damm, pp. 34\u201336 and 135.</ref> Most of the disputed area was within what would normally be considered Norwegian according to the relevant international treaties.\n\nAs Prime Minister, Stoltenberg worked for a constructive relationship with Russia through dialogue and cooperation underpinned by NATO's deterrence and defence capabilities. During his tenure, he also emphasised the need to focus on security challenges close to Allied territory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |publisher=[[Government.no]] |title=Good neighbourly relations and international cooperation |accessdate=4 April 2014 |date=4 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406210948/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |archivedate=6 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''22 July 2011 terror attacks'''\n{{Main|2011 Norway attacks}}\n[[File:Jens Stoltenberg 2012.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg speaks at a service commemorating the one year anniversary of the 2011 attacks.|alt=Jens Stoltenberg speaking at a podium.]]\nOn 22 July 2011, a bomb went off in [[Oslo]] outside the government building which houses the prime minister's office, killing eight people while wounding others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sollid|first=Stephen JM|last2=Rimstad|first2=Rune|last3=Rehn|first3=Marius|last4=Nakstad|first4=Anders R|last5=Tomlinson|first5=Ann-Elin|last6=Strand|first6=Terje|last7=Heimdal|first7=Hans|last8=Nilsen|first8=Jan|last9=Sandberg|first9=M\u00e5rten|date=2012|title=Oslo government district bombing and Ut\u00f8ya island shooting July 22, 2011: The immediate prehospital emergency medical service response|url=https://sjtrem.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1757-7241-20-3|journal=Scandinavian Journal of Trauma, Resuscitation and Emergency Medicine|language=En|volume=20|issue=1|pages=3|doi=10.1186/1757-7241-20-3|issn=1757-7241|pmc=3266631|pmid=22280935}}</ref> About an hour later, a shooting spree, which killed 69 people, was reported at [[Ut\u00f8ya]], an island forty-five minutes away where the ruling Labour Party was holding its annual youth camp. The PM was due for a visit at the youth camp the next day, and was in his residence preparing his speech at the time of the Oslo explosion.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://e24.no/makro-og-politikk/stoltenberg-skrev-tale-til-utoeya-da-bomben-smalt/20082498 \n |title=Stoltenberg skrev tale til Ut\u00f8ya da bomben smalt \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg wrote the speech to Ut\u00f8ya when the bomb hit \n |last=NTB \n |date=25 July 2011 \n |accessdate=25 July 2011 \n |publisher=[[E24 N\u00e6ringsliv|E24]] \n |language=no \n |archivedate= 9 August 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809041912/http://e24.no/makro-og-politikk/stoltenberg-skrev-tale-til-utoeya-da-bomben-smalt/20082498 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday 24 July, Stoltenberg spoke at the church service in the [[Oslo Cathedral]]. He named two of the victims at Ut\u00f8ya, Monica B\u00f8sei, who was the camp's leader, and Tore Eikeland, who was the leader of the youth chapter in Hordaland. He again vowed to work for more democracy, openness, and humanity, but without naivety.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/terrorangrepet-22-juli-politikk-og-samfunn/stoltenberg-paa-minnestund-vi-har-maktet-aa-staa-oppreist-i-en-kritisk-tid/a/10080701/ \n |title=Stoltenberg p\u00e5 minnestund: \u2013 Vi har maktet \u00e5 st\u00e5 oppreist i en kritisk tid \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg at memorial: \u2013 We have managed to stay upright in a critical time \n |last=Kleivan \n |first=Nikolai \n |date=24 July 2011 \n |newspaper=Verdens Gang \n |language=no \n |accessdate=25 July 2011 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328222457/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/terrorangrepet-22-juli-politikk-og-samfunn/stoltenberg-paa-minnestund-vi-har-maktet-aa-staa-oppreist-i-en-kritisk-tid/a/10080701/ \n |archivedate=28 March 2014 \n}}</ref> He also said that \"No one has said it better than the AUF girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can show so much hate, think how much love we could show, standing together.''\"<ref>{{cite news|date=24 July 2011 |accessdate=24 July 2011 |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/jul/24/norway-attacks-live-updates |title=orway attacks rolling coverage: Sunday 24 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828174305/http://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/jul/24/norway-attacks-live-updates |archivedate=28 August 2013 |url-status=live |quote=No one has said it better than the AUF girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can show so much hate, think how much love we could show, standing together.'' }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/smk/Whats-new/Speeches-and-articles/statsministeren/statsminister_jens_stoltenberg/2011/address-by-prime-minister-in-oslo-cathed.html |title=Address by Prime Minister in Oslo Cathedral |website=Government.no |date=24 July 2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011 |quote=No one has said it better than the Labour Youth League girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can create that much hate, you can only imagine how much love we as a togetherness can create.'' |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211093533/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/smk/Whats-new/Speeches-and-articles/statsministeren/statsminister_jens_stoltenberg/2011/address-by-prime-minister-in-oslo-cathed.html |archivedate=11 February 2012 }}</ref> The [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|AUF]] girl mentioned is [[Stine Renate H\u00e5heim]] interviewed by CNN's [[Richard Quest]] on 23 July 2011.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[CNN]] |url=http://edition.cnn.com/video/?/video/world/2011/07/23/bpr.haheim.norwegian.lawmaker.cnn |title=Norway Island survivor: CNN's Richard Quest talks to Stine Renate Haheim |accessdate=24 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121101600/http://edition.cnn.com/video/?%2Fvideo%2Fworld%2F2011%2F07%2F23%2Fbpr.haheim.norwegian.lawmaker.cnn |url-status=live |archivedate=21 January 2012 |quote=If one man can create that much hate, you can only imagine how much love we as a togetherness can create. }}</ref> H\u00e5heim again quoted her friend Helle Gannestad, who had tweeted this from home, watching events unfold on TV.<ref>{{cite web|website=Side2.no |accessdate=4 April 2014 |url=http://www.side2.no/3201858.html |title=Helle inspirerte verdensstjernen |trans-title=Helle inspired world star |archivedate=29 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329013517/http://www.side2.no/3201858.html |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2012, 33-year-old Norwegian [[Anders Behring Breivik]] was found [[Trial of Anders Behring Breivik|guilty]] by the [[Oslo District Court]] of having perpetrated by himself both [[terrorist attacks]], the bombing of the prime minister's office and the shooting spree on [[Ut\u00f8ya]] island, and was convicted to ''[[Life imprisonment in Norway|containment]]'', a special form of [[prison sentence]] that can be extended indefinitely\u2014with a time frame of 21 years and a minimum time of 10 years, which, in all, is the maximum penalty in Norway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-19365616 |title=Anders Behring Breivik: Norway court finds him sane |work=[[BBC News]] |date=24 August 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824083419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-19365616 |archivedate=24 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2012, Norwegian daily ''[[Klassekampen]]'' wrote that the [[Gj\u00f8rv Report]] on the terrorist attack \"is the hardest verdict against a Norwegian cabinet since the Fact-Finding Commission of 1945 ensured that [[Johan Nygaardsvold]]'s political career was abruptly halted.\"<ref>[http://klassekampen.no/60619/article/item/null/overivrig Overivrig] \"22. juli-kommisjonens rapport er den mest knusende dom en norsk regjering har f\u00e5tt siden Unders\u00f8kelseskommisjonen i 1945 s\u00f8rget for at Johan Nygaardsvolds politiske karriere fikk en br\u00e5 slutt.\"</ref> Stoltenberg said after the report was published that he had \"ultimate responsibility for the preparedness in our country, a responsibility I take seriously,\" but he said he would not resign.<ref>{{cite news\n |agency=CNN \n |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/13/world/europe/norway-massacre-report/ \n |title=Norway massacre could have been avoided, report finds \n |date=13 August 2012 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408012257/http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/13/world/europe/norway-massacre-report/ \n |archivedate= 8 April 2014 \n}}</ref>\n\n'''2013 election and defeat'''\n{{main|2013 Norwegian parliamentary election}}\nStoltenberg was the Prime Minister candidate for the Red-Green Coalition in the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 elections]], seeking re-election for a third term.\n\nOn 9 September 2013, the coalition failed to win majority, with 72 of the required 85 mandates, despite the Labour Party remaining the largest party in Norway with 30.8%.<ref>Accurate as of 23:20 local time on election night.</ref> In his speech the same night, he announced that his cabinet would resign in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vgtv.no/#!id=70029&index=39|title=VGTV|website=Vgtv.no|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> Stoltenberg returned to the Parliament where he became parliamentarian leader for the Labour Party and a member of the [[Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs and Defence]]. In December 2013, he was appointed by the United Nations as a [[Special Envoy on Climate Change]], alongside the former Ghanaian president [[John Kufuor]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Rolleiv |last=Solholm |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29362-stoltenberg-new-un-special-envoy |agency=[[NRK]] |accessdate=29 December 2013 |newspaper=The Norway Post |date=24 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225142525/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29362-stoltenberg-new-un-special-envoy |archivedate=25 December 2013 |url-status=live |title=Stoltenberg new UN special envoy }}</ref>\n\n====Policies as Prime Minister====\nStoltenberg has been described as a cautious politician, belonging to the right wing of [[social democracy]].<ref>Per \u00d8stby [http://www.transportarbeider.no/kunder/ntf/cms.nsf/%28$All%29/DF06C0C2FD22A5A1C12578A00037150B?OpenDocument Refser de r\u00f8dgr\u00f8nne] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917124653/http://www.transportarbeider.no/kunder/ntf/cms.nsf/%28$All%29/DF06C0C2FD22A5A1C12578A00037150B?OpenDocument |date=17 September 2016 }} {{in lang|no}} transportarbeider.no. 15 September 2010. Retrieved 31 March 2014</ref> In security policy, Stoltenberg favours increased military spending and dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2014 |language=no |url=http://www.dn.no/nyheter/2014/03/28/stoltenberg-vil-vre-bde-hauk-og-due |title=Stoltenberg vil v\u00e6re b\u00e5de hauk og due |trans-title=Stoltenberg Will be Both Hawk and Dove |publisher=[[Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv|DN.no]]; [[Norwegian Telegram Agency|NTB]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407052805/http://www.dn.no/nyheter/2014/03/28/stoltenberg-vil-vre-bde-hauk-og-due |archivedate= 7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n'''Defense and foreign politics'''\n[[File:JensandNato.jpg|thumb|[[Secretary General of NATO]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] and Stoltenberg, while visiting Oslo talk with members of [[Telemark Battalion]].]]\n[[File:Paris Summit for the Support to the Libyan People 04.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg at the Paris Summit of 19 March 2011 (back row, second from right), which marked the start of a [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]].]]\nWhile Stoltenberg was Prime Minister, Norway's defence spending increased steadily, with the result that Norway today is one of the NATO allies with the highest per capita defence expenditure.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29677-stoltenberg-appointed-new-nato-chief \n |title=Stoltenberg appointed new NATO Chief \n |newspaper=The Norway Post \n |accessdate=11 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140411231628/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29677-stoltenberg-appointed-new-nato-chief \n |archivedate=11 April 2014 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg has also been instrumental in modernising the Norwegian armed forces, and in contributing forces to various NATO operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tnp.no/norway/politics/4421-nato-appoints-jens-stoltenberg-as-nato-sg-as-of-october-1st-2014-norway |title=NATO Appoints Jens Stoltenberg as NATO SG as of October 1st 2014 |work=The Nordic Page |accessdate=11 April 2014 |place=[[Oslo]] |date=23 March 2014 |language=no |archivedate=11 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140411233130/http://www.tnp.no/norway/politics/4421-nato-appoints-jens-stoltenberg-as-nato-sg-as-of-october-1st-2014-norway |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg is a supporter of enhanced trans-Atlantic cooperation ties. He has also always been a supporter of Norwegian membership in the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Henrik Width |language=no |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-harselerte-med-EOS-avtalen-6301963.html |title=Stoltenberg harselerte med E\u00d8S-avtalen |trans-title=Stoltenberg mocked the EEA Agreement |newspaper=Aftenposten |date=19 October 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004619/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-harselerte-med-EOS-avtalen-6301963.html |archivedate=30 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg has criticized [[Israel]] over [[alleged]] violations of international law in the Palestinian Territories as well as in international waters, such as the [[Gaza flotilla raid]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/utenriks/stoltenberg-uakseptabelt-av-israel-3218802.html \n |author=Lars Barth-Heyerdahl \n |title=Stoltenberg: \u2013 Uakseptabelt av Israel: Den norske regjeringen ford\u00f8mmer bordingen av skip med n\u00f8dhjelp p\u00e5 vei til Gaza \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg: \u2013 Unacceptable of Israel: The Norwegian government condemns board of the ship with the aid headed to Gaza \n |publisher=TV2 \n |language=no \n |date=31 May 2010 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407060307/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/utenriks/stoltenberg-uakseptabelt-av-israel-3218802.html \n |archivedate= 7 April 2014 \n}}</ref> In 2006, Stoltenberg stated that \"Norway condemns Israel's actions against Palestinians. Such collective punishment is totally unacceptable.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |newspaper   = Aftenbladet\n |language    = no\n |date        = 14 July 2006\n |url         = http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/utenriks/article312125.ece\n |title       = Stoltenberg ford\u00f8mmer Israel\n |trans-title = Stoltenberg condemns Israel\n |url-status     = dead\n |archivedate = 7 April 2014\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070254/http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/utenriks/article312125.ece\n}}</ref> Stoltenberg praised doctors [[Mads Gilbert]] and [[Erik Fosse]] for their humanitarian work in the Gaza Strip during the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]], stating that \"all of Norway\" was behind them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtoesten/stoltenberg-hyller-norske-gaza-leger/a/550179/ |title=Stoltenberg hyller norske Gaza-leger |trans-title=Stoltenberg shelves Norwegian Gaza doctors |newspaper=Verdens Gang |date=1 November 2009 |archivedate= 7 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407061215/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtoesten/stoltenberg-hyller-norske-gaza-leger/a/550179/ |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref>\n\n'''Financial crisis'''\n\nStoltenberg took an international role during the financial crisis by promoting international financial cooperation. This was among other arenas done through the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) and a meeting in Chile 27\u201329 March 2009 where social democratic leaders from around the world met at a Progressive Governance Conference, just prior to the first G20 summit on the financial crisis. President [[Bill Clinton]] was among the delegates and panel that would chart a way out of the financial crisis, which included the host [[Michelle Bachelet]], Britain's finance minister [[Gordon Brown]], Brazil's President [[Lula da Silva]] and Stoltenberg. A special emergency meeting of the European Social Democratic Forum (PES) was gathered in Oslo in May 2011, on an initiative from Stoltenberg and the think tank Policy Network.\n\nBoth nationally and internationally, Stoltenberg emphasised the enormous costs the financial crisis had in the form of a high unemployment rate, and appealed for better international coordination, the balance between austerity and economic growth stimulus, active labor market measures for young people, and investments for increased innovation.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Norway came out of the financial crisis with the lowest unemployment rate in Europe.<ref name=Db>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/05/01/nyheter/innenriks/arbeidsledighet/jens_stoltenberg/1_mai/11529483/ |language=no |title=Norge har lavest arbeids-ledighet i Europa |trans-title=Norway has the lowest unemployment in Europe |work=Dagbladet |date=1 May 2010 |archivedate= 4 May 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504043235/http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/05/01/nyheter/innenriks/arbeidsledighet/jens_stoltenberg/1_mai/11529483/ }}</ref>\n\n'''Environment and climate change'''\n\nPartnering with tropical countries to preserve more of their rainforest to bind carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) in order to reduce [[greenhouse gas emissions]] was a policy of the Stoltenberg government. In 2007, the government received support from the opposition to a long-term agreement to finance forest conservation with 3 billion NOK annually.<ref name=NRK>{{cite news\n |publisher=NRK \n |language=no \n |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/gir-tre-milliarder-til-regnskogen-1.4252368 \n |title=Gir tre milliarder til regnskogen \n |date=12 September 2012 \n |archivedate=13 March 2014 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001201/http://www.nrk.no/norge/gir-tre-milliarder-til-regnskogen-1.4252368 \n}}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg through his governing advocated that international agreements with global taxes or quotas are the most effective means of reducing greenhouse gas emissions. At the [[UN Climate Change Conference 2009]], a separate proposal on the preservation of rainforests with funding from rich countries, advanced by Stoltenberg and Brazilian [[President of Brazil|Pres]]. [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] in 2009 obtained support from among others U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] during COP15 in Copenhagen.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nThe summit in Copenhagen ended without a binding agreement, but before the subsequent COP16 in [[Canc\u00fan]], Stoltenberg succeeded then-British Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] in the leadership of the committee dealing with the financing of climate actions in developing countries, also consisting of Ethiopian [[Prime Minister of Ethiopia|Prime Minister]] [[Meles Zenawi]]. Under a separate forest and climate conference in Oslo in May 2010, a proposal was presented to a number of countries, with final delivery of the report in autumn 2010.\n\nIn January 2014 Jens Stoltenberg became [[United Nations Special Envoy on Climate Change]]. During the meeting there he met with Secretary General [[Ban Ki-Moon]] as well as [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change|UN Framework Convention]] director [[Christiana Figueres]] and both [[Achim Steiner]] and [[Helen Clark]] of the [[United Nations Development Programme]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.norway-un.org/News/News-2013/Jens-Stoltenberg-becomes-UN-special-envoy-on-Climate-Change/#.U0lN5iwo5lY \n |title=Jens Stoltenberg becomes UN special envoy on Climate Change \n |accessdate=12 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412144608/http://www.norway-un.org/News/News-2013/Jens-Stoltenberg-becomes-UN-special-envoy-on-Climate-Change/#.U0lN5iwo5lY \n |archivedate=12 April 2014 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\n'''Vaccines'''\n\nStoltenberg has been an advocate for having all the world's children vaccinated against infectious diseases. The first speech he gave in his second term as Prime Minister was during Norway's \"Pharmaceutics days\" in 2005 under the title \"Vaccination against poverty\". Stoltenberg was director of the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization ([[GAVI]]) from 2002 to 2005 and was awarded the Children's Health Award in 2005.\n\nAn international initiative, with the UK, the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|Gates Foundation]] and Norway in the lead, that GAVI received more than $3.7 billion until 2015 for their work against child mortality.<ref>{{cite news\n |date=16 May 2005 \n |url=http://www.tnp.no/norway/health/2276-bill-gates-meets-jens-stoltenberg \n |title=Bill Gates Meets Jens Stoltenberg \n |newspaper=The Nordic Page \n |accessdate=12 April 2014 \n |archivedate=13 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145857/http://www.tnp.no/norway/health/2276-bill-gates-meets-jens-stoltenberg \n |url-status=live \n |language=no \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg was one of the key driving forces behind the initiative, and has stressed that this is an important contribution to save 9 million children from dying of the most common childhood illnesses.\n\nIn his New Year speech on 1 January 2013, Stoltenberg spoke about vaccination of the world's children as a personal matter of the heart. \"Small jabs are giving millions of children the gift of life. Simple medicines can save their mothers. The fact that all these mothers' and children's lives can be saved is \u2013 as I see it \u2013 a miracle of our time,\" Stoltenberg said in his speech.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 January 2013 |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/archive/Stoltenbergs-2nd-Government/Office-of-the-Prime-Minister/taler-og-artikler/2013/prime-minister-jens-stoltenbergs-new-yea.html?id=710868 |title=Stoltenbergs New Year speech |language=no |accessdate=12 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001014/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/archive/Stoltenbergs-2nd-Government/Office-of-the-Prime-Minister/taler-og-artikler/2013/prime-minister-jens-stoltenbergs-new-yea.html?id=710868 }}</ref>\n\n=== United Nations (2013\u20132014) ===\nIn 2011, Stoltenberg received the United Nations (UN) Champion of Global Change Award in New York City, chosen for his extraordinary effort toward meeting the Millennium Development Goals and bringing fresh ideas to global problems. In 2013, Stoltenberg served as a UN special envoy on [[climate change]] ([[global warming]]), and he has chaired the UN High-Level Panel on System Wide Coherence and the High-Level Advisory Group on Climate Change Financing.\n\n=== NATO Secretary General (2014\u2013present) ===\n{{See also|NATO\u2013Russia relations}}\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Listens to NATO Secretary-General Stoltenberg Speak Before Members Signed an Accession Protocol to Continue Montenegro's Admission to the Alliance in Brussels (26839433820).jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg and [[Montenegro]]'s Prime Minister [[Milo Djukanovic]] attend a NATO foreign ministers meeting on 19 May 2016]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Chats with NATO Secretary General Stoltenberg and his UK and Turkish Counterparts During the NATO Ministerial in Brussels (41029400304).jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo|Pompeo]], UK Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]] and Turkish Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu|\u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]], Brussels, April 2018]]\n[[File:TrumpNato18.jpg|thumb|A meeting of NATO heads of States and governments on 11 July 2018 in Brussels]]\nOn 28 March 2014 [[NATO]]'s [[North Atlantic Council]] appointed Stoltenberg as designated successor of [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] as the 13th [[Secretary General of NATO]] and Chairman of the council, effective from 1 October 2014.<ref name=natojens>{{cite web|date=28 March 2014 |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_108390.htm |title=Appointment of Secretary General designate |publisher=[[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] |accessdate=28 March 2014 |df= }}</ref> The appointment had been widely expected in the media for some time, and commentators pointed out that the alliance's policies toward Russia will be the most important issue faced by Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/29/world/europe/nato-picks-former-norwegian-premier-as-its-next-leader.html?_r=1 |author=James Kanter |title=Norwegian to Lead NATO as It Is Poised for Bigger Role |date=28 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408210305/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/29/world/europe/nato-picks-former-norwegian-premier-as-its-next-leader.html?_r=1 |archivedate= 8 April 2014 |url-status=live |url-access=registration  }}</ref> [[Angela Merkel]], the Chancellor of Germany, took the initiative to appoint Stoltenberg as Secretary-General, securing the support first of the United States, then of the United Kingdom, and then of all other member states.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Jens-Stoltenberg-skal-ha-lovet-a-lare-seg-fransk-7520428.html |title=Stoltenberg skal l\u00e6re seg fransk |trans-title=Stoltenberg will learn French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329220350/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Jens-Stoltenberg-skal-ha-lovet-a-lare-seg-fransk-7520428.html |archivedate=29 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=no |newspaper=Aftenposten }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=29 March 2014 |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/merkel-ringte-stoltenberg-i-host-1.11637880 |title=Stoltenberg letter p\u00e5 sl\u00f8ret: Merkel ringte meg om NATO-jobben i oktober |trans-title=Stoltenberg got a hint: Merkel called me about NATO job in October |publisher=NRK |accessdate=31 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330051613/http://www.nrk.no/norge/merkel-ringte-stoltenberg-i-host-1.11637880 |language=no |url-status=live }}</ref> Norway was a founding member of NATO in 1949, and Stoltenberg is the first Norwegian to serve as Secretary-General, although former [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]] Prime Minister [[K\u00e5re Willoch]] was considered a strong candidate in 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Toppene-avgjor-Stoltenbergs-Nato-fremtid-7508976.html |title=Toppene avgj\u00f8r Stoltenbergs Nato-fremtid |author1=Lars Molteberg Glomnes |author2=Ole Mathismoen |newspaper=Aftenposten |author3=Robert Gjerde |date=19 March 2014 |archivedate=19 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319232145/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Toppene-avgjor-Stoltenbergs-Nato-fremtid-7508976.html |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Stoltenberg said: \"I believe we don't see any immediate threat against any NATO country from the east. Our goal is still cooperation with [[Russia]] \u2026 That serves NATO and it serves Russia.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoltenberg: Russia Doesn't Pose Immediate Threat to NATO States |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2015/06/04/stoltenberg-russia-doesnt-pose-immediate-threat-to-nato-states-a47125 |work=The Moscow Times |date=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, [[Czech Republic|Czech]] Deputy Prime Minister Andrej Babi\u0161 criticized NATO's lack of response to the [[European migrant crisis]]. After talks with Stoltenberg on migrant crisis issue Babi\u0161 said: \"NATO is not interested in refugees, though Turkey, a NATO member, is their entrance gate to Europe and smugglers operate on Turkish territory\".<ref name=\"CN\">\"[http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czech-minister-babis-criticises-nato-s-stance-on-refugees/1256815 Czech minister Babis criticises NATO\u00b4s stance on refugees]\". CeskeNoviny.cz. 10 September 2015.</ref>\n\nStoltenberg strongly condemned the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] and expressed full support for [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]'s government.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/turkey-security-nato-idUSL1N1A61L6 NATO chief says Turkey's military still strong despite detentions]\". Reuters. 20 July 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_134408.htm|title=NATO Spokesperson's statement on Turkey|last=NATO|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> He did not condemn the [[2016\u2013present purges in Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO declines to condemn arrests of Turkish legislators, journalists |url=https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/nato-declines-condemn-arrests-turkish-legislators-161121-99-255828 |work=[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]] |date=21 November 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Stoltenberg admitted that some \"Turkish officers working in NATO command structures... have requested asylum in the countries where they are working.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=More academics, mayors detained as Turkish purges enter fifth month |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security/more-academics-mayors-detained-as-turkish-purges-enter-fifth-month-idUSKBN13D0IU |agency=Reuters |date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Stoltenberg stated that the NATO strongly supported \"the UN-led political process to find a solution\" to the [[Cyprus dispute|dispute]] over the northern part of [[Cyprus]], which has been under illegal occupation since the [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|Turkish invasion of 1974]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jens Stoltenberg: NATO responds to \"Russia's aggression against Ukraine\" |url=https://tass.com/world/883050 |work=TASS |date=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Stoltenberg warned that Russia has used big military exercises, including [[Zapad 2017 exercise]] in Russia's [[Kaliningrad Oblast]] and [[Belarus]], \"as a disguise or a precursor for aggressive military actions against their neighbours.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia was the target of Nato's own fake news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/russia-zapad-2017-putin-west-fake-news-us-world-war-three-ukraine-belarus-nato-a7961856.html |work=The Independent |date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, in response to the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin|Turkish invasion of northern Syria]] aimed at ousting U.S.-backed [[People's Protection Units|Syrian Kurds]] from the enclave of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]], Stoltenberg said that Turkey is \"the NATO Ally which has suffered most from terrorist attacks over many years and Turkey, as all of the countries, have the right to self defence, but it is important that this is done in a proportionate and measured way.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nato.int/cps/ic/natohq/opinions_151089.htm?selectedLocale=en | title=Joint press conference with NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg and the Minister of Defence of Spain, Mar\u00eda Dolores de Cospedal Garc\u00eda | website=NATO.int | date=25 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Stoltenberg stated: \"We don\u2019t see any threat [from Russia] against any NATO ally and therefore, I\u2019m always careful speculating too much about hypothetical situations.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO sees no Russian threat to any of its members \u2014 head |url=https://tass.com/world/990990 |work=TASS |date=21 February 2018}}</ref> Stoltenberg welcomed the [[2018 Russia\u2013United States summit]] between Vladimir Putin and Donald Trump in Helsinki, Finland.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: Gorbachev has high hopes for Putin-Trump summit |url=https://apnews.com/a8cad273fde84304a2aa31c6cd5cf7a6 |work=AP News |date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> He said NATO is not trying to isolate Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief warns against isolating Russia |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/07/11/nato-chief-warns-against-isolating-russia |work=Euronews |date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Stoltenberg stated that the former [[Republics of the Soviet Union|Soviet republic]] of \"Georgia will become a member of NATO\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgia \u2018will join NATO\u2019: Stoltenberg |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/georgia-will-join-nato-stoltenberg-142174 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Stoltenberg warned a joint session of the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] of threat posed by Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief warns of Russia threat, urges unity in U.S. address |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-nato/nato-chief-warns-of-russia-threat-urges-unity-in-u-s-address-idUSKCN1RF22L |work=Reuters |date=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief calls for confronting Russia in speech to Congress |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/03/nato-secretary-general-russia-congress-1252838 |work=Politico |date=3 April 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, Stoltenberg hailed [[Turkey]]'s contribution to NATO. He said: \"Turkey joined the Alliance in 1952, and it continues to be a highly valued member of our family of nations. As secretary-general, I greatly appreciate all that Turkey does for our Alliance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO is committed to the defense of Turkey: Stoltenberg |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/nato-is-committed-to-the-defense-of-turkey-stoltenberg-143167 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Stoltenberg warned that NATO needs to \"address the rise of [[China]],\" by closely cooperating with [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO needs to address China's rise, says Stoltenberg |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-australia-nato/nato-needs-to-address-chinas-rise-says-stoltenberg-idUSKCN1UX0YX |agency=Reuters |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg \"strongly condemned\" the [[2019 Abqaiq\u2013Khurais attack]] on key [[Saudi Arabia]]'s oil facilities and accused [[Iran]] of \"supporting different terrorist groups and being responsible for destabilising the whole region.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief 'extremely concerned' after attacks on Saudi |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190916-nato-chief-extremely-concerned-after-attacks-on-saudi |work=France 24 |date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkey invaded]] the [[Rojava|Kurdish areas in Syria]]. Stoltenberg said that Turkey has \"legitimate security concerns\" during press conference with Turkish FM [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's actions in Syria must be measured: NATO chief |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-nato/turkeys-actions-in-syria-must-be-measured-nato-chief-idUSKBN1WO1YO |agency=Reuters |date=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. military's [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]], which killed the high-level Iranian General [[Qasem Soleimani]], brought strong reactions from around the world. Stoltenberg said, following a meeting on 6{{nbsp}}January, \"all members of the Atlantic alliance stood behind the United States in the Middle East\" and that \"Iran must refrain from further violence and provocations.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-nato/us-briefs-nato-over-iran-strike-avoids-european-criticism-idUSKBN1Z51SI |title=U.S. briefs NATO over Iran strike, avoids European criticism |last=Emmott |first=Robin |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Incognito taxi driver in Norway===\nIn August 2013, Stoltenberg said on his Facebook page that he had spent an afternoon working ''[[Anonymity|incognito]]'' as a taxi driver in Oslo.<ref name=beeb>{{cite news|work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23655675 |title=Norway PM Jens Stoltenberg works as secret taxi driver |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811192438/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23655675 |archivedate=11 August 2013 |date=11 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Stoltenberg said he had wanted to \"hear from real Norwegian voters\" and that \"taxis were one of the few places where people shared their true views.\" He added that, before driving the taxi, he had not driven a car in eight years.<ref name=beeb/> The event was videotaped in a [[hidden camera]] fashion, and released as a promotional video by the Labour party for the election campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peters |first=Tim |title=Taxi-Jens lurte velgere med skjult kamera ** \u2013 Fikk en del kritikk for kj\u00f8ringen min |newspaper=VG |accessdate=23 March 2014 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/valg-2013/artikkel.php?artid=10119094 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225210/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/valg-2013/artikkel.php?artid=10119094 |archivedate=23 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref> It was later confirmed that 5 of the 14 customers were paid and recruited by the production company that produced the event for the Labour party.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davidson |first=Jacob |accessdate=23 March 2014 |url=http://world.time.com/2013/08/12/watch-norwegian-p-m-jens-stoltenberg-goes-incognito-as-a-cab-driver/ |title=Norwegian Prime Minister's Taxi Stunt Involved Paid Actors |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225635/http://world.time.com/2013/08/12/watch-norwegian-p-m-jens-stoltenberg-goes-incognito-as-a-cab-driver/ |archivedate=23 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Johansen |first=Nilas |title=Fikk betalt for tur med \"Taxi-Jens\" Brukte \"street casting\" for \u00e5 sikre passasjerer til statsministeren |trans-title=Got paid for the trip with \"Taxi Jens\" Used \"street casting\" to ensure passengers to the Prime Minister |accessdate=23 March 2014 |newspaper=VG |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=10119280 |date=12 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225254/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=10119280 |archivedate=23 March 2014 |language=no }}</ref> None, however, knew they would meet Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw.com/en/a-taxi-stunt-goes-awry-for-norways-prime-minister/av-17023271\n|title=Norwegian Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg Drives a Taxi |date=12 August 2013  |first1=Andreas |last1=Illmer  |publisher=Deutsche Welle, Germany |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsvaqF9KZXI |title=Norwegian Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg Drives a Taxi (Video) |date=12 August 2013\n|publisher=Deutsche Welle, Germany |website=YouTube.com|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n* Stoltenberg had regular contacts with a [[KGB]] agent disguised as a Soviet diplomat, and participated in protest rallies against the [[Vietnam War|U.S. war in Vietnam]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"local\">\"[https://www.thelocal.no/20150806/nato-boss-sung-anti-nato-songs-as-a-youth Nato boss sang anti-Nato songs as a youth]\". ''[[The Local]]''. 6 August 2015.</ref> In 2011, Stoltenberg said \"We sang the chorus, \u2018Singing Norway, Norway out of Nato'. It was a hit.\"<ref name=\"local\"/>  \n* In 2001, Stoltenberg crashed his Labour Party-owned car into a parked car; he then left the premises without leaving a note with his name or number; the damages cost 8000 [[Norwegian kroner]] to repair.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hultgreen, Gunnar |title=Jens varslet ikke eieren |trans-title=Jens did not notify the owner |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=8 December 2001 |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2001/12/08/299904.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011208102121/http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2001/12/08/299904.html |url-status=live |archivedate= 8 December 2001 |accessdate=5 November 2016 }}</ref>  \n* In 2002, Stoltenberg admitted to having used [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] in his youth.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kaasa, Kjell M. |title=Ja, jeg har pr\u00f8vd hasj! |trans-title=Yes, I have tried weed! |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=2 November 2002 |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2002/11/02/352834.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021102110239/http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2002/11/02/352834.html |archivedate= 2 November 2002 |url-status=live |accessdate=19 November 2010 }}</ref>  He therefore asked the [[Ministry of Justice and Public Security]] to evaluate his impartiality in the upcoming government response to the report on drugs by the Stoltenberg Commission, headed by his father, Thorvald Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vurderer statsministerens habilitet i narkotikapolitikken |trans-title=Considering the Prime Minister's impartiality in drug policy |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10010872 |work=[[Verdens Gang|VG]] |date=10 November 2010 |accessdate=19 November 2010 |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency|NTB]] |language=no |archivedate=13 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113023454/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10010872 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* In 2011, Stoltenberg received a prize from the [[UN Foundation]] for excellent global leadership and Norway's support of the [[UN]]. Earlier the same year, Stoltenberg had allocated 150 million [[Norwegian kroner]] of the foreign aid budget to the same foundation, which led to criticism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gedde-Dahl, Siri |title=Stoltenberg delte ut penger - fikk pris i retur |trans-title=Stoltenberg handed out money - got prize in return |work=[[Aftenposten]] |language=no |date=25 November 2011 |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Stoltenberg-delte-ut-penger-A--fikk-pris-i-retur-6706022.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125232422/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Stoltenberg-delte-ut-penger-A--fikk-pris-i-retur-6706022.html |url-status=live |archivedate=25 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref> Also in 2011 Stoltenberg got a 380,000 [[Norwegian kroner|kroner]] boat as a birthday gift from the [[Norwegian Labour Party]] and the [[Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions]]; the givers also paid the tax for the gift which led to criticism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Thomas Ege, Rune |title=Stoltenberg fikk b\u00e5t til 380.000 |trans-title=Stoltenberg got boat to 380.000 |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=22 July 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/stoltenberg-regjeringen/stoltenberg-fikk-baat-til-380-000/a/10080554/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126002555/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/stoltenberg-regjeringen/stoltenberg-fikk-baat-til-380-000/a/10080554/ |url-status=live |archivedate=26 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Johanson, Marianne |title=Ap betalte skatt for b\u00e5tgaven til Jens |trans-title=AP paid tax for the boat gift |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=22 October 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/arbeiderpartiet/ap-betalte-skatt-for-baatgaven-til-jens/a/10022907/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501113206/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/arbeiderpartiet/ap-betalte-skatt-for-baatgaven-til-jens/a/10022907 |url-status=live |archivedate= 1 May 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref>\nAdditions to N.A.T.O. due reasons of reality are bound to referendum not only by military personel of the other nations within N.A.T.O. but also by and through national referendum. (Social, Cultural, Regional, Linguistical). Europe has had a none draft protocole since the 90's. None of these precepts are being observed and defacto obviated, making reasons for entry of eastern european nations suspect. (R.I.C.O. actors).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Jens Stoltenberg}}\n\n===News links===\n* [http://search.time.com/?q=jens+stoltenberg&site=time ''Time'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/search/?q=jens%20stoltenberg#52a94d3d279f ''Forbes'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [http://www.newsweek.com/topic/jens-stoltenberg ''Newsweek'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.newyorker.com/search?q=jens+stoltenberg ''The New Yorker'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/s/jens_stoltenberg/index.html ''The New York Times'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.wsj.com/search/term.html?KEYWORDS=jens%20stoltenberg ''The Wall Street Journal'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.ft.com/search?q=jens+stoltenberg ''Financial Times'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Egil Knudsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]]|years=1985\u20131989}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Turid Birkeland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]|years=2002\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Finn Kristensen]]|as=Minister of Industry}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry and Energy]]|years=1993\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Grete Knudsen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]|years=1996\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gudmund Restad]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]]|years=2000\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]]|years=2005\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Erna Solberg]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary General of NATO]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NATOSecGens}}\n{{Current NATO leaders}}\n{{Norwegian Labour Party}}\n{{Stoltenberg cabinet}}\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{NorwegianFinancialMinisters}}\n{{Stortinget 2001-2005}}\n{{Stortinget 2009-2013}}\n{{Stortinget 2013-2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoltenberg, Jens}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (Norway)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Finance of Norway]]\n[[Category:Norwegian agnostics]]\n[[Category:Norwegian economists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oslo Cathedral School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oslo Waldorf School]]\n[[Category:People from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Secretaries General of NATO]]\n[[Category:Stoltenberg family|Jens]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Norwegian politician, 13th Secretary-General of NATO, 27th Prime Minister of Norway}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Jens Stoltenberg\n|image          = NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg.jpg\n|office         = 13th [[Secretary General of NATO]]\n|term_start     = 1 October 2014\n|term_end       = \n|deputy         = [[Alexander Vershbow]]<br />[[Rose Gottemoeller]]<br />[[Mircea Geoan\u0103]]\n|predecessor    = [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]\n|successor      = \n|office1        = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n|monarch1       = [[Harald V of Norway|Harald V]]\n|term_start1    = 17 October 2005\n|term_end1      = 16 October 2013\n|predecessor1   = [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]\n|successor1     = [[Erna Solberg]]\n|monarch2       = Harald V\n|term_start2    = 17 March 2000\n|term_end2      = 19 October 2001\n|predecessor2   = [[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]\n|successor2     = Kjell Magne Bondevik\n|office3= Leader of the Opposition \n|term_start3= 16 October 2013\n|term_end3= 14 June 2014\n|primeminister3= Erna Solberg \n|predecessor3= [[Erna Solberg]]\n|successor3= [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]] \n|term_start4= 19 October 2001\n|term_end4= 17 October 2005 \n|primeminister4= Kjell Magne Bondevik \n|predecessor4= \n|successor4= Erna Solberg \n|office5        = Leader of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]\n|term_start5    = 6 April 2002\n|term_end5      = 14 June 2014\n|predecessor5   = [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]\n|successor5     = [[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]]\n|office6        = [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister6= [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]\n|term_start6    = 25 October 1996\n|term_end6      = 17 October 1997\n|predecessor6   = [[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]\n|successor6     = [[Gudmund Restad]]\n|office7        = [[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry and Energy]]\n|primeminister7 = [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]]\n|term_start7    = 7 October 1993\n|term_end7      = 25 October 1996\n|predecessor7   = [[Finn Kristensen]] {{small|(Industry)}}\n|successor7     = [[Grete Faremo]] {{small|(Petroleum & Energy)}}\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1959|03|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n|party          = [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour]]\n|spouse         = [[Ingrid Schulerud]] (1987&ndash;present)\n|children       = 2\n|parents        = [[Karin Stoltenberg|Karin Heiberg]]<br />[[Thorvald Stoltenberg]]\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Oslo]]\n|signature      = Jens Stoltenberg signature.svg\n|website        = {{url|nb-no.facebook.com/jensstoltenberg|Official Facebook}}<br />{{url|twitter.com/jensstoltenberg|Official Twitter}}\n}}\n\n'''Jens Stoltenberg''' (born 16 March 1959) is a Norwegian politician who has been serving as the [[List of NATO Secretaries General|13th]] [[Secretary General of NATO]] since 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/who_is_who_49999.htm\n|title=NATO Biography for Jens Stoltenberg, Secretary General |date=18 May 2017 |publisher=NATO Publications |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Stoltenberg-Jens.html |title=World Biography for Jens Stoltenberg of Norway\n|date=20 May 2017 |publisher=Encyclopedia of World Biography |website=NotableBiographies.com |accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO Names Stoltenberg Next Chief |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26791044 |publisher=BBC, UK |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref> A member of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]], he was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 2000 to 2001 and from 2005 to 2013.\n\nIn 2011, Stoltenberg received the [[United Nations Foundation]]'s Champion of Global Change Award, chosen for his extraordinary effort toward meeting the [[Millennium Development Goals]] and bringing fresh ideas to global problems.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lbkPIsdwv_Q |title=Jens Stoltenberg: 2011 UN Foundation Global Leadership Awards Dinner |date=10 November 2011 |publisher=United Nations Foundation, New York City, USA |website=YouTube.com |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe mission of Jens Stoltenberg as secretary general of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was extended for another two years. Stoltenberg has been responsible for the past five years and is set to lead NATO until 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/nato-allies-extend-stoltenbergs-term-as-secretary-general/|title=NATO allies extend Stoltenberg\u2019s term as secretary-general|first=David M.|last=Herszenhorn|date=28 March 2019|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Early life===\nStoltenberg was born 16 March 1959 in [[Oslo]], Norway, into the [[Stoltenberg (Norwegian family)|Stoltenberg family]]. His father, [[Thorvald Stoltenberg]] (1931\u20132018), was a prominent Labour party politician who served as an ambassador, as defence minister and as foreign minister. His mother, [[Karin Stoltenberg]] (n\u00e9e Heiberg; 1931\u20132012), was a geneticist who served as [[state secretary]] in multiple governments during the 1980s.<ref name=a>{{cite news|last=Kolstad |first=Tom |title=Stoltenberg-familien i \u00e5penhjertig interview |trans-title=Stoltenberg family is having candid interview |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-familien-i-apenhjertig-intervju-6666837.html |newspaper=Aftenposten.no |date=17 October 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022120324/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-familien-i-apenhjertig-intervju-6666837.html |url-status=live |archivedate=22 October 2012 |language=no }}</ref> [[Marianne Heiberg]], married to former Foreign Minister [[Johan J\u00f8rgen Holst]], was his maternal aunt. Jens lived in [[SFR Yugoslavia]] from 1961 to 1964 while his father worked at the Norwegian embassy.<ref>{{cite web|author=V. N. |accessdate=4 April 2014 |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.289.html:379509-Stoltenberg-Beograd-ostao-u-srcu |title=Stoltenberg: Beograd ostao u srcu |trans-title=Stoltenberg: Belgrade remained in my heart |website=Novosti.rs |date=12 May 2012 |archivedate=22 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022120324/http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/naslovna/aktuelno.289.html%3A379509-Stoltenberg-Beograd-ostao-u-srcu }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vg.no/i/m69OVv|title=Jens Stoltenberg om barneskoletiden: - Jeg kunne ikke lese eller skrive|website=www.vg.no}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nStoltenberg attended primary school at [[Oslo Waldorf School]], and upper secondary school at [[Oslo katedralskole|Oslo Cathedral School]]. He served his mandatory military service with the Army's Infantry Training Centre at [[Evjemoen]] in [[Aust-Agder]].\n\nAfter leaving the army, Stoltenberg enrolled at the [[University of Oslo]], graduating in 1987 with the [[cand.oecon.]] degree in economics. The title of his thesis was ''Makro\u00f8konomisk planlegging under usikkerhet. En empirisk analyse'' (\"Macroeconomic planning under uncertainty. An empirical analysis\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ssb.no/histstat/in/in_8516.pdf |last=Stoltenberg |first=Jens |title=Makro\u00f8konomisk planlegging under usikkerhet. En empirisk analyse |trans-title=Macroeconomic planning is uncertain; an empirical analysis |website=Ssb.no |accessdate=17 January 2013 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116071758/http://www.ssb.no/histstat/in/in_8516.pdf |archivedate=16 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Early political activity===\nStoltenberg's first steps into politics came in his early teens, when he was influenced by his sister [[Camilla Stoltenberg|Camilla]], who at the time was a member of the then [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] group [[Red Youth (Norway)|Red Youth]]. Opposition to the [[Vietnam War]] was his triggering motivation. Following heavy [[List of bombing campaigns of the Vietnam War|bombing raids]] against the North Vietnamese port city of [[Hai Phong]] at the end of the Vietnam War, he participated in [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|protest rallies]] targeting the [[Embassy of the United States in Oslo|United States Embassy in Oslo]]. On at least one occasion embassy windows were broken by stone-throwing protesters. Several of Stoltenberg's friends were arrested by the police after these events.<ref>{{cite book|author=Salvesen, Geir|title=Thorvalds verden|trans-title=Thorvald's world|year=1994|publisher=[[Schibsted]]|location=Oslo, Norway|pages=398\u2013399|isbn=82-516-1545-3}}</ref>\n\n===Family life===\nStoltenberg is married to diplomat [[Ingrid Schulerud]] and they have two children: a son, Axel Stoltenberg (born 1989) who is studying Chinese at the [[Shanghai Jiaotong University]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Stoltenberg til Kina |trans-title=Stoltenberg to China |newspaper=Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv |url=http://www.dn.no/talent/article2462660.ece |accessdate=17 January 2013 |date=3 September 2012 |language=no |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928032825/http://www.dn.no/talent/article2462660.ece |archivedate=28 September 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Axel Stoltenberg, styremedlem |url=http://www.ansa.no/ANSAland/Kina/Lokallag/ANSA-Shanghai/Styret-i-ANSA-Shanghai/Solveig-Hunstad-Evensen/ |website=Ansa.no |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archivedate=27 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927215514/http://www.ansa.no/ANSAland/Kina/Lokallag/ANSA-Shanghai/Styret-i-ANSA-Shanghai/Solveig-Hunstad-Evensen/ }}</ref> and daughter Anne Catharina Stoltenberg (born 1992) who is a part of Smerz, a pop music duo signed to [[XL Recordings]].<ref name=a/><ref>{{cite news|author=Helljesen, Vilde |title=\"Hopalong Cassidy\" fyller 50 \u00e5r |trans-title=\"Hopalong Cassidy\" turns 50 years |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6522229 |publisher=[[Norwegian Broadcasting Corporation|NRK]] |location=Oslo, Norway |date=14 March 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2009 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518043207/http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.6522229 |archivedate=18 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/5391896|title=Smerz (2)|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\nHe has one living sister, [[Camilla Stoltenberg|Camilla]], a medical researcher and administrator who is one year older than him; and one late sister, [[Nini Stoltenberg|Nini]], four years younger, who died in 2014. Nini was a recovering heroin [[drug addiction|addict]], and the Norwegian media have covered the family's efforts to cope with this challenge.<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Hvem i helvete i regjeringen er det som har bestemt det? \n |trans-title=Who the hell is the government that has decided it? \n |work=Dagbladet \n |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2008/04/07/531582.html \n |date=9 April 2008 \n |language=no \n |accessdate=25 October 2009 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409234133/http://www.dagbladet.no/magasinet/2008/04/07/531582.html \n |archivedate= 9 April 2008 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\nHe prefers to spend his summer vacations at his family's cottage on the idyllic [[Hvaler|Hvaler Islands]] in the [[Oslofjord]].<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Tinlund \n |first=Tore \n |title=Her er Stoltenbergs ferieparadis \n |trans-title=Here is Stoltenberg's vacation paradise \n |url=http://www.f-b.no/nyheter/her-er-stoltenbergs-ferieparadis-1.1830547 \n |date=31 August 2009 \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |language=no \n |newspaper=Fredrikstads blad \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620153558/http://www.f-b.no/nyheter/her-er-stoltenbergs-ferieparadis-1.1830547 \n |archivedate=20 June 2013 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> An avid outdoorsman, he rides his bike often and during the winter season he is an active cross-country skier.<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Hellen \n |first=Bj\u00f8rnar \n |language=no \n |title=Stoltenberg tester VM-l\u00f8ypene \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg tested World Cup trails \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |publisher=NRK \n |url=http://www.nrk.no/sport/stoltenberg-testet-vm-loypene-1.7505838 \n |date=13 February 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928044328/http://www.nrk.no/sport/stoltenberg-testet-vm-loypene-1.7505838 \n |archivedate=28 September 2013 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> In December 2011, in order to mark 100 years since [[Roald Amundsen]] reached the south pole on skis, Stoltenberg journeyed to [[Antarctica]].<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Kristiansen \n |first=Bj\u00f8rn \n |title=Stoltenberg p\u00e5 S\u00f8rpolen \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg at the South Pole \n |language=no \n |date=13 December 2011 \n |accessdate=17 January 2012 \n |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/12/12/nyheter/innenriks/jens_stoltenberg/sorpolen/roald_amundsen/19382520/ \n |newspaper=Dagbladet \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109080304/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/12/12/nyheter/innenriks/jens_stoltenberg/sorpolen/roald_amundsen/19382520/ \n |archivedate= 9 January 2012 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nAlthough being portrayed as a staunch [[Atheism|atheist]] for most of his adult life, and declining membership in the formerly official [[Church of Norway]],<ref>{{cite news\n |last=Mel\u00e5 \n |first=Veronica \n |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=9086377 \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |newspaper=VG \n |title=Statsministeren m\u00e5 v\u00e6re kristen \n |language=no \n |date=14 July 2000 \n |archivedate=10 June 2011 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610153154/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=9086377 \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg has stated that he does not consider himself an atheist. He explained: \"Although I am not a member of any denomination, I do believe that there is something greater than man. Some call it God, others call it something else. For me, it's about understanding that we humans are small in relation to nature, in relation to the powers that are bigger and stronger than man can ever comprehend. I find that in a church.\"<ref name=b>{{cite news \n |title=Man m\u00e5 tro at det nytter \n |trans-title=One must believe that it is possible \n |url=http://www.bt.no/nyheter/--Man-ma-tro-at-det-nytter-2633333.html \n |author1=Erik Fossen \n |author2=H\u00e5vard Bjelland \n |accessdate=17 January 2013 \n |date=31 December 2011 \n |newspaper=Bt.no \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927204323/http://www.bt.no/nyheter/--Man-ma-tro-at-det-nytter-2633333.html \n |archivedate=27 September 2013 \n |language=no \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early career (1979\u20131990) ===\nFrom 1979 to 1981, Stoltenberg was a journalist for ''[[Arbeiderbladet]]''. From 1985 to 1989, he was the leader of the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]]. From 1989 to 1990, he worked as an Executive Officer for [[Statistics Norway]], Norway's central institution for producing official statistics. He also worked part-time as an hourly paid instructor at the University of Oslo during this period. Between 1990 and 1992, he was leader of the [[Oslo]] chapter of the Labour Party.<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/>\n\nUp to 1990, he had regular contacts with a Soviet diplomat. He ended this relationship after being informed by the [[Norwegian Police Security Service]] his contact was a [[KGB]] agent, warning him of further contact. Stoltenberg's code name within the KGB was \"Steklov\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Kodenavn \"Steklov\" |trans-title=Code Name \"Steklov\" |accessdate=3 November 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=5916647 |work=[[Verdens Gang|VG]] |date=24 October 2000 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018061834/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=5916647 |archivedate=18 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/amagasinet/article1187770.ece |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |language=no |accessdate=3 November 2011 |author=Kjetil S. |date=19 October 2011 |title=J\u00f8ss, herr Statsminister |trans-title=Gee, Mr. Prime Minister |archivedate=21 October 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021093145/http://www.aftenposten.no/amagasinet/article1187770.ece |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alf R. Jacobsen |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/07/06/kultur/debatt/kronikk/spionasje/arbeiderpartiet/17206163/ |title=Stortinget m\u00e5 granske |trans-title=Parliament must scrutinize |accessdate=27 March 2014 |date=6 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327234518/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/07/06/kultur/debatt/kronikk/spionasje/arbeiderpartiet/17206163/ |url-status=live |archivedate=27 March 2014 |language=no }}</ref>\n\n===Political career in Norway===\n\n==== Ministry for Environment and Minister for Trade and Energy (1990\u20131996) ====\n{{Main|Brundtland's Third Cabinet}}\nStoltenberg served as [[State Secretary (Norway)|State Secretary]] in the [[Norwegian Ministry of the Environment|Ministry of the Environment]] from 1990 to 1991. He was first elected to [[Parliament of Norway|Parliament]] in 1993 for the [[Oslo]] constituency, and is a member of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]].  He served as [[Minister of Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry]] from 1993 to 1996, until Brundtland resigned.<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/>\n\n==== Minister of Finance (1996\u20132000) ====\n{{Main|Jagland's Cabinet}}\nIn 1996, [[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]] became Prime Minister, and Stoltenberg became [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]].<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\"/> On 29 September 1997, Jagland resigned because of [[36.9 ultimatum|an ultimatum]] he had issued stating that the cabinet would resign should the party receive less than 36.9% of the popular vote.<ref>{{cite news |first=Herbj\u00f8rn |last=S\u00f8reb\u00f8 |authorlink=Herbj\u00f8rn S\u00f8reb\u00f8 |title=Ikkje noko mediemord |url=http://www.dagogtid.no/arkiv/2000/07/herb.html |work=[[Dag og Tid]] |date=17 February 2000 |language=no |url-status=dead |accessdate=31 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.dagogtid.no/arkiv/2000/07/herb.html |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref> Labour only received 35.0%; true to his promise, Jagland resigned as a consequence of its [[36.9 ultimatum]], and power was transferred to the [[Kjell Magne Bondevik's first term as Prime Minister of Norway|first cabinet of Kjell Magne Bondevik]].<ref name=resign>{{cite news|title=Meddelelse fra statsminister Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland om Regjeringens avskjedss\u00f8knad |first=Berit |last=Almendingen |date=29 September 1997 |work=Nettavisen |url=http://www.stortinget.no/no/Saker-og-publikasjoner/Saker/Sak/?p=1921 |language=no |accessdate=1 February 2009 |archivedate=16 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416195609/http://www.stortinget.no/no/Saker-og-publikasjoner/Saker/Sak/?p=1921 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SEATTLETIMES\">{{cite news|author=Mary Williams Walsh |title=Norway's Problem: Too Much Cash \u2013 Oil Is Flowing And Surplus Is Fat |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19971016&slug=2566475 |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=2 February 2009 |date=16 October 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120907230554/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19971016&slug=2566475 |archivedate= 7 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After Jagland's resignation and while in parliamentary opposition, Stoltenberg served on the standing committee on Oil and Energy Affairs in the [[Stortinget|Storting]].<ref name=\"BIOGRAPHY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Stoltenberg-Jens.html|title=Jens Stoltenberg Biography|work=notablebiographies.com|language=no|accessdate=2 February 2009}}</ref> He became the Parliamentary Leader and Prime Minister candidate for the Labour Party in February 2000.\n\n==== First term as Prime Minister (2000\u20132001) ====\n{{Main|Stoltenberg's First Cabinet}}\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6-8 September 2000-28.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg with Russian [[President of Russia|President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in New York City, 2000]]\nIn 2000, the [[Kjell Magne Bondevik's first term as Prime Minister of Norway|first cabinet of Bondevik]] resigned following an unsuccessful [[motion of confidence]].<ref name=\"CABINETII\">{{cite news|title=Norway's new cabinet named |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/680950.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 March 2000 |accessdate=1 February 2009 |url-status=live |archivedate=20 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420211441/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/680950.stm }}</ref> Stoltenberg's first cabinet governed Norway from 17 March 2000 to 19 October 2001.<ref name=\"CABINETII\"/> Stoltenberg was the [[deputy leader]] of the labor party while Jagland was the [[party leader]]. Instead Jagland was given the post as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Foreign Minister]]. Stoltenberg's first tenure as Prime Minister (2000\u20132001) was controversial within his own party, being responsible for reforms and modernisation of the [[welfare state]] that included part-privatising several key state-owned services and corporations. In the [[2001 Norwegian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] of 10 September 2001, the party suffered one of its worst results ever, winning only 24% of the vote.\n\nThe 2001, election met with instability for the Labour Party. The Norwegian newspaper ''[[Dagbladet]]'' stated: \"We are heading for a political earthquake when the votes are counted tonight, if we believe the opinion polls.\"<ref name=\"LABORREIIC\"/> In an interview with [[The Associated Press]] Jagland stated \"It is unstable and unpredictable.\"<ref name=\"LABORREIIC\">{{cite news|accessdate=2 February 2009 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/europe/09/10/norway.ballot/index.html |title=Norway set for close polls result |agency=CNN |date=10 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014112310/http://edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/europe/09/10/norway.ballot/index.html |archivedate=14 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the election in 2001, Stoltenberg and his cabinet were forced to resign, with the Labour Party suffering from its worst election campaign results since 1924.<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/> With the 98% votes taken, the Labour Party only garnered 24%, falling from 35%.<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/> Jagland, the Labor Party leader, commented on the results saying, \"We will have to make a decision about whether to continue in government after we know the full results\".<ref name=\"LABORRE\">{{cite news|accessdate=1 February 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1536377.stm |title=Norway poll sparks power struggle |work=BBC News |date=11 September 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420211443/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/1536377.stm |archivedate=20 April 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> After the election Stoltenberg said, \"What is clear is that this was a very bad election.\"<ref name=\"LABORRE\"/>\n\nSeveral analysts have pointed out that one of the reasonable causes for their loss was that with only one year in power until the next election, more time was spent initiating or trying to start reforms than telling the people why they had to be done. Such reforms included selling down in state-owned companies, re-organisation of health care and public hospitals and changes in sick pay. The changes made from the 2001 election to the 2005 election were described by Norwegian newspaper ''VG'' as an \"extreme makeover.\"<ref name=\"Extreme makeover\">{{cite news|first=Eirik |last=Mosveen |title=Ekstrem forvandling |trans-title=Extreme makeover |work=VG |date=11 August 2005 |language=no |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=106643 |access-date=12 March 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=13 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001303/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=106643 }}</ref>\n\n'''Party leader election'''\nThe bad election result in 2001 was quickly followed by a leadership battle between Jagland and Stoltenberg. Both Jagland, as leader, and Stoltenberg, as deputy leader, said they were open to be challenged for their positions at the party's congress in November 2002. Stoltenberg refused to say whether he would challenge Jagland for the leadership position, which was seen by political commentators as a sign that he probably would seek the leadership position.<ref>{{cite news|author=Marie Melg\u00e5rd, Tommy H. Brakstad |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/11/08/nyheter/jens_stoltenberg/thorbjorn_jagland/thor_viksveen/18933263/ |title=Slik var striden mellom Jens og Jagland |trans-title=Such was the battle between Jamie and Jagland |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=8 November 2011 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329215013/http://www.dagbladet.no/2011/11/08/nyheter/jens_stoltenberg/thorbjorn_jagland/thor_viksveen/18933263/ |archivedate=29 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the beginning of February 2002, Jagland, who had been briefly hospitalized in January, and had a subsequent sick leave,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/sykemeldt-til-3.feb-1.503884 |title=Sykemeldt til 3.feb |trans-title=Sick leave on 3 February |language=no |publisher=[[NRK]] |date=17 January 2002 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004801/http://www.nrk.no/norge/sykemeldt-til-3.feb-1.503884 |url-status=dead }}</ref> said that he would not seek reelection as leader.<ref>{{cite news |language=no |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2014 |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/article364621.ece#.UzVlsoVti8A |title=Gamle synder p\u00e5 lur i Ap |trans-title=Old sins lurking in AP |archivedate=29 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329220210/http://www.aftenposten.no/meninger/article364621.ece#.UzVlsoVti8A |url-status=dead }}</ref> In November 2002, Stoltenberg was unanimously elected new leader at the party's congress.<ref>{{cite news|language=no |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/stoltenberg-aps-nye-leder-1.507713 |title=Stoltenberg Aps nye leder |trans-title=Stoltenberg's Labor's new leader |date=10 November 2002 |publisher=[[NRK]] |accessdate=28 March 2014 |url-status=live |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004805/http://www.nrk.no/norge/stoltenberg-aps-nye-leder-1.507713 }}</ref>\n\n==== Second term as Prime Minister (2005\u20132013) ====\n[[File:Jens stoltenberg1.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg delivering a speech at Youngstorget, 1 May 2009.]]\n{{Main|Stoltenberg's Second Cabinet}}\nStoltenberg's second cabinet governed Norway from 17 October 2005 to 16 October 2013. The [[2005 Norwegian parliamentary election|2005 parliamentary election]] saw a vast improvement for Labour, and the party gained a majority in parliament together with the other \"Red-Green\" parties, the [[Sosialistisk Venstreparti|Socialist Left Party]] and the [[Senterpartiet|Centre Party]]. This paved the way for a historic first in Norway, with Labour joining in a coalition government, the [[Red-Green Coalition (Norway)|Red-Green Coalition]], after a [[First Declaration of Soria Moria|coalition deal]] with Stoltenberg was struck. Since the government's formation, key political issues such as [[Norwegian Armed Forces|Norwegian military]] participation in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]], petroleum activities in the [[Barents Sea]], [[LGBT]] rights, immigration and the quality of standard education were greatly debated by the public. Following [[2009 Norwegian parliamentary election|Stoltenberg's re-election in 2009]], he worked on the Swedish response to the [[Late-2000s recession|ongoing global recession]] and championed for [[environmentalism|environmentalist policies]] through private and corporate taxation.<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=15 September 2009 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8253849.stm |title=Norway's government is re-elected |work=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=14 September 2009 |language=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914100558/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8253849.stm |archivedate=14 September 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Medvedev in Norway (img12).jpeg|thumb|left|Stoltenberg with Russian President [[Dimitry Medvedev]], 27 April 2010.]]\nA [[Norway\u2013Russia border|marine border dispute with Russia]] in the Barents Sea since 1978 was settled when Stoltenberg and [[President of Russia]] [[Dimitry Medvedev]] signed an agreement on 27 April 2010 in Oslo.<ref>{{cite web|date=27 April 2010 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/27/norway-russia-barents-idUSLDE63Q14D20100427?type=marketsNews |title=UPDATE 3-Russia and Norway strike Arctic sea border deal |first=Denis |last=Dyomkin |first2=Gwladys |last2=Fouche |agency=Reuters |accessdate=27 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728040728/https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/27/norway-russia-barents-idUSLDE63Q14D20100427?type=marketsNews |archivedate=28 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/28/world/europe/28norway.html |title=Russia and Norway Reach Accord on Barents Sea |first=Walter |last=Gibbs |work=[[New York Times]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430074409/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/28/world/europe/28norway.html |archivedate=30 April 2010 |url-status=live |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010 }}</ref> The agreement is a compromise, which divides a disputed area of around 175,000 km2 (68,000 sq mi) into two approximately equally sized parts.<ref name=dn-28april2010>{{cite news |title=Gjennombrudd i Barentshavet |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |pages=6\u201313 |language=no |trans-title=Breakthrough in Barents Sea |date=28 April 2010 |work=Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv |accessdate=9 April 2014 |archivedate=8 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408154744/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, the agreement still needs ratification by the [[State Duma]] and the [[Parliament of Norway]] in order to be implemented. Whereas Norway had previously insisted on a border in accordance with the [[equidistance principle]], which is recognized in international law, specifically the [[United Nations Convention on Law of the Sea]] Article 15 and the [[Convention on the Territorial Sea and the Contiguous Zone]] Article 6, Russia invoked a [[Stalin]]-era decree of the [[Soviet Union]] from 1926, which was not recognised by any other country. The new agreement replaced a controversial<ref>[[K\u00e5re Willoch]] (2002): ''Myter og virkelighet''. Oslo: Cappelen.{{page needed|date=June 2015}}</ref> temporary agreement negotiated by [[Jens Evensen]] and [[Arne Treholt]], who was later revealed to be a Soviet spy and who aided the Soviet Union in the negotiations.<ref>''Stein Vale'' (2009): ''Teppefall i Treholtsaken''. Oslo: Cappelen Damm, pp. 34\u201336 and 135.</ref> Most of the disputed area was within what would normally be considered Norwegian according to the relevant international treaties.\n\nAs Prime Minister, Stoltenberg worked for a constructive relationship with Russia through dialogue and cooperation underpinned by NATO's deterrence and defence capabilities. During his tenure, he also emphasised the need to focus on security challenges close to Allied territory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |publisher=[[Government.no]] |title=Good neighbourly relations and international cooperation |accessdate=4 April 2014 |date=4 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406210948/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/ud/campaigns/the-high-north/naeringsutvikling_verdiskapning/neighbourly_relations.html?regj_oss=1&id=732075 |archivedate=6 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''22 July 2011 terror attacks'''\n{{Main|2011 Norway attacks}}\n[[File:Jens Stoltenberg 2012.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg speaks at a service commemorating the one year anniversary of the 2011 attacks.|alt=Jens Stoltenberg speaking at a podium.]]\nOn 22 July 2011, a bomb went off in [[Oslo]] outside the government building which houses the prime minister's office, killing eight people while wounding others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sollid|first=Stephen JM|last2=Rimstad|first2=Rune|last3=Rehn|first3=Marius|last4=Nakstad|first4=Anders R|last5=Tomlinson|first5=Ann-Elin|last6=Strand|first6=Terje|last7=Heimdal|first7=Hans|last8=Nilsen|first8=Jan|last9=Sandberg|first9=M\u00e5rten|date=2012|title=Oslo government district bombing and Ut\u00f8ya island shooting July 22, 2011: The immediate prehospital emergency medical service response|url=https://sjtrem.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1757-7241-20-3|journal=Scandinavian Journal of Trauma, Resuscitation and Emergency Medicine|language=En|volume=20|issue=1|pages=3|doi=10.1186/1757-7241-20-3|issn=1757-7241|pmc=3266631|pmid=22280935}}</ref> About an hour later, a shooting spree, which killed 69 people, was reported at [[Ut\u00f8ya]], an island forty-five minutes away where the ruling Labour Party was holding its annual youth camp. The PM was due for a visit at the youth camp the next day, and was in his residence preparing his speech at the time of the Oslo explosion.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://e24.no/makro-og-politikk/stoltenberg-skrev-tale-til-utoeya-da-bomben-smalt/20082498 \n |title=Stoltenberg skrev tale til Ut\u00f8ya da bomben smalt \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg wrote the speech to Ut\u00f8ya when the bomb hit \n |last=NTB \n |date=25 July 2011 \n |accessdate=25 July 2011 \n |publisher=[[E24 N\u00e6ringsliv|E24]] \n |language=no \n |archivedate= 9 August 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809041912/http://e24.no/makro-og-politikk/stoltenberg-skrev-tale-til-utoeya-da-bomben-smalt/20082498 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday 24 July, Stoltenberg spoke at the church service in the [[Oslo Cathedral]]. He named two of the victims at Ut\u00f8ya, Monica B\u00f8sei, who was the camp's leader, and Tore Eikeland, who was the leader of the youth chapter in Hordaland. He again vowed to work for more democracy, openness, and humanity, but without naivety.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/terrorangrepet-22-juli-politikk-og-samfunn/stoltenberg-paa-minnestund-vi-har-maktet-aa-staa-oppreist-i-en-kritisk-tid/a/10080701/ \n |title=Stoltenberg p\u00e5 minnestund: \u2013 Vi har maktet \u00e5 st\u00e5 oppreist i en kritisk tid \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg at memorial: \u2013 We have managed to stay upright in a critical time \n |last=Kleivan \n |first=Nikolai \n |date=24 July 2011 \n |newspaper=Verdens Gang \n |language=no \n |accessdate=25 July 2011 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328222457/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/terrorangrepet-22-juli-politikk-og-samfunn/stoltenberg-paa-minnestund-vi-har-maktet-aa-staa-oppreist-i-en-kritisk-tid/a/10080701/ \n |archivedate=28 March 2014 \n}}</ref> He also said that \"No one has said it better than the AUF girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can show so much hate, think how much love we could show, standing together.''\"<ref>{{cite news|date=24 July 2011 |accessdate=24 July 2011 |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/jul/24/norway-attacks-live-updates |title=orway attacks rolling coverage: Sunday 24 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828174305/http://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2011/jul/24/norway-attacks-live-updates |archivedate=28 August 2013 |url-status=live |quote=No one has said it better than the AUF girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can show so much hate, think how much love we could show, standing together.'' }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/smk/Whats-new/Speeches-and-articles/statsministeren/statsminister_jens_stoltenberg/2011/address-by-prime-minister-in-oslo-cathed.html |title=Address by Prime Minister in Oslo Cathedral |website=Government.no |date=24 July 2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011 |quote=No one has said it better than the Labour Youth League girl who was interviewed by CNN: ''If one man can create that much hate, you can only imagine how much love we as a togetherness can create.'' |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211093533/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/smk/Whats-new/Speeches-and-articles/statsministeren/statsminister_jens_stoltenberg/2011/address-by-prime-minister-in-oslo-cathed.html |archivedate=11 February 2012 }}</ref> The [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|AUF]] girl mentioned is [[Stine Renate H\u00e5heim]] interviewed by CNN's [[Richard Quest]] on 23 July 2011.<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[CNN]] |url=http://edition.cnn.com/video/?/video/world/2011/07/23/bpr.haheim.norwegian.lawmaker.cnn |title=Norway Island survivor: CNN's Richard Quest talks to Stine Renate Haheim |accessdate=24 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121101600/http://edition.cnn.com/video/?%2Fvideo%2Fworld%2F2011%2F07%2F23%2Fbpr.haheim.norwegian.lawmaker.cnn |url-status=live |archivedate=21 January 2012 |quote=If one man can create that much hate, you can only imagine how much love we as a togetherness can create. }}</ref> H\u00e5heim again quoted her friend Helle Gannestad, who had tweeted this from home, watching events unfold on TV.<ref>{{cite web|website=Side2.no |accessdate=4 April 2014 |url=http://www.side2.no/3201858.html |title=Helle inspirerte verdensstjernen |trans-title=Helle inspired world star |archivedate=29 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329013517/http://www.side2.no/3201858.html |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2012, 33-year-old Norwegian [[Anders Behring Breivik]] was found [[Trial of Anders Behring Breivik|guilty]] by the [[Oslo District Court]] of having perpetrated by himself both [[terrorist attacks]], the bombing of the prime minister's office and the shooting spree on [[Ut\u00f8ya]] island, and was convicted to ''[[Life imprisonment in Norway|containment]]'', a special form of [[prison sentence]] that can be extended indefinitely\u2014with a time frame of 21 years and a minimum time of 10 years, which, in all, is the maximum penalty in Norway.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-19365616 |title=Anders Behring Breivik: Norway court finds him sane |work=[[BBC News]] |date=24 August 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824083419/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-19365616 |archivedate=24 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2012, Norwegian daily ''[[Klassekampen]]'' wrote that the [[Gj\u00f8rv Report]] on the terrorist attack \"is the hardest verdict against a Norwegian cabinet since the Fact-Finding Commission of 1945 ensured that [[Johan Nygaardsvold]]'s political career was abruptly halted.\"<ref>[http://klassekampen.no/60619/article/item/null/overivrig Overivrig] \"22. juli-kommisjonens rapport er den mest knusende dom en norsk regjering har f\u00e5tt siden Unders\u00f8kelseskommisjonen i 1945 s\u00f8rget for at Johan Nygaardsvolds politiske karriere fikk en br\u00e5 slutt.\"</ref> Stoltenberg said after the report was published that he had \"ultimate responsibility for the preparedness in our country, a responsibility I take seriously,\" but he said he would not resign.<ref>{{cite news\n |agency=CNN \n |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/13/world/europe/norway-massacre-report/ \n |title=Norway massacre could have been avoided, report finds \n |date=13 August 2012 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408012257/http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/13/world/europe/norway-massacre-report/ \n |archivedate= 8 April 2014 \n}}</ref>\n\n'''2013 election and defeat'''\n{{main|2013 Norwegian parliamentary election}}\nStoltenberg was the Prime Minister candidate for the Red-Green Coalition in the [[2013 Norwegian parliamentary election|2013 elections]], seeking re-election for a third term.\n\nOn 9 September 2013, the coalition failed to win majority, with 72 of the required 85 mandates, despite the Labour Party remaining the largest party in Norway with 30.8%.<ref>Accurate as of 23:20 local time on election night.</ref> In his speech the same night, he announced that his cabinet would resign in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vgtv.no/#!id=70029&index=39|title=VGTV|website=Vgtv.no|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref> Stoltenberg returned to the Parliament where he became parliamentarian leader for the Labour Party and a member of the [[Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs and Defence]]. In December 2013, he was appointed by the United Nations as a [[Special Envoy on Climate Change]], alongside the former Ghanaian president [[John Kufuor]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Rolleiv |last=Solholm |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29362-stoltenberg-new-un-special-envoy |agency=[[NRK]] |accessdate=29 December 2013 |newspaper=The Norway Post |date=24 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225142525/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29362-stoltenberg-new-un-special-envoy |archivedate=25 December 2013 |url-status=live |title=Stoltenberg new UN special envoy }}</ref>\n\n====Policies as Prime Minister====\nStoltenberg has been described as a cautious politician, belonging to the right wing of [[social democracy]].<ref>Per \u00d8stby [http://www.transportarbeider.no/kunder/ntf/cms.nsf/%28$All%29/DF06C0C2FD22A5A1C12578A00037150B?OpenDocument Refser de r\u00f8dgr\u00f8nne] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917124653/http://www.transportarbeider.no/kunder/ntf/cms.nsf/%28$All%29/DF06C0C2FD22A5A1C12578A00037150B?OpenDocument |date=17 September 2016 }} {{in lang|no}} transportarbeider.no. 15 September 2010. Retrieved 31 March 2014</ref> In security policy, Stoltenberg favours increased military spending and dialogue.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2014 |language=no |url=http://www.dn.no/nyheter/2014/03/28/stoltenberg-vil-vre-bde-hauk-og-due |title=Stoltenberg vil v\u00e6re b\u00e5de hauk og due |trans-title=Stoltenberg Will be Both Hawk and Dove |publisher=[[Dagens N\u00e6ringsliv|DN.no]]; [[Norwegian Telegram Agency|NTB]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407052805/http://www.dn.no/nyheter/2014/03/28/stoltenberg-vil-vre-bde-hauk-og-due |archivedate= 7 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n'''Defense and foreign politics'''\n[[File:JensandNato.jpg|thumb|[[Secretary General of NATO]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] and Stoltenberg, while visiting Oslo talk with members of [[Telemark Battalion]].]]\n[[File:Paris Summit for the Support to the Libyan People 04.jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg at the Paris Summit of 19 March 2011 (back row, second from right), which marked the start of a [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]].]]\nWhile Stoltenberg was Prime Minister, Norway's defence spending increased steadily, with the result that Norway today is one of the NATO allies with the highest per capita defence expenditure.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29677-stoltenberg-appointed-new-nato-chief \n |title=Stoltenberg appointed new NATO Chief \n |newspaper=The Norway Post \n |accessdate=11 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140411231628/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29677-stoltenberg-appointed-new-nato-chief \n |archivedate=11 April 2014 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg has also been instrumental in modernising the Norwegian armed forces, and in contributing forces to various NATO operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tnp.no/norway/politics/4421-nato-appoints-jens-stoltenberg-as-nato-sg-as-of-october-1st-2014-norway |title=NATO Appoints Jens Stoltenberg as NATO SG as of October 1st 2014 |work=The Nordic Page |accessdate=11 April 2014 |place=[[Oslo]] |date=23 March 2014 |language=no |archivedate=11 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140411233130/http://www.tnp.no/norway/politics/4421-nato-appoints-jens-stoltenberg-as-nato-sg-as-of-october-1st-2014-norway |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg is a supporter of enhanced trans-Atlantic cooperation ties. He has also always been a supporter of Norwegian membership in the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Henrik Width |language=no |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-harselerte-med-EOS-avtalen-6301963.html |title=Stoltenberg harselerte med E\u00d8S-avtalen |trans-title=Stoltenberg mocked the EEA Agreement |newspaper=Aftenposten |date=19 October 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004619/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Stoltenberg-harselerte-med-EOS-avtalen-6301963.html |archivedate=30 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg has criticized [[Israel]] over [[alleged]] violations of international law in the Palestinian Territories as well as in international waters, such as the [[Gaza flotilla raid]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/utenriks/stoltenberg-uakseptabelt-av-israel-3218802.html \n |author=Lars Barth-Heyerdahl \n |title=Stoltenberg: \u2013 Uakseptabelt av Israel: Den norske regjeringen ford\u00f8mmer bordingen av skip med n\u00f8dhjelp p\u00e5 vei til Gaza \n |trans-title=Stoltenberg: \u2013 Unacceptable of Israel: The Norwegian government condemns board of the ship with the aid headed to Gaza \n |publisher=TV2 \n |language=no \n |date=31 May 2010 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407060307/http://www.tv2.no/nyheter/utenriks/stoltenberg-uakseptabelt-av-israel-3218802.html \n |archivedate= 7 April 2014 \n}}</ref> In 2006, Stoltenberg stated that \"Norway condemns Israel's actions against Palestinians. Such collective punishment is totally unacceptable.\"<ref>{{cite news\n |newspaper   = Aftenbladet\n |language    = no\n |date        = 14 July 2006\n |url         = http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/utenriks/article312125.ece\n |title       = Stoltenberg ford\u00f8mmer Israel\n |trans-title = Stoltenberg condemns Israel\n |url-status     = dead\n |archivedate = 7 April 2014\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070254/http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/utenriks/article312125.ece\n}}</ref> Stoltenberg praised doctors [[Mads Gilbert]] and [[Erik Fosse]] for their humanitarian work in the Gaza Strip during the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]], stating that \"all of Norway\" was behind them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtoesten/stoltenberg-hyller-norske-gaza-leger/a/550179/ |title=Stoltenberg hyller norske Gaza-leger |trans-title=Stoltenberg shelves Norwegian Gaza doctors |newspaper=Verdens Gang |date=1 November 2009 |archivedate= 7 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407061215/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/midtoesten/stoltenberg-hyller-norske-gaza-leger/a/550179/ |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref>\n\n'''Financial crisis'''\n\nStoltenberg took an international role during the financial crisis by promoting international financial cooperation. This was among other arenas done through the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) and a meeting in Chile 27\u201329 March 2009 where social democratic leaders from around the world met at a Progressive Governance Conference, just prior to the first G20 summit on the financial crisis. President [[Bill Clinton]] was among the delegates and panel that would chart a way out of the financial crisis, which included the host [[Michelle Bachelet]], Britain's finance minister [[Gordon Brown]], Brazil's President [[Lula da Silva]] and Stoltenberg. A special emergency meeting of the European Social Democratic Forum (PES) was gathered in Oslo in May 2011, on an initiative from Stoltenberg and the think tank Policy Network.\n\nBoth nationally and internationally, Stoltenberg emphasised the enormous costs the financial crisis had in the form of a high unemployment rate, and appealed for better international coordination, the balance between austerity and economic growth stimulus, active labor market measures for young people, and investments for increased innovation.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Norway came out of the financial crisis with the lowest unemployment rate in Europe.<ref name=Db>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/05/01/nyheter/innenriks/arbeidsledighet/jens_stoltenberg/1_mai/11529483/ |language=no |title=Norge har lavest arbeids-ledighet i Europa |trans-title=Norway has the lowest unemployment in Europe |work=Dagbladet |date=1 May 2010 |archivedate= 4 May 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504043235/http://www.dagbladet.no/2010/05/01/nyheter/innenriks/arbeidsledighet/jens_stoltenberg/1_mai/11529483/ }}</ref>\n\n'''Environment and climate change'''\n\nPartnering with tropical countries to preserve more of their rainforest to bind carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>) in order to reduce [[greenhouse gas emissions]] was a policy of the Stoltenberg government. In 2007, the government received support from the opposition to a long-term agreement to finance forest conservation with 3 billion NOK annually.<ref name=NRK>{{cite news\n |publisher=NRK \n |language=no \n |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/gir-tre-milliarder-til-regnskogen-1.4252368 \n |title=Gir tre milliarder til regnskogen \n |date=12 September 2012 \n |archivedate=13 March 2014 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001201/http://www.nrk.no/norge/gir-tre-milliarder-til-regnskogen-1.4252368 \n}}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg through his governing advocated that international agreements with global taxes or quotas are the most effective means of reducing greenhouse gas emissions. At the [[UN Climate Change Conference 2009]], a separate proposal on the preservation of rainforests with funding from rich countries, advanced by Stoltenberg and Brazilian [[President of Brazil|Pres]]. [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] in 2009 obtained support from among others U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] during COP15 in Copenhagen.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nThe summit in Copenhagen ended without a binding agreement, but before the subsequent COP16 in [[Canc\u00fan]], Stoltenberg succeeded then-British Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] in the leadership of the committee dealing with the financing of climate actions in developing countries, also consisting of Ethiopian [[Prime Minister of Ethiopia|Prime Minister]] [[Meles Zenawi]]. Under a separate forest and climate conference in Oslo in May 2010, a proposal was presented to a number of countries, with final delivery of the report in autumn 2010.\n\nIn January 2014 Jens Stoltenberg became [[United Nations Special Envoy on Climate Change]]. During the meeting there he met with Secretary General [[Ban Ki-Moon]] as well as [[United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change|UN Framework Convention]] director [[Christiana Figueres]] and both [[Achim Steiner]] and [[Helen Clark]] of the [[United Nations Development Programme]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.norway-un.org/News/News-2013/Jens-Stoltenberg-becomes-UN-special-envoy-on-Climate-Change/#.U0lN5iwo5lY \n |title=Jens Stoltenberg becomes UN special envoy on Climate Change \n |accessdate=12 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412144608/http://www.norway-un.org/News/News-2013/Jens-Stoltenberg-becomes-UN-special-envoy-on-Climate-Change/#.U0lN5iwo5lY \n |archivedate=12 April 2014 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref>\n\n'''Vaccines'''\n\nStoltenberg has been an advocate for having all the world's children vaccinated against infectious diseases. The first speech he gave in his second term as Prime Minister was during Norway's \"Pharmaceutics days\" in 2005 under the title \"Vaccination against poverty\". Stoltenberg was director of the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization ([[GAVI]]) from 2002 to 2005 and was awarded the Children's Health Award in 2005.\n\nAn international initiative, with the UK, the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|Gates Foundation]] and Norway in the lead, that GAVI received more than $3.7 billion until 2015 for their work against child mortality.<ref>{{cite news\n |date=16 May 2005 \n |url=http://www.tnp.no/norway/health/2276-bill-gates-meets-jens-stoltenberg \n |title=Bill Gates Meets Jens Stoltenberg \n |newspaper=The Nordic Page \n |accessdate=12 April 2014 \n |archivedate=13 April 2014 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413145857/http://www.tnp.no/norway/health/2276-bill-gates-meets-jens-stoltenberg \n |url-status=live \n |language=no \n}}</ref> Stoltenberg was one of the key driving forces behind the initiative, and has stressed that this is an important contribution to save 9 million children from dying of the most common childhood illnesses.\n\nIn his New Year speech on 1 January 2013, Stoltenberg spoke about vaccination of the world's children as a personal matter of the heart. \"Small jabs are giving millions of children the gift of life. Simple medicines can save their mothers. The fact that all these mothers' and children's lives can be saved is \u2013 as I see it \u2013 a miracle of our time,\" Stoltenberg said in his speech.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 January 2013 |url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/archive/Stoltenbergs-2nd-Government/Office-of-the-Prime-Minister/taler-og-artikler/2013/prime-minister-jens-stoltenbergs-new-yea.html?id=710868 |title=Stoltenbergs New Year speech |language=no |accessdate=12 March 2014 |archivedate=13 March 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313001014/http://www.regjeringen.no/en/archive/Stoltenbergs-2nd-Government/Office-of-the-Prime-Minister/taler-og-artikler/2013/prime-minister-jens-stoltenbergs-new-yea.html?id=710868 }}</ref>\n\n=== United Nations (2013\u20132014) ===\nIn 2011, Stoltenberg received the United Nations (UN) Champion of Global Change Award in New York City, chosen for his extraordinary effort toward meeting the Millennium Development Goals and bringing fresh ideas to global problems. In 2013, Stoltenberg served as a UN special envoy on [[climate change]] ([[global warming]]), and he has chaired the UN High-Level Panel on System Wide Coherence and the High-Level Advisory Group on Climate Change Financing.\n\n=== NATO Secretary General (2014\u2013present) ===\n{{See also|NATO\u2013Russia relations}}\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Listens to NATO Secretary-General Stoltenberg Speak Before Members Signed an Accession Protocol to Continue Montenegro's Admission to the Alliance in Brussels (26839433820).jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg and [[Montenegro]]'s Prime Minister [[Milo Djukanovic]] attend a NATO foreign ministers meeting on 19 May 2016]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Chats with NATO Secretary General Stoltenberg and his UK and Turkish Counterparts During the NATO Ministerial in Brussels (41029400304).jpg|thumb|Stoltenberg with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo|Pompeo]], UK Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]] and Turkish Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu|\u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]], Brussels, April 2018]]\n[[File:TrumpNato18.jpg|thumb|A meeting of NATO heads of States and governments on 11 July 2018 in Brussels]]\nOn 28 March 2014 [[NATO]]'s [[North Atlantic Council]] appointed Stoltenberg as designated successor of [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] as the 13th [[Secretary General of NATO]] and Chairman of the council, effective from 1 October 2014.<ref name=natojens>{{cite web|date=28 March 2014 |url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_108390.htm |title=Appointment of Secretary General designate |publisher=[[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] |accessdate=28 March 2014 |df= }}</ref> The appointment had been widely expected in the media for some time, and commentators pointed out that the alliance's policies toward Russia will be the most important issue faced by Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/29/world/europe/nato-picks-former-norwegian-premier-as-its-next-leader.html?_r=1 |author=James Kanter |title=Norwegian to Lead NATO as It Is Poised for Bigger Role |date=28 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408210305/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/29/world/europe/nato-picks-former-norwegian-premier-as-its-next-leader.html?_r=1 |archivedate= 8 April 2014 |url-status=live |url-access=registration  }}</ref> [[Angela Merkel]], the Chancellor of Germany, took the initiative to appoint Stoltenberg as Secretary-General, securing the support first of the United States, then of the United Kingdom, and then of all other member states.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Jens-Stoltenberg-skal-ha-lovet-a-lare-seg-fransk-7520428.html |title=Stoltenberg skal l\u00e6re seg fransk |trans-title=Stoltenberg will learn French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329220350/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/uriks/Jens-Stoltenberg-skal-ha-lovet-a-lare-seg-fransk-7520428.html |archivedate=29 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=no |newspaper=Aftenposten }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=29 March 2014 |url=http://www.nrk.no/norge/merkel-ringte-stoltenberg-i-host-1.11637880 |title=Stoltenberg letter p\u00e5 sl\u00f8ret: Merkel ringte meg om NATO-jobben i oktober |trans-title=Stoltenberg got a hint: Merkel called me about NATO job in October |publisher=NRK |accessdate=31 March 2014 |archivedate=30 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330051613/http://www.nrk.no/norge/merkel-ringte-stoltenberg-i-host-1.11637880 |language=no |url-status=live }}</ref> Norway was a founding member of NATO in 1949, and Stoltenberg is the first Norwegian to serve as Secretary-General, although former [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]] Prime Minister [[K\u00e5re Willoch]] was considered a strong candidate in 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Toppene-avgjor-Stoltenbergs-Nato-fremtid-7508976.html |title=Toppene avgj\u00f8r Stoltenbergs Nato-fremtid |author1=Lars Molteberg Glomnes |author2=Ole Mathismoen |newspaper=Aftenposten |author3=Robert Gjerde |date=19 March 2014 |archivedate=19 March 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319232145/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/politikk/Toppene-avgjor-Stoltenbergs-Nato-fremtid-7508976.html |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Stoltenberg said: \"I believe we don't see any immediate threat against any NATO country from the east. Our goal is still cooperation with [[Russia]] \u2026 That serves NATO and it serves Russia.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Stoltenberg: Russia Doesn't Pose Immediate Threat to NATO States |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2015/06/04/stoltenberg-russia-doesnt-pose-immediate-threat-to-nato-states-a47125 |work=The Moscow Times |date=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, [[Czech Republic|Czech]] Deputy Prime Minister Andrej Babi\u0161 criticized NATO's lack of response to the [[European migrant crisis]]. After talks with Stoltenberg on migrant crisis issue Babi\u0161 said: \"NATO is not interested in refugees, though Turkey, a NATO member, is their entrance gate to Europe and smugglers operate on Turkish territory\".<ref name=\"CN\">\"[http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czech-minister-babis-criticises-nato-s-stance-on-refugees/1256815 Czech minister Babis criticises NATO\u00b4s stance on refugees]\". CeskeNoviny.cz. 10 September 2015.</ref>\n\nStoltenberg strongly condemned the [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] and expressed full support for [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]'s government.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/turkey-security-nato-idUSL1N1A61L6 NATO chief says Turkey's military still strong despite detentions]\". Reuters. 20 July 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_134408.htm|title=NATO Spokesperson's statement on Turkey|last=NATO|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> He did not condemn the [[2016\u2013present purges in Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO declines to condemn arrests of Turkish legislators, journalists |url=https://www.dpa-international.com/topic/nato-declines-condemn-arrests-turkish-legislators-161121-99-255828 |work=[[Deutsche Presse-Agentur]] |date=21 November 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Stoltenberg admitted that some \"Turkish officers working in NATO command structures... have requested asylum in the countries where they are working.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=More academics, mayors detained as Turkish purges enter fifth month |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security/more-academics-mayors-detained-as-turkish-purges-enter-fifth-month-idUSKBN13D0IU |agency=Reuters |date=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Stoltenberg stated that the NATO strongly supported \"the UN-led political process to find a solution\" to the [[Cyprus dispute|dispute]] over the northern part of [[Cyprus]], which has been under illegal occupation since the [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|Turkish invasion of 1974]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Jens Stoltenberg: NATO responds to \"Russia's aggression against Ukraine\" |url=https://tass.com/world/883050 |work=TASS |date=17 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Stoltenberg warned that Russia has used big military exercises, including [[Zapad 2017 exercise]] in Russia's [[Kaliningrad Oblast]] and [[Belarus]], \"as a disguise or a precursor for aggressive military actions against their neighbours.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia was the target of Nato's own fake news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/russia-zapad-2017-putin-west-fake-news-us-world-war-three-ukraine-belarus-nato-a7961856.html |work=The Independent |date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, in response to the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin|Turkish invasion of northern Syria]] aimed at ousting U.S.-backed [[People's Protection Units|Syrian Kurds]] from the enclave of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]], Stoltenberg said that Turkey is \"the NATO Ally which has suffered most from terrorist attacks over many years and Turkey, as all of the countries, have the right to self defence, but it is important that this is done in a proportionate and measured way.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nato.int/cps/ic/natohq/opinions_151089.htm?selectedLocale=en | title=Joint press conference with NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg and the Minister of Defence of Spain, Mar\u00eda Dolores de Cospedal Garc\u00eda | website=NATO.int | date=25 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Stoltenberg stated: \"We don\u2019t see any threat [from Russia] against any NATO ally and therefore, I\u2019m always careful speculating too much about hypothetical situations.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO sees no Russian threat to any of its members \u2014 head |url=https://tass.com/world/990990 |work=TASS |date=21 February 2018}}</ref> Stoltenberg welcomed the [[2018 Russia\u2013United States summit]] between Vladimir Putin and Donald Trump in Helsinki, Finland.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: Gorbachev has high hopes for Putin-Trump summit |url=https://apnews.com/a8cad273fde84304a2aa31c6cd5cf7a6 |work=AP News |date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> He said NATO is not trying to isolate Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief warns against isolating Russia |url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/07/11/nato-chief-warns-against-isolating-russia |work=Euronews |date=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Stoltenberg stated that the former [[Republics of the Soviet Union|Soviet republic]] of \"Georgia will become a member of NATO\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgia \u2018will join NATO\u2019: Stoltenberg |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/georgia-will-join-nato-stoltenberg-142174 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Stoltenberg warned a joint session of the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] of threat posed by Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief warns of Russia threat, urges unity in U.S. address |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-nato/nato-chief-warns-of-russia-threat-urges-unity-in-u-s-address-idUSKCN1RF22L |work=Reuters |date=3 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief calls for confronting Russia in speech to Congress |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/03/nato-secretary-general-russia-congress-1252838 |work=Politico |date=3 April 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, Stoltenberg hailed [[Turkey]]'s contribution to NATO. He said: \"Turkey joined the Alliance in 1952, and it continues to be a highly valued member of our family of nations. As secretary-general, I greatly appreciate all that Turkey does for our Alliance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO is committed to the defense of Turkey: Stoltenberg |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/nato-is-committed-to-the-defense-of-turkey-stoltenberg-143167 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=5 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Stoltenberg warned that NATO needs to \"address the rise of [[China]],\" by closely cooperating with [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO needs to address China's rise, says Stoltenberg |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-australia-nato/nato-needs-to-address-chinas-rise-says-stoltenberg-idUSKCN1UX0YX |agency=Reuters |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nStoltenberg \"strongly condemned\" the [[2019 Abqaiq\u2013Khurais attack]] on key [[Saudi Arabia]]'s oil facilities and accused [[Iran]] of \"supporting different terrorist groups and being responsible for destabilising the whole region.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=NATO chief 'extremely concerned' after attacks on Saudi |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190916-nato-chief-extremely-concerned-after-attacks-on-saudi |work=France 24 |date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkey invaded]] the [[Rojava|Kurdish areas in Syria]]. Stoltenberg said that Turkey has \"legitimate security concerns\" during press conference with Turkish FM [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey's actions in Syria must be measured: NATO chief |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-nato/turkeys-actions-in-syria-must-be-measured-nato-chief-idUSKBN1WO1YO |agency=Reuters |date=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. military's [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike]], which killed the high-level Iranian General [[Qasem Soleimani]], brought strong reactions from around the world. Stoltenberg said, following a meeting on 6{{nbsp}}January, \"all members of the Atlantic alliance stood behind the United States in the Middle East\" and that \"Iran must refrain from further violence and provocations.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-iraq-security-iran-nato/us-briefs-nato-over-iran-strike-avoids-european-criticism-idUSKBN1Z51SI |title=U.S. briefs NATO over Iran strike, avoids European criticism |last=Emmott |first=Robin |date=6 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]] }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Incognito taxi driver in Norway===\nIn August 2013, Stoltenberg said on his Facebook page that he had spent an afternoon working ''[[Anonymity|incognito]]'' as a taxi driver in Oslo.<ref name=beeb>{{cite news|work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23655675 |title=Norway PM Jens Stoltenberg works as secret taxi driver |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811192438/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23655675 |archivedate=11 August 2013 |date=11 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Stoltenberg said he had wanted to \"hear from real Norwegian voters\" and that \"taxis were one of the few places where people shared their true views.\" He added that, before driving the taxi, he had not driven a car in eight years.<ref name=beeb/> The event was videotaped in a [[hidden camera]] fashion, and released as a promotional video by the Labour party for the election campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Peters |first=Tim |title=Taxi-Jens lurte velgere med skjult kamera ** \u2013 Fikk en del kritikk for kj\u00f8ringen min |newspaper=VG |accessdate=23 March 2014 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/valg-2013/artikkel.php?artid=10119094 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225210/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/valg-2013/artikkel.php?artid=10119094 |archivedate=23 March 2014 |url-status=live |language=no }}</ref> It was later confirmed that 5 of the 14 customers were paid and recruited by the production company that produced the event for the Labour party.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davidson |first=Jacob |accessdate=23 March 2014 |url=http://world.time.com/2013/08/12/watch-norwegian-p-m-jens-stoltenberg-goes-incognito-as-a-cab-driver/ |title=Norwegian Prime Minister's Taxi Stunt Involved Paid Actors |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225635/http://world.time.com/2013/08/12/watch-norwegian-p-m-jens-stoltenberg-goes-incognito-as-a-cab-driver/ |archivedate=23 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Johansen |first=Nilas |title=Fikk betalt for tur med \"Taxi-Jens\" Brukte \"street casting\" for \u00e5 sikre passasjerer til statsministeren |trans-title=Got paid for the trip with \"Taxi Jens\" Used \"street casting\" to ensure passengers to the Prime Minister |accessdate=23 March 2014 |newspaper=VG |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=10119280 |date=12 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323225254/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/norsk-politikk/artikkel.php?artid=10119280 |archivedate=23 March 2014 |language=no }}</ref> None, however, knew they would meet Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw.com/en/a-taxi-stunt-goes-awry-for-norways-prime-minister/av-17023271\n|title=Norwegian Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg Drives a Taxi |date=12 August 2013  |first1=Andreas |last1=Illmer  |publisher=Deutsche Welle, Germany |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsvaqF9KZXI |title=Norwegian Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg Drives a Taxi (Video) |date=12 August 2013\n|publisher=Deutsche Welle, Germany |website=YouTube.com|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n* Stoltenberg had regular contacts with a [[KGB]] agent disguised as a Soviet diplomat, and participated in protest rallies against the [[Vietnam War|U.S. war in Vietnam]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"local\">\"[https://www.thelocal.no/20150806/nato-boss-sung-anti-nato-songs-as-a-youth Nato boss sang anti-Nato songs as a youth]\". ''[[The Local]]''. 6 August 2015.</ref> In 2011, Stoltenberg said \"We sang the chorus, \u2018Singing Norway, Norway out of Nato'. It was a hit.\"<ref name=\"local\"/>  \n* In 2001, Stoltenberg crashed his Labour Party-owned car into a parked car; he then left the premises without leaving a note with his name or number; the damages cost 8000 [[Norwegian kroner]] to repair.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hultgreen, Gunnar |title=Jens varslet ikke eieren |trans-title=Jens did not notify the owner |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=8 December 2001 |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2001/12/08/299904.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011208102121/http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2001/12/08/299904.html |url-status=live |archivedate= 8 December 2001 |accessdate=5 November 2016 }}</ref>  \n* In 2002, Stoltenberg admitted to having used [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] in his youth.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kaasa, Kjell M. |title=Ja, jeg har pr\u00f8vd hasj! |trans-title=Yes, I have tried weed! |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=2 November 2002 |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2002/11/02/352834.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021102110239/http://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/2002/11/02/352834.html |archivedate= 2 November 2002 |url-status=live |accessdate=19 November 2010 }}</ref>  He therefore asked the [[Ministry of Justice and Public Security]] to evaluate his impartiality in the upcoming government response to the report on drugs by the Stoltenberg Commission, headed by his father, Thorvald Stoltenberg.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vurderer statsministerens habilitet i narkotikapolitikken |trans-title=Considering the Prime Minister's impartiality in drug policy |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10010872 |work=[[Verdens Gang|VG]] |date=10 November 2010 |accessdate=19 November 2010 |agency=[[Norwegian News Agency|NTB]] |language=no |archivedate=13 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113023454/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10010872 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* In 2011, Stoltenberg received a prize from the [[UN Foundation]] for excellent global leadership and Norway's support of the [[UN]]. Earlier the same year, Stoltenberg had allocated 150 million [[Norwegian kroner]] of the foreign aid budget to the same foundation, which led to criticism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Gedde-Dahl, Siri |title=Stoltenberg delte ut penger - fikk pris i retur |trans-title=Stoltenberg handed out money - got prize in return |work=[[Aftenposten]] |language=no |date=25 November 2011 |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Stoltenberg-delte-ut-penger-A--fikk-pris-i-retur-6706022.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125232422/http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Stoltenberg-delte-ut-penger-A--fikk-pris-i-retur-6706022.html |url-status=live |archivedate=25 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref> Also in 2011 Stoltenberg got a 380,000 [[Norwegian kroner|kroner]] boat as a birthday gift from the [[Norwegian Labour Party]] and the [[Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions]]; the givers also paid the tax for the gift which led to criticism.<ref>{{cite news|author=Thomas Ege, Rune |title=Stoltenberg fikk b\u00e5t til 380.000 |trans-title=Stoltenberg got boat to 380.000 |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=22 July 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/stoltenberg-regjeringen/stoltenberg-fikk-baat-til-380-000/a/10080554/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126002555/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/stoltenberg-regjeringen/stoltenberg-fikk-baat-til-380-000/a/10080554/ |url-status=live |archivedate=26 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Johanson, Marianne |title=Ap betalte skatt for b\u00e5tgaven til Jens |trans-title=AP paid tax for the boat gift |work=[[Dagbladet]] |language=no |date=22 October 2011 |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/arbeiderpartiet/ap-betalte-skatt-for-baatgaven-til-jens/a/10022907/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501113206/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/arbeiderpartiet/ap-betalte-skatt-for-baatgaven-til-jens/a/10022907 |url-status=live |archivedate= 1 May 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Jens Stoltenberg}}\n\n===News links===\n* [http://search.time.com/?q=jens+stoltenberg&site=time ''Time'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.forbes.com/search/?q=jens%20stoltenberg#52a94d3d279f ''Forbes'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [http://www.newsweek.com/topic/jens-stoltenberg ''Newsweek'' magazine: Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.newyorker.com/search?q=jens+stoltenberg ''The New Yorker'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/s/jens_stoltenberg/index.html ''The New York Times'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.wsj.com/search/term.html?KEYWORDS=jens%20stoltenberg ''The Wall Street Journal'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n* [https://www.ft.com/search?q=jens+stoltenberg ''Financial Times'': Jens Stoltenberg]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Egil Knudsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Workers' Youth League (Norway)|Workers' Youth League]]|years=1985\u20131989}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Turid Birkeland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]|years=2002\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonas Gahr St\u00f8re]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Finn Kristensen]]|as=Minister of Industry}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Trade and Industry (Norway)|Minister of Industry and Energy]]|years=1993\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Grete Knudsen]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigbj\u00f8rn Johnsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]|years=1996\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gudmund Restad]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]]|years=2000\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kjell Magne Bondevik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]]|years=2005\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Erna Solberg]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary General of NATO]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{NATOSecGens}}\n{{Current NATO leaders}}\n{{Norwegian Labour Party}}\n{{Stoltenberg cabinet}}\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{NorwegianFinancialMinisters}}\n{{Stortinget 2001-2005}}\n{{Stortinget 2009-2013}}\n{{Stortinget 2013-2017}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stoltenberg, Jens}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (Norway)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Finance of Norway]]\n[[Category:Norwegian agnostics]]\n[[Category:Norwegian economists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oslo Cathedral School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oslo Waldorf School]]\n[[Category:People from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 1st Class]]\n[[Category:Secretaries General of NATO]]\n[[Category:Stoltenberg family|Jens]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n", "name_user": "186.185.165.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eControversies:Added definite controversies.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jens_Stoltenberg"}
{"title_page": "Jennifer Finch", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jennifer Finch\n| image            = Jennifer-precious finch.jpg\n| caption          = Finch performing in the 1990s\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Jennifer Precious Finch\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1966|8|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = Los Angeles, United States|\n| years_active     = 1979\u2013present\n| occupation       = musician, [[blogger (person)|blogger]], photographer\n| instrument       = [[Bass guitar]]\n| genre            = [[Alternative metal]], [[grunge]], [[punk rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[L7 (band)|L7]]<br> [[Sugar Babydoll]]<br>[[The Pandoras]]<br>OtherStarPeople<br>[[Betty Blowtorch]]<br>[[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]]\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Finch''' (also '''Jennifer Precious Finch'''), born August 5, 1966, is an American musician, designer, and photographer most notable for being the primary [[Bass guitar|bass player]] of the punk rock band [[L7 (band)|L7]].  Active in L7 from 1986 to 1996, Finch also wrote music and performed with her bands OtherStarPeople and [[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]] in the interim before joining the reunited L7 in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nFinch was born August 5, 1966 and grew up in [[West Los Angeles]]. She was adopted in 1967 by Robert Edward Finch, an aeronautics engineer, and his wife Sandra Jacobson; they later divorced in 1974<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jenniferfinch.com/jennifer-finch-about/|title=About Jennifer Precious Finch|last=|first=|date=|website=JenniferFinch.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Finch credits the support of her adoptive father, who was also an amateur photographer, as being instrumental to her creative development.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3b5nw5/bed-and-breakfast-and-fisting-v18n8|title=Jennifer Finch's Scrapbook|last=M\u00e9rigeot-Magnenat|first=Clarisse|date=March 25, 2011|work=Vice|access-date=September 7, 2019|last2=M\u00e9rigeot-Magnenat|first2=Pauline}}</ref> Finch took an interest in photography at an early age and attended a summer art session at [[Otis College of Art and Design|Otis Parsons]] in 1980.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.laweekly.com/14-and-shooting/|title=14 and Shooting|last=Albert|first=John|date=November 1, 2006|work=LA Weekly|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> She briefly appears in the crowd of [[The Germs]] performance in the 1981 film, [[The Decline of Western Civilization]].\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nFinch began her musical career in the mid 1980s.  She played bass in the San Francisco-based band [[Sugar Babydoll|Sugar Baby Doll]] (or Sugar Babylon) from 1984 - 1986.<ref>{{Cite book|title=We Were Going to Change the World: Interviews with Women from the 1970s and 1980s Southern California Punk Rock Scene|last=Russo|first=Stacy|publisher=Santa Monica Press|year=2017|isbn=9781595807953|location=Solana Beach, California|pages=}}</ref> The band featured [[Courtney Love]], future founder of [[Hole (band)|Hole]], and future [[Babes in Toyland (band)|Babes in Toyland]] founder [[Kat Bjelland]].<ref name=\":4\"/> This line-up produced a demo recording which remains unreleased.<ref>[http://www.katbjelland.com/sugarbabylon/indexsugar.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060424141441/http://www.katbjelland.com/sugarbabylon/indexsugar.html |date=April 24, 2006 }}</ref> Finch subsequently played in the short-lived Hollywood band [[The Pandoras]], formed by bassist Gwynne Kahn.\n\nIn 1986, Finch joined the Los Angeles-based punk rock group L7, as the bass guitar player and additional vocalist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pleasekillme.com/jennifer-precious-finch-l7/|title=One More Thing - Catching Up with L7's Jennifer Precious Finch|last=Jasmine|first=Lucreita Tye|date=August 28, 2019|work=Please Kill Me|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>  In the documentary film L7: Pretend We\u2019re Dead, bandmate [[Donita Sparks]] described Finch as \"persistent\" and stated that after Finch joined the band, her networking skills and stage energy continued to significantly boost the momentum building within the group.  She remained with L7 throughout the band's most successful period in the early 1990s.  Finch contributed to the albums ''[[L7 (album)|L7]]'' (1988) ''[[Smell the Magic]]''(1990), ''[[Bricks Are Heavy]]'' (1992), and ''[[Hungry for Stink]]'' (1994).  Finch was the sole songwriter during this period for several of L7's songs including \"(Right On) Thru\", \"[[Everglade (song)|Everglade]]\", \"One More Thing\", and \"Shirley\".\n\nIn 1994, Finch and her L7 bandmate [[Demetra Plakas|Demetra \"Dee\" Plakas]] performed with Japanese musician [[Hide (musician)|Hide]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IqPSqDVZOP0 |title=hide \u2013 Eyes Love You (live POP JAM 1993.08.11) |publisher=YouTube |date=December 3, 2007 |accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-feature-l7/|title=Spill Feature: L7|last=Dean|first=Mark|date=September 20, 2016|work=The Spill Magazine|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> also appearing in the original video for his song \"[[50% & 50%|Doubt]]\".<ref name=\"asouvenir\">As seen on [[Hide (musician)|Hide]]'s home video release, ''A Souvenir''.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Finch was featured in a music video for [[Hole (band)|Hole]] for their breakthrough album ''[[Live Through This]]'', as the original bassist [[Kristen Pfaff]] had died of an over-dose in June of that year. In 1995, after the death of her father, Finch adopted the name \"Precious\" as an homage to him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jenniferfinch.com/music-history/ |title=Music History |access-date=April 5, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070241/http://jenniferfinch.com/music-history/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Finch officially departed L7 in 1996, though the reasons are unclear.\n\nAfter departing from L7, Finch wrote music and sang for her band OtherStarPeople with Xander Smith.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/other-star-people-mn0000496306/biography|title=Biography: Other Star People|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=|work=All Music|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />  OtherStarPeople completed their debut record ''Diamonds In The Belly Of The Dog'' in 1998;  the group were signed with [[A&M Records]]/[[Interscope Records|Interscope]] and the album was released in August 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/29h04.html|title=Interview: OtherStarPeople|last=Steininger|first=Alex|date=March 2000|work=In Music We Trust|access-date=September 7, 2019|issue=29}}</ref> [[Joshua Clover]] of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine described the OtherStarPeople record as bringing \"less weight and more strangeness than Finch's old crew - it's L.A.-slick and punky-dirty\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clover|first=Joshua|date=August 1999|title=Reviews: The Shredder|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQRXCTo-FtUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Spin|volume=15|pages=157|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFinch was also involved with [[Betty Blowtorch]], appearing in the 2003 documentary film Betty Blowtorch And Her Amazing True Life Adventures.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFinch founded the punk rock group [[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]] in Los Angeles in 2002.  The band played dates on the [[Warped Tour]] in 2003 and 2005.  The Shocker released ''Up Your Ass Tray as'' an EP in 2003, followed by a full-length album in 2006 on [[Go-Kart Records]].  Finch served as the sole songwriter and primary singer of The Shocker through 2006.\n\nIn January 2011, Finch co-founded new band Sex in Progress along with Evie Evil of [[Evil Beaver (band)|Evil Beaver]].\n\nFinch produced a [[Ramones]]' tribute album<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Brats-On-The-Beat-Ramones-For-Kids/release/3423544|title=Brats on the Beat: Ramones for Kids|last=|first=|date=November 2006|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Brats on the Beat]]'' for the [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]. The album features \"kid friendly\" versions of Ramones' songs with guest vocals and music provided by various [[Punk rock|punk]] musicians.<ref name=\":5\" />\n[[File:L7 - Rock am Ring 2015-9409.jpg|thumb|Finch performing with L7 in 2015]]\nIn 2014, L7 reformed with the primary line up of Finch with [[Suzi Gardner]], [[Donita Sparks]] , and [[Demetra Plakas|Dee Plakas]].  They toured extensively and released new singles in 2017 and 2018.\n\nL7's latest full album ''[[Scatter the Rats]]'' was released on [[Blackheart Records]] on May 3, 2019 to generally favorable reviews.  Finch wrote the song \"Garbage Truck\".  The band resumed a six-week national tour starting on May 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.laweekly.com/music/scatter-rats-l7s-back-10150065|title=Scatter, Rats! L7's Back With Their First Album in 20 Years|last=Callwood|first=Brett|date=May 1, 2019|work=L.A. Weekly|access-date=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Photography===\nAt the age of 13, Finch began to take photos of her friends in Los Angeles on a camera given to her by her father. These pictures eventually documented the early punk scene that she became involved in before joining L7 in 1986. Her photography (1979\u20131995) was on display at an ''[[LA Weekly]]'' sponsored art show at Aidan Ryley Taylor Gallery in Hollywood, until November 18, 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> The collection, called \"14 and Shooting\" features a number of notable figures, including photographs of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers|The Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Red Kross]], and [[The Cramps]].  John Albert of ''LA Weekly'' reflected that Finch's images often depict the musicians in more intimate moments as well as providing a generally dark perspective of youth in Southern California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/14andshooting |title=Myspace |publisher=Myspace |date= |accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref>  Finch's photographs traveled to the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] for display in January 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whitehotmagazine.com/articles/2010-interview-jennifer-precious-finch/2053|title=Interview: Jennifer Precious Finch|last=Forson|first=Kofi|date=April 2010|work=White Hot Magazine|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Television and film===\nFinch has acted in the 1984 film ''[[The Census Taker]]'' and in the 1994 [[John Waters]] film ''[[Serial Mom]]'' as part of the fictitious band the Camel Lips.<ref name=\":1\" />  Finch appeared as herself in the 2007 documentary ''[[Punk's Not Dead (2007 film)|Punk's Not Dead]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Her music was featured in the 1999 film [[Office Space]] and on the popular TV series ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0277419/|title=Jennifer Finch|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFinch appears in interviews and original footage throughout the documentary film ''L7: Pretend We're Dead'', directed by [[Sarah Price (filmmaker)|Sarah Price]] and released in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6288290/|title=L7: Pretend We're Dead (2016)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>  The film was nominated for a VO5 NME Award for Best Music Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/l7-reveal-tour-slam-capitalist-motherf--kers-on-new-song-w516529|title=L7 Announce Tour, Slam 'Capitalist Motherf--kers' on 'I Came Back To Bitch'|last=Grant|first=Sarah|date=February 9, 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the early 90s, Finch dated [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s [[Dave Grohl]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://bigtakeover.com/profiles/finch-takes-flight-again-a-profile-of-l7-s-jennifer-finch|title=Finch Takes Flight Again: A Profile Of L7's Jennifer Finch|last=Rosenschein|first=Ari|date=November 22, 2015|work=The Big Take Over|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> and later [[Billy Corgan]] of [[The Smashing Pumpkins]]. She was married to actor, musician and race car driver [[Chris Pedersen (actor)|Chris Pedersen]] from 2000\u20132007.  Finch resides in [[Culver City, California|Culver City]], California.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stompandstammer.com/feature-stories/l7/|title=L7|last=Clark|first=Jeff|date=August 2, 2016|website=Stomp and Stammer Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===L7===\n*[[L7 (album)|''L7'']] (1988)\n*''[[Smell the Magic]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Bricks are Heavy]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Hungry for Stink]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Scatter the Rats]]'' (2019)\n\n===OtherStarPeople===\n*''Diamonds in The Belly of The Dog'' (1999)\n\n===The Shocker===\n*''Up Your Ass Tray'' EP ([[Oglio Records]], 2003)\n*''Up Your Ass Tray: The Full Length'' ([[Go-Kart Records|Go Kart]], 2006)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jenniferfinchphoto.com/ Jennifer Finch Photography]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/bratsonthebeat Ramones for Kids website]\n\n{{L7}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finch, Jennifer}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American punk rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Female bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Female punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:L7 (band) members]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Riot grrrl musicians]]\n[[Category:American abortion-rights activists]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American female guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jennifer Finch\n| image            = Jennifer-precious finch.jpg\n| caption          = Finch performing in the 1990s\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Jennifer Precious Finch\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1966|8|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = Los Angeles, United States|\n| years_active     = 1979\u2013present\n| occupation       = musician, [[blogger (person)|blogger]], photographer\n| instrument       = [[Bass guitar]]\n| genre            = [[Alternative metal]], [[grunge]], [[punk rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[L7 (band)|L7]]<br> [[Sugar Babydoll]]<br>[[The Pandoras]]<br>OtherStarPeople<br>[[Betty Blowtorch]]<br>[[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]]\n| website          = \n}}\n'''Jennifer Finch''' (also '''Jennifer Precious Finch'''), born August 5, 1966, is an American musician, designer, and photographer most notable for being the primary [[Bass guitar|bass player]] of the punk rock band [[L7 (band)|L7]].  Active in L7 from 1986 to 1996, Finch also wrote music and performed with her bands OtherStarPeople and [[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]] in the interim before joining the reunited L7 in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nFinch was born August 5, 1966 and grew up in [[West Los Angeles]]. She was adopted in 1967 by Robert Edward Finch, an aeronautics engineer, and his wife Sandra Jacobson; they later divorced in 1974<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jenniferfinch.com/jennifer-finch-about/|title=About Jennifer Precious Finch|last=|first=|date=|website=JenniferFinch.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> Finch credits the support of her adoptive father, who was also an amateur photographer, as being instrumental to her creative development.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/3b5nw5/bed-and-breakfast-and-fisting-v18n8|title=Jennifer Finch's Scrapbook|last=M\u00e9rigeot-Magnenat|first=Clarisse|date=March 25, 2011|work=Vice|access-date=September 7, 2019|last2=M\u00e9rigeot-Magnenat|first2=Pauline}}</ref> Finch took an interest in photography at an early age and attended a summer art session at [[Otis College of Art and Design|Otis Parsons]] in 1980.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.laweekly.com/14-and-shooting/|title=14 and Shooting|last=Albert|first=John|date=November 1, 2006|work=LA Weekly|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> She briefly appears in the crowd of [[The Germs]] performance in the 1981 film, [[The Decline of Western Civilization]].\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nFinch began her musical career in the mid 1980s.  She played bass in the San Francisco-based band [[Sugar Babydoll|Sugar Baby Doll]] (or Sugar Babylon) from 1984 - 1986.<ref>{{Cite book|title=We Were Going to Change the World: Interviews with Women from the 1970s and 1980s Southern California Punk Rock Scene|last=Russo|first=Stacy|publisher=Santa Monica Press|year=2017|isbn=9781595807953|location=Solana Beach, California|pages=}}</ref> The band featured [[Courtney Love]], future founder of [[Hole (band)|Hole]], and future [[Babes in Toyland (band)|Babes in Toyland]] founder [[Kat Bjelland]].<ref name=\":4\"/> This line-up produced a demo recording which remains unreleased.<ref>[http://www.katbjelland.com/sugarbabylon/indexsugar.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060424141441/http://www.katbjelland.com/sugarbabylon/indexsugar.html |date=April 24, 2006 }}</ref> Finch subsequently played in the short-lived Hollywood band [[The Pandoras]], formed by bassist Gwynne Kahn.\n\nIn 1986, Finch joined the Los Angeles based punk rock group L7, as the bass guitar player and additional vocalist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pleasekillme.com/jennifer-precious-finch-l7/|title=One More Thing - Catching Up with L7's Jennifer Precious Finch|last=Jasmine|first=Lucreita Tye|date=August 28, 2019|work=Please Kill Me|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>  In the documentary film L7: Pretend We\u2019re Dead, band mate [[Donita Sparks]] described Finch as \u201cpersistent\u201d and stated that after Finch joined the band, her networking skills and stage energy continued to significantly boost the momentum building within the group.  She remained with L7 throughout the band's most successful period in the early 1990s.  Finch contributed to the albums ''[[L7 (album)|L7]]'' (1988) ''[[Smell the Magic]]''(1990), ''[[Bricks Are Heavy]]'' (1992), and ''[[Hungry for Stink]]'' (1994).  Finch was the sole songwriter during this period for several of L7\u2019s songs including \"(Right On) Thru\", \u201c[[Everglade (song)|Everglade]]\u201d, \"One More Thing\", and \u201cShirley\u201d.\n\nIn 1994, Finch and her L7 band mate [[Demetra Plakas|Demetra \"Dee\" Plakas]] performed with Japanese musician [[Hide (musician)|Hide]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IqPSqDVZOP0 |title=hide \u2013 Eyes Love You (live POP JAM 1993.08.11) |publisher=YouTube |date=December 3, 2007 |accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://spillmagazine.com/spill-feature-l7/|title=Spill Feature: L7|last=Dean|first=Mark|date=September 20, 2016|work=The Spill Magazine|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> also appearing in the original video for his song \"[[50% & 50%|Doubt]]\".<ref name=\"asouvenir\">As seen on [[Hide (musician)|Hide]]'s home video release, ''A Souvenir''.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Finch was featured in a music video for [[Hole (band)|Hole]] for their breakthrough album ''[[Live Through This]]'', as the original bassist [[Kristen Pfaff]] had died of an over-dose in June of that year. In 1995, after the death of her father, Finch adopted the name \"Precious\" as an homage to him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jenniferfinch.com/music-history/ |title=Music History |access-date=April 5, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070241/http://jenniferfinch.com/music-history/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Finch officially departed L7 in 1996, though the reasons are unclear.\n\nAfter departing from L7, Finch wrote music and sang for her band OtherStarPeople with Xander Smith.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/other-star-people-mn0000496306/biography|title=Biography: Other Star People|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=|work=All Music|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" />  OtherStarPeople completed their debut record ''Diamonds In The Belly Of The Dog'' in 1998;  the group were signed with [[A&M Records]]/[[Interscope Records|Interscope]] and the album was released in August 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/29h04.html|title=Interview: OtherStarPeople|last=Steininger|first=Alex|date=March 2000|work=In Music We Trust|access-date=September 7, 2019|issue=29}}</ref> [[Joshua Clover]] of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine described the OtherStarPeople record as bringing \"less weight and more strangeness than Finch's old crew - it's L.A.-slick and punky-dirty\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clover|first=Joshua|date=August 1999|title=Reviews: The Shredder|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQRXCTo-FtUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Spin|volume=15|pages=157|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nFinch was also involved with [[Betty Blowtorch]], appearing in the 2003 documentary film Betty Blowtorch And Her Amazing True Life Adventures.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFinch founded the punk rock group [[The Shocker (band)|The Shocker]] in Los Angeles in 2002.  The band played dates on the [[Warped Tour]] in 2003 and 2005.  The Shocker released ''Up Your Ass Tray as'' an EP in 2003, followed by a full-length album in 2006 on [[Go-Kart Records]].  Finch served as the sole songwriter and primary singer of The Shocker through 2006.\n\nIn January 2011, Finch co-founded new band Sex in Progress along with Evie Evil of [[Evil Beaver (band)|Evil Beaver]].\n\nFinch produced a [[Ramones]]' tribute album<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Brats-On-The-Beat-Ramones-For-Kids/release/3423544|title=Brats on the Beat: Ramones for Kids|last=|first=|date=November 2006|website=Discogs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Brats on the Beat]]'' for the [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]]. The album features \"kid friendly\" versions of Ramones' songs with guest vocals and music provided by various [[Punk rock|punk]] musicians.<ref name=\":5\" />\n[[File:L7 - Rock am Ring 2015-9409.jpg|thumb|Finch performing with L7 in 2015]]\nIn 2014, L7 reformed with the primary line up of Finch with [[Suzi Gardner]], [[Donita Sparks]] , and [[Demetra Plakas|Dee Plakas]].  They toured extensively and released new singles in 2017 and 2018.\n\nL7's latest full album ''[[Scatter the Rats]]'' was released on [[Blackheart Records]] on May 3, 2019 to generally favorable reviews.  Finch wrote the song \u201cGarbage Truck\u201d.  The band resumed a six week national tour starting on May 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.laweekly.com/music/scatter-rats-l7s-back-10150065|title=Scatter, Rats! L7's Back With Their First Album in 20 Years|last=Callwood|first=Brett|date=May 1, 2019|work=L.A. Weekly|access-date=May 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Photography===\nAt the age of 13, Finch began to take photos of her friends in Los Angeles on a camera given to her by her father. These pictures eventually documented the early punk scene that she became involved in before joining L7 in 1986. Her photography (1979\u20131995) was on display at an ''[[LA Weekly]]'' sponsored art show at Aidan Ryley Taylor Gallery in Hollywood, until November 18, 2006.<ref name=\":0\" /> The collection, called \"14 and Shooting\" features a number of notable figures, including photographs of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers|The Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Red Kross]], and [[The Cramps]].  John Albert of ''LA Weekly'' reflected that Finch's images often depict the musicians in more intimate moments as well as providing a generally dark perspective of youth in Southern California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/14andshooting |title=Myspace |publisher=Myspace |date= |accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref>  Finch\u2019s photographs traveled to the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] for display in January 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whitehotmagazine.com/articles/2010-interview-jennifer-precious-finch/2053|title=Interview: Jennifer Precious Finch|last=Forson|first=Kofi|date=April 2010|work=White Hot Magazine|access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Television and film===\nFinch has acted in the 1984 film ''[[The Census Taker]]'' and in the 1994 [[John Waters]] film ''[[Serial Mom]]'' as part of the fictitious band the Camel Lips.<ref name=\":1\" />  Finch appeared as herself in the 2007 documentary ''[[Punk's Not Dead (2007 film)|Punk's Not Dead]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Her music was featured in the 1999 film [[Office Space]] and on the popular TV series ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'' in 2008.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0277419/|title=Jennifer Finch|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFinch appears in interviews and original footage throughout the documentary film ''L7: Pretend We're Dead'', directed by [[Sarah Price (filmmaker)|Sarah Price]] and released in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6288290/|title=L7: Pretend We're Dead (2016)|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>  The film was nominated for a VO5 NME Award for Best Music Film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/l7-reveal-tour-slam-capitalist-motherf--kers-on-new-song-w516529|title=L7 Announce Tour, Slam 'Capitalist Motherf--kers' on 'I Came Back To Bitch'|last=Grant|first=Sarah|date=February 9, 2018|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the early 90s, Finch dated [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s [[Dave Grohl]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://bigtakeover.com/profiles/finch-takes-flight-again-a-profile-of-l7-s-jennifer-finch|title=Finch Takes Flight Again: A Profile Of L7's Jennifer Finch|last=Rosenschein|first=Ari|date=November 22, 2015|work=The Big Take Over|access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref> and later [[Billy Corgan]] of [[The Smashing Pumpkins]]. She was married to actor, musician and race car driver [[Chris Pedersen (actor)|Chris Pedersen]] from 2000-2007.  Finch resides in [[Culver City, California|Culver City]], California.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stompandstammer.com/feature-stories/l7/|title=L7|last=Clark|first=Jeff|date=August 2, 2016|website=Stomp and Stammer Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===L7===\n*[[L7 (album)|''L7'']] (1988)\n*''[[Smell the Magic]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Bricks are Heavy]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Hungry for Stink]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Scatter the Rats]]'' (2019)\n\n===OtherStarPeople===\n*''Diamonds in The Belly of The Dog'' (1999)\n\n===The Shocker===\n*''Up Your Ass Tray'' EP ([[Oglio Records]], 2003)\n*''Up Your Ass Tray: The Full Length'' ([[Go-Kart Records|Go Kart]], 2006)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jenniferfinchphoto.com/ Jennifer Finch Photography]\n*[http://www.myspace.com/bratsonthebeat Ramones for Kids website]\n\n{{L7}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{D