nstrumentarium''. Saarbr\u00fccken: Pfau-Verlag.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Steenhuisen|2009}}|reference=Steenhuisen, Paul. 2009.  \"Interview with Mauricio Kagel\". In [https://web.archive.org/web/20141015151345/http://www.uap.ualberta.ca/UAP.asp?LID=41&bookID=687 ''Sonic Mosaics: Conversations with Composers'']. Edmonton:  University of Alberta Press. {{ISBN|978-0-88864-474-9}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Young|2011}}|reference=Young, Logan K. 2011. ''Mauricio Kagel: A Semic Life''. Washington, D.C.: T(W)E(L)V(E)! BOOKS. {{ISBN|1-257-37563-6}}.}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mauricio-kagel.com/gb/biografy.html Mauricio Kagel] website, biography\n* [http://www.universaledition.com/Mauricio-Kagel/composers-and-works/composer/349 Mauricio Kagel] biography and works on the UE website (publisher)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060206095346/http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Users/bh25/kagel.htm Mauricio Kagel site by Bj\u00f6rn Heile]\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio3/cutandsplice/kagel.shtml Kagel Biography by BBC Radio 3 programme Cut and Splice].\n*[http://www.ubu.com/film/kagel.html Mauricio Kagel at UbuWeb Film] presents various Kagel films, including the full version of ''Ludwig Van'', available for free download.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061103051251/http://www.avantgardeproject.org/AGP2/index.htm Kagel's ''Acustica'' at the Avant Garde Project] has FLAC files made from a high-quality LP transcription available for free download.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041210161741/http://www.edition-peters.com/kagel/ Edition Peters: Mauricio Kagel] October 1998.\n*[http://www.beckmesser.de/neue_musik/kagel/int-e.html Interview: There Will Always Be Questions Enough] Mauricio Kagel in conversation with Max Nyffeler.\n*[http://www.ubu.com/sound/kagel.html UbuWeb: Mauricio Kagel] featuring ''Der Schall'' (1968) and ''ACUSTICA'' for experimental sound-producers and loud-speakers.\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/19/AR2008091903900.html ''Washington Post'' obit] by Anne Midgette.\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/sep/19/obituary.mauricio.kagel?gusrc=rss&feed=music ''Guardian'' obit] by Adrian Jack.\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/20/arts/music/20kagel.html?_r=1&oref=slogin ''New York Times'' obituary] by William Grimes.\n{{ContemporaryMusicOnline|Kagel|works}}\n* {{BrahmsOnline|1786}}\n*[http://www.bruceduffie.com/kagel.html Interview with Mauricio Kagel], November 2, 1992\n\n{{Darmstadt School}}\n{{Electronic music}}\n{{Modernist composers}}\n{{Ernst von Siemens Music Prize}}\n{{Schock Prize laureates}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kagel, Mauricio}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Argentine musicians]]\n[[Category:Argentine classical composers]]\n[[Category:German classical composers]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Grammophon artists]]\n[[Category:Rolf Schock Prize laureates]]\n[[Category:Argentine emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:Argentine Jews]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:German Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German composers]]\n[[Category:Ernst von Siemens Music Prize winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century German composers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Mauricio Kagel (1985).jpg|thumb|Mauricio Kagel, 1985]]\n'''Mauricio Ra\u00fal Kagel''' ({{IPA-es|mau\u02c8\u027eisjo \u02c8ka\u0263el}}; December 24, 1931 \u2013 September 18, 2008) was a [[Germans|German]]-[[Argentina|Argentine]] [[composer]] notable for developing the [[theatrical]] side of musical [[performance]] {{harv|Grimshaw|2009}}. He spent his last fifty years in Germany, dying after a long illness at the age of 76 {{harv|Nonnenmann|2008}}.\n\n==Biography==\nKagel was born in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], into an Ashkenazi Jewish family that had fled from Russia in the 1920s {{harv|Anon.|n.d.}}. He studied music, history of [[literature]], and [[philosophy]] in [[Buenos Aires]] {{harv|Grimshaw|2009}}. In 1957 he moved as a scholar to [[Cologne]], Germany, where he lived until his death.\n\n===As teacher===\n\nFrom 1960\u201366 and 1972\u201376 he taught at the [[Darmst\u00e4dter Ferienkurse|International Summer School at Darmstadt]] {{harv|Attinello|2001}}. He also taught from 1964\u201365 at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]] as [[Slee Professor of music theory]]. At the [[Deutsche Film- und Fernsehakademie Berlin|Berlin Film and Television Academy]] he was a visiting lecturer. He served as director of courses for new music in [[Gothenburg]] and Cologne {{harv|Attinello|2001}}. He was professor for new music theatre at the [[Cologne Conservatory]] from 1974\u201397.<!--Attinello 2001 would cover this as well, except he does not give the terminal date.--> Among his students were [[Maria de Alvear]], [[Carola Bauckholt]], [[Branimir Krsti\u0107]], [[David Sawer]], {{ill|Rickard Scheffer|sv}}, [[Juan Maria Solare]], [[Gerald Barry (composer)|Gerald Barry]], and [[Chao-Ming Tung]]. {{See LMST|Mauricio|Kagel}}\n\n===As composer===\n\nSome of his pieces give specific theatrical instructions to the performers {{harv|Kennedy and Bourne|2006}}, such as to adopt certain facial expressions while playing, to make their stage entrances in a particular way, to physically interact with other performers, and so on. For this reason commentators at times related his work to the [[Theatre of the Absurd]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} He has been regarded by music historians as deploying a critical intelligence interrogating the position of music in society {{harv|Griffiths|1978|loc=188}}.<!--Is this a quote or paraphrase?--> He was also active in the fields of film and photography, proving that the possibilities of music are inexhaustible.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}} In 1991 Kagel was invited by [[Walter Fink]] as the second composer featured in the annual [[Rheingau Musik Festival#Portraits of living composers|Komponistenportr\u00e4t]] of the [[Rheingau Musik Festival]]. In 2000 he received the [[Ernst von Siemens Music Prize]].\n\n==Works==\n''Staatstheater'' (1970) remains, probably, Kagel\u2019s best-known work. It is the piece that most clearly shows his absurdist tendency.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}} He described it as a \u201c[[ballet]] for non-dancers,\u201d{{Cite quote|date=September 2008}} although it is in many ways more like an [[opera]]; the devices it uses as [[musical instrument]]s include [[chamber pot]]s and [[enema]] equipment. As the work progresses, the piece itself, and opera and ballet in general, becomes its own subject matter.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\nSimilar is the [[radio]] [[Play (theatre)|play]] ''Ein Aufnahmezustand'' (1969) which is about the incidents surrounding the recording of a radio play. In ''Con voce'' (With Voice), a masked trio silently mimes playing instruments. ''Match'' (1964), is a \u201ctennis game\u201d for cellists with a percussionist as umpire {{harv|Griffiths|1978|loc=188}} (for [[Siegfried Palm]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}<!--Formerly offered citation, [http://www.bertdekkers.nl/klassiek/kagel_list.html Kagel: Match], lists a recording made by Palm, but does not confirm the work was written for him.-->), also the subject of one of Kagel's films and perhaps the best-known of his works of instrumental theatre {{harv|Griffiths|1981|loc=812}}.\n\nBut Kagel wrote a large number of more conventional \u201cpure\u201d pieces too, including [[orchestra]]l music, [[chamber music]]. Many of these make references to music of the past by, among others, Beethoven, Brahms, Bach and Liszt ({{harvnb|Warnaby|1986|loc=38}}; {{harvnb|Decarsin|1985|loc=260}}).\n\nKagel also made [[film]]s, with one of the best known being ''[[Ludwig van (film)|Ludwig van]]'' (1970), a critical interrogation of the uses of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s music made during the bicentenary of that composer's birth {{harv|Griffiths|1978|loc=188}}. In it, a reproduction of Beethoven's studio is seen, as part of a fictive visit of the [[Beethoven House]] in [[Bonn]]. Everything in it is papered with sheet music of Beethoven's pieces. The soundtrack of the film is a [[piano]] playing the music as it appears in each shot. Because the music has been wrapped around curves and edges, it is somewhat distorted, but Beethovenian motifs can still be heard. In other parts, the film contains parodies of radio or TV broadcasts connected with the \"Beethoven Year 1770\". Kagel later turned the film into a piece of sheet music itself which could be performed in a concert without the film\u2014the score consists of close-ups of various areas of the studio, which are to be interpreted by the performing [[pianist]].\n\n===For orchestra===\n\n* ''Dos piezas'' for orchestra (1952)\n* ''Heterophonie'' for orchestra (1959\u201361)\n* ''Zehn M\u00e4rsche, um den Sieg zu verfehlen'' (Ten marches in order to miss victory), for brass orchestra (1979)\n* ''Les id\u00e9es fixes'', rondo for orchestra (1988/89)\n* ''Opus 1.991'' for orchestra (1990)\n* ''Konzertst\u00fcck'' ([[Concert piece]]), for timpani and orchestra (1990\u201392)\n* ''\u00c9tudes'' for orchestra (I 1992, II 1995/96, III 1996)\n* ''Fremde T\u00f6ne & Widerhall'' (Strange sounds and echo), for orchestra (2005)\n\n===Chamber music===\n\n* [[String Sextet (Kagel)|String Sextet]] (1953\u201357)\n* ''Transici\u00f3n II'' for piano, percussion, and two tapes (1958\u201359)\n* ''Sonant'' for guitar, harp, contrabass, and skin instruments (1960)\n* ''Match'' for three players (two celli and percussionist-umpire) (1964)\n* ''Musik f\u00fcr Renaissance-Instrumente'', for two up to twenty-two instruments (1965\u201366)\n* String Quartets Nos. 1 and 2 (1965\u201367)\n* ''Der Schall'' for five players performing on 54 plucked-string, percussion, and wind instruments (1968)\n* ''Acustica'' for experimental sound-producers and loud-speakers (1968\u201370)\n* ''Morceau de concours'' for 1 or 2 trumpets (1968\u201372)\n* ''Dressur'', trio for wood percussion (1977)\n* ''Rrrrrrr...'', six duos for two percussionists (1982)\n* ''Pan'' a tutti i Papagheni, for piccolo and string quartet (1985)\n* Piano Trio No. 1 (1985)\n* String Quartet No. 3 (1986)\n* ''Aus dem Nachlass'', pieces for viola, cello, and contrabass (1986)\n* ''Phantasiest\u00fcck'' for flute and piano (1989)\n* String Quartet No. 4 (1993)\n* ''Schattenkl\u00e4nge'', three pieces for bass clarinet (1995)\n* ''Art bruit'' for a percussionist and an assistant (1994/95)\n* Piano Trio No. 2 (2001)\n\n===Vocal works===\n\n* ''F\u00fcrst Igor \u2013 Strawinsky'', a requiem for [[Igor Strawinsky]] for bass and instruments (1982)\n* ''[[Sankt-Bach-Passion]]'' for soloists, choirs and orchestra (premiered in 1985)\n* ''Mitternachtsst\u00fck'' for voices and instruments on four fragments from the diary of [[Robert Schumann]] (1980\u201381/86)\n* ''Schwarzes Madrigal'' (Black madrigal), for choir, trumpet, tuba and 2 percussionists (1998/99)\n* ''In der Matratzengruft'' for tenor and ensemble (2008)\n\n===Stage works===\n\n* ''Staatstheater'' (1967/70)\n* ''Mare nostrum'', Scenic Play for countertenor, baritone, flute, oboe, guitar, harp, cello and percussion (1975)\n* ''Kantrimiusik'', pastorale for voices and instruments (1975)\n* ''Music-Epic about the Devil \u201cLa trahison orale\u201d'' (1983)\n\n===Film===\n\n* ''Ludwig van'' (1969)\n\n==References==\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Anon.|n.d.}}|reference=Anon. n.d. \"[http://www.mauricio-kagel.com/gb/biografy.html# Mauricio Kagel, 1931\u20132008]\". Mauricio Kagel website. (Accessed 21 September 2010).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Attinello|2001}}|reference=Attinello, Paul. 2001. \"Kagel, Mauricio.\" ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Decarsin|1985}}|reference=Decarsin, Fran\u00e7ois. 1985. \"Liszt's ''Nuages gris'' and Kagel's ''Unguis incarnatus est'': A Model and Its Issue\", translated by Jonathan Dunsby. ''Music Analysis'' 4, no. 3:259\u201363.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Griffiths|1978}}|reference=[[Paul Griffiths (writer)|Griffiths, Paul]]. 1978. ''A Concise History of Modern Music: From Debussy to Boulez''. London: Thames and Hudson. {{ISBN|0-500-18167-5}}. (Originally published as ''A Concise History of Avant-garde Music: from Debussy to Boulez''. New York: Oxford University Press, 1978. {{ISBN|0-19-520044-6}} (cloth), {{ISBN|0-19-520045-4}} (pbk.). Reissued as ''Modern Music: A Concise History from Debussy to Boulez''. New York: Thames and Hudson, 1985. {{ISBN|0-500-20164-1}}. Revised edition, as ''Modern Music: A Concise History''. New York: Thames and Hudson, 1994. {{ISBN|0-500-20278-8}}.)}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Griffiths|1981}}|reference=Griffiths, Paul. 1981. \"Unnecessary Music: Kagel at 50\". ''Musical Times'' 122:811\u201312.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Grimshaw|2009}}|reference=Grimshaw, Jeremy. 2009 \"[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=q7525/biography|pure_url=yes}} Mauricio Kagel]\". ''Allmusic'' website (accessed 24 January 2010).}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Heile|2006}}|reference=Heile, Bj\u00f6rn. 2006. ''The Music of Mauricio Kagel''. Aldershot, Hants; Burlington, VT: Ashgate. {{ISBN|0-7546-3523-6}}.}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kennedy and Bourne|2006}}|reference=[[Michael Kennedy (music critic)|Kennedy, Michael]], and Joyce Bourne Kennedy (eds.). 2006. \"Kagel, Mauricio\". ''The Oxford Dictionary of Music'', second edition, revised. Oxford, Toronto