s Shirley Feeney (voice)\n*1982: ''[[Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour]]'' (1 episode) as Shirley (voice)\n*1985: ''When Dreams Come True'' (TV Movie) as Susan Matthews\n*1986: ''Help Wanted: Kids'' as Lisa Burke\n*1986: ''The Leftovers'' as Heather Drew\n*1988: ''Save the Dog!'' (TV Movie) as Becky\n*1988: ''Tricks of the Trade'' (TV Movie) as Catherine\n*1990: ''[[Perry Mason (TV movies)|Perry Mason: The Case of the Poisoned Pen]]'' (TV Movie) as Rita Sue Bliss\n*1990: ''[[Normal Life (TV series)|Normal Life]]'' (13 episodes) as Anne Harlow\n*1990: ''Menu for Murder'' (TV Movie) as Connie Mann\n*1991: ''Earth Angel'' (TV Movie) as Judith\n*1993\u20131994: ''[[Getting By]]'' (31 episodes) as Cathy Hale\n*1994: ''[[Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'' as Wandamae\n*1995: ''[[Escape from Terror: The Teresa Stamper Story]]'' (TV Movie) as Wanda Walden\n*1995: ''The Laverne & Shirley Reunion'' as Herself\n*1995: ''[[The Magic School Bus (TV series)|The Magic School Bus]]'' (1 episode) as Gerri Poveri (voice)\n*1996: ''[[The Stepford Husbands]]'' (TV Movie) as Caroline Knox\n*1999: ''[[The Patty Duke Show#Reunion movie|The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights]]'' (TV Movie) as Sue Ellen Caldwell\n*2000\u20132001: ''[[Strip Mall]]'' (6 episodes) as Herself\n*2000\u20132002: ''[[For Your Love (TV series)|For Your Love]]'' (3 episodes) as Ronnie\n*2002: ''Laverne & Shirley Together Again'' (TV Movie) as Herself / Shirley Feeney\n*2003: ''[[8 Simple Rules]]'' as Mary Ellen Doyle\n*2004: ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as Nora Hodges\n*2007: ''[[Drive (2007 TV series)|Drive]]'' as House Mother\n*2012: ''Strawberry Summer'' (Hallmark name), ''Easy Heart'' (Pixl name) (TV Movie) as Ruth Yates\n*2013: ''[[Sam & Cat]]'' as Janice Dobbins\n*2016: ''[[The Odd Couple (2015 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' as Vivian\n*2016: ''A Dream of Christmas'' (TV Movie) as Jayne 'The Angel'\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|930286|Cindy Williams}}\n*{{emmytvlegends name|cindy-williams}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qchV2eC9oOQ Video] Discussion with Actress Cindy Williams at [[New York Film Academy]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Cindy}}\n\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Hudson family (show business)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles City College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Van Nuys, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cindy_Williams"}
{"title_page": "Brian Colvin (referee)", "text_new": "'''Brian Colvin''' (born 20 Sep 1978 in [[Scotland]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] referee for the [[Scottish Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/referees/brian-colvin/83725/|title=B. Colvin|website=soccerway.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colvin, Brian}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish football referees]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Brian Colvin''' (born 20 Sep 1978 in [[Scotland]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] referee for the [[Scottish Premier League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/referees/brian-colvin/83725/|title=B. Colvin|website=soccerway.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish football referees]]\n", "name_user": "DB1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "default sort", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Colvin_(referee)"}
{"title_page": "Pepe Reina", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish association football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Spanish name|Reina|P\u00e1ez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Pepe Reina\n| image          = Pepe Reina 2017.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Reina with [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in 2017\n| fullname       = Jos\u00e9 Manuel Reina P\u00e1ez<ref>{{cite web|title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of Players|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|accessdate=13 September 2013|page=29|format=PDF|date=4 June 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|8|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Madrid]], Spain\n| height         = 1.88 m<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sscnapoli.it/Team/Jose-Manuel-Reina | title = Jos\u00e8 ManuelReina | language = it | website = SSC Napoli | access-date = 2 July 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150703211407/http://www.sscnapoli.it/Team/Jose-Manuel-Reina | archive-date = 3 July 2015 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub    = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] (on loan from [[A.C. Milan|Milan]])\n| clubnumber     = 29\n| youthyears1    = 1988\u20131995\n| youthclubs1    = EF Madrid Oeste\n| youthyears2    = 1995\u20131999\n| youthclubs2    = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| years1         = 1999\n| clubs1         = [[FC Barcelona C|Barcelona C]]\n| caps1          = 3\n| goals1         = 0\n| years2         = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs2         = [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]]\n| caps2          = 41\n| goals2         = 0\n| years3         = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs3         = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| caps3          = 30\n| goals3         = 0\n| years4         = 2002\u20132005\n| clubs4         = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| caps4          = 109\n| goals4         = 0\n| years5         = 2005\u20132014\n| clubs5         = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps5          = 285\n| goals5         = 0\n| years6         = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs6         = \u2192 [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] (loan)\n| caps6          = 30\n| goals6         = 0\n| years7         = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs7         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n| caps7          = 3\n| goals7         = 0\n| years8         = 2015\u20132018\n| clubs8         = [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]]\n| caps8          = 111\n| goals8         = 0\n| years9         = 2018\u2013\n| clubs9         = [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]\n| caps9          = 5\n| goals9         = 0\n| years10        = 2020\u2013 \n| clubs10        = \u2192 [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] (loan)\n| caps10         = 6\n| goals10        = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20131999\n| nationalteam1  = [[Spain national under-16 football team|Spain U16]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1999\n| nationalteam2  = [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain U17]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2000\n| nationalteam3  = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 2\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2000\u20132003\n| nationalteam4  = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 20\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 2005\u20132018\n| nationalteam6  = [[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n| nationalcaps6  = 36\n| nationalgoals6 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2000\u20132002\n| nationalteam5  = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]]\n| nationalcaps5  = 2\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| club-update    = 23:14, 9 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 9 October 2017\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Manuel''' \"'''Pepe'''\" '''Reina P\u00e1ez''' ({{IPA-es|xo\u02c8se ma\u02c8nwel \u02c8pepe \u02c8rejna \u02c8pae\u03b8}}; born 31 August 1982) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for English club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on loan from [[A.C. Milan]].\n\nThe son of famed [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] goalkeeper [[Miguel Reina]], Pepe Reina began his career with the Barcelona youth team and made his [[La Liga]] debut in the [[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301 season]]. He signed for [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in 2002, winning the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]] twice. Reina moved on to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and made his debut in the [[2005 UEFA Super Cup]], which Liverpool won. He instantly became first-choice goalkeeper and went on to win both the [[FA Cup]] \u2013 where he saved three out of four [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] in [[2006 FA Cup Final|the final]] \u2013 and the [[FA Community Shield]]. In 2007, he reached the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League Final]] with Liverpool, matching the feat achieved by his father in 1974, but Liverpool lost to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]].\n\nFollowing eight consecutive seasons as Liverpool's first-choice keeper, Reina spent the 2013\u201314 season on loan at [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], where he was reunited with [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]], the coach who signed him to play for Liverpool in 2005. During his loan tenure in [[Naples]], Reina was part of the side that won the [[2014 Coppa Italia Final|2014]] [[Coppa Italia]]. Reina then completed a permanent move to [[FC Bayern M\u00fcnchen|Bayern Munich]] in 2014 upon returning to Napoli on a permanent deal in 2015 after having been the second-choice keeper for Bayern behind [[Manuel Neuer]]. In 2018, Reina left Napoli for [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] and 1.5 years later he completed a loan move to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].\n\nAt international level, Reina played for Spain's youth team, winning the [[UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]] in 1999. He made his senior debut in 2005, and has generally been selected as the second-choice keeper behind [[Iker Casillas]]. He was part of the Spain squad for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] and made one appearance in their victorious [[UEFA Euro 2008]] campaign, earning him his first international honour. He was later part of the Spain squads that won their first ever [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] and their third [[UEFA European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012]], as well as featuring at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] and [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]].\n\nReina is also the record holder for appearances by a Spanish player in the [[Premier League]], with more than 200 appearances in just his first five seasons, 108 of the 219 appearances being [[clean sheet]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.premierleague.com/players/2911/Pepe-Reina/stats | title = Players | publisher = premierleague.com | accessdate = 8 August 2014}}</ref> In the 2010\u201311 season, he kept his 100th Premier League clean sheet for Liverpool in a 3\u20130 win against Aston Villa.\n\n==Club career==\n===Barcelona===\nThe son of former [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] goalkeeper [[Miguel Reina]], Pepe Reina began his football career in the [[youth system|youth academy]] of Barcelona, [[La Masia]], in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2006/05/22/mas_futbol/1148279223_850215.html|title=23 Reina: Especialista en penaltis y en devorar bistecs|trans-title=23 Reina: Specialist in penalties and in devouring steaks |language=es|date=22 May 2006|accessdate=3 May 2019 |work=Diario AS}}</ref> From 1999, he played as a first-choice goalkeeper for the [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona reserve side]], which then competed in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third tier in the Spanish football pyramid]]. In 2000, At age 18, he was called up for the Barcelona first-team after the first and second choice goalkeepers, [[Richard Dutruel]] and [[Francesc Arnau]], suffered injuries. He made his debut as a substitute for Durtruel in a 3\u20133 draw with [[Celta de Vigo]] on 2 December 2000.<ref name=pepe>{{cite news|url=http://pepereina25.com/en/biografia/|title=Biography|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=pepereina25.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140422233200/http://pepereina25.com/en/biografia/|archive-date=22 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made 19 appearances in the remainder of the [[2000\u201301 La Liga]] season and appeared seven times in the [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup]],<ref name=pepe/> where ''Bar\u00e7a'' lost to Reina's future team [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at the semi-final stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/apr/19/minutebyminute.sport|title=Liverpool 1 v 0 Barcelona|date=20 April 2001|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nReina made 16 appearances for the club during the [[2001\u201302 FC Barcelona season|2001\u201302 season]], serving as understudy to [[Roberto Bonano]].<ref name=pepe/> On 31 October 2001, he made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in Barcelona's 1\u20130 group stage win against [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] at [[Camp Nou]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2001/matches/round=1545/match=1008613/index.html|title=Barcelona 1-0 Fenerbah\u00e7e|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=UEFA}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing the German goalkeeper [[Robert Enke]], Barcelona told Reina he was free to leave the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11833/2239120/reina-seals-villarreal-move|title=Reina seals Villarreal move|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=BSkyB}}</ref>\n\n===Villarreal===\nIn July 2002, Reina joined [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] and went on to spend three seasons with the Valencian club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/4085498.stm|title=Reina still keen for Anfield move|date=18 June 2005|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> In 2004, Villarreal reached the semi-final of the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] and, in Reina's final season at the club, he helped ''El Submarino Amarillo'' qualify for the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the first time in its history.<ref name=pepe/>\n\n===Liverpool===\n====2005\u201306 season====\n[[File:Pepe Reina.JPG|thumb|Reina playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2007]]\nReina was signed by Liverpool from Villarreal in July 2005, with manager [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]] hailing him as \"the best goalkeeper in Spain\". Reina made his Liverpool debut against Total Network Solutions, now known as [[The New Saints F.C.|The New Saints]], in the first qualifying round for the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League]].\n\nFor the [[2005\u201306 Liverpool F.C. season|2005\u201306 season]], Reina took over as Liverpool's first-choice goalkeeper, relegating [[2005 UEFA Champions League Final]] hero [[Jerzy Dudek]] to the bench. At the start of the season on 17 August 2005, Reina made his international debut for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in a friendly against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]. Spain won 2\u20130.\n\nThe season turned out to be successful for Liverpool as they improved upon the previous year's league placing and won the [[2005\u201306 FA Cup|FA Cup]]. It was also a huge success personally for Reina as he made [[List of Liverpool F.C. records and statistics|Liverpool records]]. On 3 December 2005, Reina kept his sixth consecutive [[clean sheet]] against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in the [[Premier League]], to break the Liverpool club record for successive clean sheets in the [[Premier League]]. He surpassed [[David James (footballer)|David James']] record of five games, from the [[1996\u201397 Liverpool F.C. season|1996\u201397 season]]. Reina's run ended at eight league games, when [[James Beattie (footballer)|James Beattie]] scored for [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in Liverpool's 3\u20131 [[Merseyside derby]] win on 28 December 2005. Reina also broke Liverpool's clean sheet record in all competitions, with 11 between October and December 2005. [[Mineiro (footballer)|Mineiro]], of [[S\u00e3o Paulo Futebol Clube|S\u00e3o Paulo]], finally scored past him on 18 December 2005, during the [[2005 FIFA Club World Cup]] final.\n\nOn 5 February 2006, in a Premier League match against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], Reina, having made a challenge on [[Ei\u00f0ur Gu\u00f0johnsen]] moments earlier, was [[Misconduct (football)|sent off]] for violent conduct against [[Arjen Robben]]. Robben, who fell to the ground,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4744098.stm | work=BBC News | title=Mourinho in a mess | date=23 February 2006 | accessdate=7 May 2010 | first=Jonathan | last=Stevenson}}</ref> was described as \"going down like he'd been sledgehammered\" by pundit [[Alan Hansen]]. Liverpool lost the match 2\u20130 and Reina was given a three-match suspension. On 16 April 2006, Reina celebrated his 50th appearance for Liverpool by keeping a clean sheet against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. As a result, he holds a Liverpool record for the fewest goals conceded by a goalkeeper in his first 50 matches. The previous record was set by [[Ray Clemence]] in [[1970\u201371 Liverpool F.C. season|1970\u201371]], when he conceded 32 goals. Reina conceded just 29. In May 2006, Reina was awarded the Premier League's [[Barclays Golden Glove|Golden Glove]] award for keeping 20 clean sheets in the [[2005\u201306 FA Premier League|2005\u201306 season]].\n\nIn the final domestic match of the season \u2013 the [[2006 FA Cup Final]] on 13 May 2006 \u2013 Reina made a number of errors to allow [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] to lead 3\u20132. [[Steven Gerrard]] took the match to [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] with a late equaliser. The match ended 3\u20133 and went to [[Penalty shootout|penalties]], where Reina saved three out of four penalties to gain the cup win.\n\n====2006\u201307 season====\nDuring the [[2006\u201307 FA Premier League|2006\u201307 season]], Reina's status as Liverpool's number-one goalkeeper was further cemented after Jerzy Dudek conceded nine goals within a week in two cup ties against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].{{cn|date=January 2019}} After the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|2007 Champions League]] semi-final first-leg against Chelsea, Reina was awarded man of the match by Liverpool supporters after a string of superb saves, including two saves from midfielder [[Frank Lampard]]. He repeated his good form in the second leg, keeping a clean sheet. The match went to a penalty shootout, where Reina reinforced his penalty-saving reputation, stopping two of the three Chelsea kicks as Liverpool won 4\u20131. On his return home from the match, he discovered his house in [[Woolton]] had been burgled.{{cn|date=January 2019}} \n\nThree weeks later in [[Athens]], Reina became only the third player to follow in his father's footsteps by appearing in a [[List of European Cup and UEFA Champions League finals|European Cup final]].{{cn|date=January 2019}} Liverpool lost [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final|2\u20131]] in the final to [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]. Reina signed a new five-year contract Liverpool on 7 June 2007.<ref name=\"Reina pens new Liverpool contract\">{{cite news | title = Reina pens new Liverpool contract | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/6731279.stm | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 7 June 2007 | accessdate = 7 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2007, Reina again won the Premier League's Golden Glove Award for the second successive season, after keeping 19 clean sheets in the [[2006\u201307 FA Premier League|2006\u201307 Premier League]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web | title = Reina nets goalkeeping award | url = http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-nets-goalkeeping-award | accessdate = 10 October 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141006113019/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-nets-goalkeeping-award | archivedate = 6 October 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308 season====\n[[File:PepeReina.JPG|thumb|upright|Reina playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in 2009]]\nReina began the season by saving a penalty from [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]'s [[Nwankwo Kanu]] to help his team to a 0\u20130 draw.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6984881.stm|title=Portsmouth 0-0 Liverpool  |date=15 September 2007|accessdate=15 September 2015|work=BBC}}</ref> On 2 February 2008, Reina became the quickest goalkeeper in Liverpool history to reach 50 clean sheets. He hit the milestone during a 3\u20130 win against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], on his 92nd league outing, beating the previous record by three.<ref>{{cite web | title = Jos\u00e9 Manuel breaks Anfield record | url = http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N158702080203-0937.htm | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080524040850/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N158702080203-0937.htm | archivedate = 24 May 2008 | accessdate = 3 February 2008}}</ref>\n\nReina played all 38 [[2007\u201308 Premier League|Premier League]] matches for Liverpool and won his third consecutive Golden Glove award with 18 clean sheets.<ref name=decline>{{cite news|url=http://talksport.com/magazine/features/121205/why-pepe-reinas-decline-may-be-liverpools-fault-and-arsenals-gain-186869|title=Why Pepe Reina's 'decline' may be Liverpool's fault and Arsenal's gain|date=5 December 2012| accessdate = 21 April 2014|work=TalkSport}}</ref>\n\n====2008\u201309 season====\nReina played every minute of Liverpool's [[2008\u201309 Premier League|2008\u201309 Premier League season]], keeping 20 clean sheets,<ref name=decline/> as the team finished as league runners-up with 86 points.<ref name=brink>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-v-swansea-preview-3359337|title=Liverpool F.C. v Swansea Preview: Pepe Reina on brink of another Reds landmark|date=5 November 2011|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=Liverpool Echo}}</ref> On 22 March 2009, Reina kept his 100th clean sheet for Liverpool in a Premier League match against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1166123/Liverpool-keeper-Reina-world-Anfield-skipper-Gerrard.html|title=Liverpool keeper Reina on top of the world for Anfield skipper Gerrard|date=31 March 2009|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=Daily Mail}}</ref> During the match, he assisted a goal for [[Albert Riera]] with a long pass in Liverpool's 5\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7937107.stm|title=Liverpool 5-0 Aston Villa|date=22 March 2009| access-date = 2 July 2015|work=BBC | first = Phil | last = McNulty}}</ref>\n\n====2009\u201310 season====\nReina again played all 38 matches during the [[2009\u201310 Premier League]] season, keeping 17 clean sheets.<ref name=pots>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-crowned-player-of-09-10|title=Reina crowned Player of 09-10|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=Liverpool F.C.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423040503/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/reina-crowned-player-of-09-10|archivedate=23 April 2014}}</ref> He tied with Chelsea's [[Petr \u010cech]] for the Golden Glove award for the season, but \u010cech was awarded the trophy with a superior goals-to-game ratio. Reina was named Liverpool's Player of the Season for [[2009\u201310 Liverpool F.C. season|2009\u201310]] with 75% of the vote.<ref name=pots/>\n\nOn 17 October 2009, Liverpool were beaten 1\u20130 by Sunderland with a goal from [[Darren Bent]], which was deflected past Reina via a beach ball thrown from the crowd.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8308907.stm|title=Sunderland 1 - 0 Liverpool|date=17 October 2009|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010, Reina signed a new six-year contract with Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/pepe-reina-signs-new-six-year-2757837 | title = Pepe Reina signs new six-year deal at Liverpool F.C. | publisher = dailypost.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\nReina got his [[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010\u201311 season]] off to a poor start, with a late own goal to give Arsenal a 1\u20131 draw in Liverpool's opening Premier League fixture. Manager [[Roy Hodgson]], club [[Captain (association football)|captain]] Steven Gerrard and vice-captain [[Jamie Carragher]] were all quick to get behind Reina and back him to not let the mistake affect his season.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8916002.stm | work=BBC News | title=Hodgson backs Reina after blunder | date=15 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/latest-news/stevie-reina-will-make-up-for-it |title=Stevie: Reina will make up for it \u2013 Liverpool F.C. |publisher=Liverpoolfc.tv |date=16 August 2010 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819121130/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/latest-news/stevie-reina-will-make-up-for-it |archivedate=19 August 2010  }}</ref>\n\nReina captained the team in [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] matches against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] and [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] due to the absences of Steven Gerrard and Jamie Carragher. On 6 December 2010, Reina captained Liverpool in the Premier League in a 3\u20130 victory against Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/latest-news/reina-to-skipper-reds |title=Reina to skipper Reds \u2013 Liverpool F.C. |publisher=Liverpoolfc.tv |date=1 December 2010 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204113359/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/latest-news/reina-to-skipper-reds |archivedate=4 December 2010  }}</ref> This clean sheet gave him his 100th in 198 league matches, the fastest Liverpool goalkeeper to reach the milestone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11662/6561187/reinas-ton-good|title=Reina's ton good|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=21 May 2014|work=BSkyB}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2011, Reina played his 150th consecutive league match for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/kenny-reina-s-the-world-s-best|title=Kenny: Reina's the world's best|date=17 May 2011|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=Liverpool F.C.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227061713/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/kenny-reina-s-the-world-s-best|archivedate=27 February 2014}}</ref> He was one of only two players to have played in all of Liverpool's league games for 2010\u201311 season.<ref name=brink/> In June 2011, Reina underwent double [[hernia]] surgery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jun/13/pepe-reina-liverpool|title=Liverpool optimistic for pre-season after Jos\u00e9 Reina's hernia surgery|date=13 June 2011|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\n[[File:Pepe Reina vs Bolton 2011 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Reina with Liverpool in 2011]]\nReina announced on 3 September 2011 that he wanted to stay at Liverpool for another five or six years.<ref name=\"reina fitness 2011\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14106863.stm|title=Kenny Dalglish upbeat over fitness of Gerrard and Reina|date=11 July 2011|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2011, Reina broke the club record for most clean sheets in a 2\u20130 [[2011\u201312 Football League Cup|Football League Cup]] quarter-final win over Chelsea. The record had previously been held by Ray Clemence and [[Bruce Grobelaar]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=48716/profile/index.html|title=Pepe Reina|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=UEFA}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2012, Reina won his second major honour with Liverpool, beating [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] on penalties in the [[2012 Football League Cup Final|2012 League Cup final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/337027?cc=5739|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229015220/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/337027|archivedate=29 February 2012|title=Reds win Carling Cup on penalties|date=26 February 2012|work=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=11 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2012, Reina received a red card in a 2\u20130 defeat against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] due to violent conduct on Newcastle player [[James Perch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/318250?cc=5739|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406083209/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/318250?cc=5739|archivedate=6 April 2012 |title=Liverpool take an April fall|date=1 April 2012|work=ESPN Soccernet|accessdate=11 April 2012 }}</ref>\nReina's suspension ended his streak of 183 consecutive Premier League appearances which had begun in August 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17503293|title=Newcastle 2-0 Liverpool|date=1 April 2012|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> He missed Premier League matches against Aston Villa and Blackburn Rovers, as well as the FA Cup semi-final against Everton on 14 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/9180855/Liverpools-Glen-Johnson-blames-James-Perch-for-Pepe-Reinas-suspension.html|title=Liverpool's Glen Johnson blames James Perch for Pepe Reina's suspension|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 May, Reina started for Liverpool in their 2\u20131 [[2012 FA Cup Final]] defeat to Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/17878435|title=Chelsea 2-1 Liverpool|date=5 May 2012|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn 30 August 2012, Reina made a mistake in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] to give the [[Edinburgh]] club the lead at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/9510207/Liverpool-1-Heart-of-Midlothian-1-2-1-agg-match-report.html|title=Liverpool 1 Heart of Midlothian 1; 2-1 agg: match report|date=30 August 2012|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> He made another error against [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]], allowing [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]] to score a late equaliser in a 2\u20132 draw on 3 February 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/brendan-rodgers-says-liverpool-are-bitterly-disappointed-following-jose-reina-mistake-8479490.html|title=Brendan Rodgers says Liverpool are 'bitterly disappointed' following Jose Reina 'mistake'|date=3 February 2013|accessdate=21 April 2014|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of the [[2012\u201313 Liverpool F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]], rumours suggested that [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]] was to leave [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] and Reina was to be his replacement. According to his father, an agreement had been reached for Reina to sign, but when Vald\u00e9s chose to stay at Barcelona for another season, no move took place.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/2013/11/08/en/football/barcelona/1383937664.html |title='Reina had an agreement with Barcelona' |work=Marca |date=11 August 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> In anticipation of Reina's departure, Liverpool had signed [[Belgium national football team|Belgian international]] goalkeeper [[Simon Mignolet]] from Sunderland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11669/8841302/brendan-rodgers-explains-napoli-loan-move-for-liverpool-keeper-pepe-reina |title=Brendan Rodgers explains Napoli loan move for Liverpool keeper Pepe Reina |first=Tim |last=Oscroft |publisher=Sky Sports |date=26 July 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> As a result, on 29 July 2013 Reina completed a loan move to [[Serie A]] side [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], reuniting him with former Liverpool manager [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/140030-reds-confirm-pepe-reina-loan-move |title=Reds confirm Pepe Reina loan move |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=29 July 2013 |accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Napoli====\nReina was loaned out to Napoli for the [[2013\u201314 S.S.C. Napoli season|2013\u201314 season]]. Liverpool failed to inform Reina about the loan prior to the move.<ref name=\"Liverpool's Pepe Reina regrets manner of Napoli move\">{{cite news|title=Liverpool's Pepe Reina regrets manner of Napoli move|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/23487934|accessdate=6 August 2014|publisher=BBC Sports|date=29 July 2013}}</ref> He had made 394 appearances for Liverpool prior to the loan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pepe Reina: Liverpool keeper set to move to Bayern Munich|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/28669117|accessdate=6 August 2014|publisher=BBC Sports|date=5 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Reina saved a penalty from [[Lukas Podolski]] against Arsenal in the pre-season [[Emirates Cup]] tournament,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/aug/03/arsenal-napoli-emirates-cup |title=Arsenal turn boos to cheers after coming back to draw with Napoli |first=Simon |last=Burnton |newspaper=The Observer |date=3 August 2013 |accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref> and in September, in a 2\u20131 win over Milan in September, he saved a [[Mario Balotelli]] penalty, the first goalkeeper ever to do so in a competitive match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/sep/23/mario-balotelli-miss-rafael-benitz-napoli |title=Mario Balotelli's miss overshadows Rafael Ben\u00edtez's Napoli revolution |first=Paolo |last=Bandini |website=The Guardian |date=23 September 2013 |accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September, Reina declared that his Liverpool career was over: \"At the moment it's difficult to think about being a Liverpool player next year. They have a young goalkeeper in Simon Mignolet and the manager prefers him to me. That's the reason why I'm here and he will be at the club next year as well. There's no reason to think I'll be a Liverpool player from now on but we'll see where the future takes us. It's been a good move so far and I don't regret what happened. I would have preferred to say goodbye in a different way.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2435679/PEPE-REINA-My-Liverpool-days-Ill-back.html | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Pepe Reina exclusive: My Liverpool days are over, I'll never go back | first = Matt | last = Barlow | date = 27 September 2013 | accessdate = 8 August 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Pepe Reina 2016.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Reina playing for Napoli in 2016]]\n\nOn 3 May 2014, Reina won the [[Coppa Italia]] with Napoli after a 3\u20131 win against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.espnfc.com/uk/en/report/388636/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504023056/http://www.espnfc.com/uk/en/report/388636/report.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739|archivedate=4 May 2014|title= Insigne brace seals Coppa|date=3 May 2014|work=ESPN|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Bayern Munich===\nOn 8 August 2014, Liverpool confirmed<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/168538-reina-joins-bayern-munich | title = Reina joins Bayern Munich | publisher = Liverpool F.C. | date= 8 August 2014 | accessdate= 8 August 2014}}</ref> Reina had joined the [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] on a three-year deal, bringing an eight-year spell with the club to an end. He wore the number 23 shirt for Bayern, the same number he wears for the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbayern.de/en/news/news/2014/news-in-brief-080814.php|title= Reina inks three-year deal | publisher = FC Bayern Munich | date = 8 August 2014 | accessdate= 8 August 2014}}</ref> On 14 March 2015, Reina made his debut for Bayern, starring in a 4\u20130 away win against [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=SV Werder Bremen 0-4 Bayern Munich|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31875401|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 March 2015|date=14 March 2015}}</ref> His appearance in that match meant that he became the first goalkeeper and Spaniard in history to play in four of Europe's top leagues: [[La Liga|Spain]], [[Premier League|England]], [[Serie A|Italy]] and [[Bundesliga|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.goal.com/en/news/15/germany/2015/03/14/9814452/pepe-reina-the-first-goalkeeper-to-play-in-europes-big-four | title = Pepe Reina the first goalkeeper to play in Europe's big four leagues | publisher = goal.com | date = 14 March 2015 | accessdate = 15 March 2015 | first = Tony | last =  Mahoney}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://metro.co.uk/2015/03/14/pepe-reina-becomes-first-goalkeeper-to-play-in-all-four-of-europes-top-leagues-with-bayern-munich-start-against-werder-bremen-5103851/ | title = Pepe Reina becomes first goalkeeper to play in all four of Europe's top leagues after Bayern Munich start against Werder Bremen | publisher = metro.co.uk | date = 14 March 2015 | accessdate = 15 March 2015 | first = Vaishali | last = Bhardwaj}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sportsjoe.ie/football/pepe-reina-broke-a-few-records-by-starting-for-bayern-munich-today/17465 | title = Pepe Reina broke a few records by starting for Bayern Munich today | publisher = sportsjoe.ie | date = 14 March 2015 | accessdate = 15 March 2015 | first = Robert | last = Redmond}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May, as Bayern had already won the [[2014\u201315 Bundesliga]] and had a Champions League semi-final second leg against Barcelona to come, regular goalkeeper [[Manuel Neuer]] was rested for their home match against [[FC Augsburg]] and Reina started. He was given a straight red card after 14 minutes when he conceded a penalty with a foul on [[Ra\u00fal Bobadilla]]; Neuer came on in place of [[Philipp Lahm]] but [[Paul Verhaegh]] hit the post for Augsburg, which eventually won 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayern Mun 0-1 FC Augsburg|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32589589|accessdate=9 May 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Napoli===\nOn 23 June 2015, it was announced that Reina would return to Napoli on a three-year deal, after a one-year spell at Bayern Munich.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Pepe Reina al Napoli | trans-title = Pepe Reina to Napoli |url=http://www.sscnapoli.it/static/news/Pepe-Reina-al-Napoli-5616.aspx | publisher=S.S.C. Napoli |date=23 June 2015 | accessdate = 23 June 2015 | language = it}}</ref>\n\n===A.C. Milan===\nOn 15 May 2018, it was announced that Reina would move to [[Serie A]] rivals [[A.C. Milan]] on a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman]] transfer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/reina-arrival-donnarumma-exit-ac-milan-mirabelli-liverpool/tvcahumtcz7r11jfbvxis62rx|title= Reina arrival does not mean Donnarumma exit - AC Milan's Mirabelli| website = Goal.com | date = 15 May 2018 | access-date = 18 May 2018 | first = Jamie | last = Smith}}</ref> The deal was officialized on 2 July 2018 and he signed a three-year contract with the ''Rossoneri''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/media/2018-07-02/official-reina-and-strinic-are-rossoneri|title= Official: Reina and Strinic are Rossoneri| website = A.C. Milan | date = 2 July 2018 | access-date = 3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Aston Villa====\nOn 13 January 2020, Reina joined Premier League side [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on loan for the rest of the 2019\u201320 season; after the team's usual first choice goalkeeper [[Tom Heaton]] was ruled out through injury until the summer.<ref name=\"sky-loan\">{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11677/11905781/pepe-reina-aston-villa-agree-loan-deal-with-ac-milan-for-rest-of-season |title=Pepe Reina: Aston Villa agree loan deal with AC Milan for rest of season|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]  |date=10 January 2020 |accessdate=10 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avfc.co.uk/News/2020/01/13/pepe-reina-joins-aston-villa|title=Pepe Reina joins Aston Villa on loan|last=|first=|date=13 January 2020|website=[[Aston Villa F.C.]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Spain national football team Euro 2012 trophy 03.jpg|thumb|Reina with the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]], celebrating winning [[UEFA Euro 2012]]]]\nReina has been a regular in the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]] since 2005, mostly as second-choice keeper after [[Iker Casillas]]. He was part of the team that won the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 European Championships]].\n\nReina made his debut on 17 August 2005, keeping a clean sheet in a 2\u20130 friendly win over [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at [[El Molin\u00f3n]] in [[Gij\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Espa\u00f1a vence 2-0 a Uruguay en amistoso|trans-title=Spain win 2-0 against Uruguay in a friendly|url=http://www.eluniverso.com/2005/08/17/0001/15/A1F2254791134622A4192B503D0C10B5.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=El Universo|agency=Associated Press|date=17 August 2005|language=Spanish}}</ref> He was a member of the Spanish squad which reached the last 16 of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], but did not play. At [[UEFA Euro 2008]], he played the final group match in [[Salzburg]] as Spain had already advanced, conceding a header by reigning champion [[Greece national football team|Greece]]'s [[Angelos Charisteas]], although Spain came back to win 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McKenzie|first1=Andrew|title=Russia 2-0 Sweden & Greece 1-2 Spain|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363473.stm|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, he and Casillas together broke the national record for the longest time spent without conceding a goal after defeating [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] 3\u20130. The pair went unbeaten for 710 minutes since Reina conceded from Charisteas, longer than the legendary [[Andoni Zubizarreta]] and [[Francisco Buyo]]. [[Wesley Sonck]] of [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] ended their streak when he scored against Casillas in a World Cup qualifier later that month.<ref>{{cite news|title=B\u00e9lgica pone fin a la imbatibilidad de Espa\u00f1a|trans-title=Belgium put a stop to Spain's inpenetrability|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/camino_al_mundial/2010/es/desarrollo/1175620.html|accessdate=16 April 2015|publisher=Marca|date=15 October 2008|language=Spanish}}</ref> The following year, he was part of the Spanish squad which reached the semi-finals at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in South Africa. His sole appearance was in the last group game in [[Bloemfontein]], keeping a clean sheet in a 2\u20130 win over hosts [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]], a result which was a world record 15th consecutive international victory for Spain.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spain 2-0 South Africa|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8108987.stm|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=20 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nReina was also in Spain's squad for the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Confederations Cup]], in which they reached [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|the final]]. His sole appearance in the tournament came in the second group game against Oceanian champions [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]], a 10\u20130 win at the [[Maracan\u00e3 Stadium|Maracan\u00e3]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Magowan|first1=Alistair|title=Spain 10-0 Tahiti|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22896367|accessdate=16 April 2015|work=BBC Sport|date=20 June 2013}}</ref> With Spain's elimination already confirmed, he was selected to start in Spain's final group match of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] keeping a clean sheet against [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] in a 3\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285263|title=Australia 0-3 Spain|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=24 June 2014|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, he was named in Spain's final squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Morata misses out on Spain's 23-man World Cup squad|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/morata-misses-out-on-spain-world-cup-squad/1ub1qz7jod09i1lfvdcy84ea2l|date=21 May 2018 | access-date = 21 May 2018 | first = Tom | last = Maston}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nReina is well known for his distribution, ball skills, technique, positioning, shot-stopping, leadership, and ability to save penalties; he has also functioned as a \"[[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|sweeper-keeper]]\" on occasion throughout his career, due to his anticipation and speed when rushing off his line, as well as his ability to start plays or create chances from the back.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/gigi-buffon-announces-he-will-retire-after-the-2018-fifa-world-c-192724|title=Gigi Buffon announces he will retire after the 2018 FIFA World Cup|publisher=calciomercato|author1=Lorenzo Bettoni|date=25 January 2016|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/pepe-reina-semi-tragic-tale-keeper-all-right-places-wrong-times#:rEAxPZ7eIaBWPA|title=Pepe Reina: the semi-tragic tale of a keeper in all the right places at the wrong times|publisher=FourFourTwo|author1=Alex Hess|date=18 March 2015|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/pepe-reina-liverpool-napoli-julio-cesar-rafa-492375|title=Benitez Seeks Napoli Reunion With Liverpool Shot Stopper - Report|publisher=International Business Times|author1=Tony Morgan|date=19 July 2013|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/8916701/Liverpool-goalkeeper-Pepe-Reina-believes-club-are-on-the-right-road-to-fulfilling-their-Europe-dream.html|title=Liverpool goalkeeper Pepe Reina believes club are on the right road to fulfilling their Europe dream|publisher=The Telegraph|author1=Duncan White|date=26 November 2011|accessdate=15 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/news/y=2009/m=9/news=peter-seeking-inspiration-from-petr-1109483.html|title=Peter seeking inspiration from Petr|publisher=FIFA.com|date=29 September 2009|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/slideshow/3849/23/title/guida-ai-volti-nuovi-della-serie-a-201314|title=Pepe Reina (Napoli)|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/117796/buffon-%E2%80%98juventus-were-presumptuous%E2%80%99|title=Buffon: 'Juventus were presumptuous'|publisher=Football Italia|date=27 February 2018|accessdate=27 February 2018}}</ref> Fellow goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]] named Reina as the best goalkeeper of his era with his feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://90min.com/posts/2732836-gianluigi-buffon-names-arsenal-s-petr-cech-as-the-best-goalkeeper-of-his-era|title=Gianluigi Buffon Names Arsenal's Petr Cech as the Best Goalkeeper of his Era|publisher=90min|author=Mahmoud Jaber|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref> He has set a number of goalkeeping records for Liverpool and won the [[Barclays Golden Glove|Premier League Golden Glove]] award for most clean sheets in a single season in his first three seasons at the club.\n\n==Personal life==\nReina married his longtime girlfriend Yolanda Ruiz in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|C\u00f3rdoba]] on 19 May 2006,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.totalfootballmadness.com/2010/05/11/wags-yolanda-ruiz-wife-of-pepe-reina/ | title = WAGS \u2013 Yolanda Ruiz, Wife Of Pepe Rein | publisher = totalfootballmadness.com | date = 11 May 2010 | accessdate = 8 August 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140808061939/http://www.totalfootballmadness.com/2010/05/11/wags-yolanda-ruiz-wife-of-pepe-reina/ | archivedate = 8 August 2014 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> before joining up with the Spain national squad for the 2006 World Cup. The couple have five children. Reina was the former next door neighbour of [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] striker and Spanish international teammate [[Fernando Torres]].<ref name=\"neighbour\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/mar/05/eternal-love-pepe-reina-liverpool|title=I'm happy but I won't swear eternal love to anyone, says Pepe Reina|first=Sid|last=Lowe|work=The Guardian |date=5 March 2011|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> When he was at Liverpool, Reina was neighbours with teammate [[Luis Su\u00e1rez]].<ref name=\"neighbour\" /> \n\nReina's father [[Miguel Reina]] was in goal for Atl\u00e9tico Madrid in the [[1974 European Cup Final]], which Atl\u00e9tico lost to Bayern Munich 4\u20130 in a replay after the first match finished 1\u20131.\n\nAlthough a steely and serious figure as goalkeeper, Reina is known for his exuberant, jester-like character off the pitch, often entertaining his teammates with jokes and songs,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QKPYuIVenf8|title=Pepe Reina SUPERLOCO en el avi\u00f3n!|first=|last=FCule|date=30 June 2008|publisher=|accessdate=21 June 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vLMedpU9bA4|title=Reina sings to Casillas and Sara in the plane. - Celebraci\u00f3n en el avi\u00f3n.|first=|last=TodosConLaRoja|date=12 July 2010|publisher=|accessdate=21 June 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> and famously acting as a crowd-pleasing master of ceremonies at Spain's official victory celebrations following the 2008 European Championship,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vzlYXf3WXwo|title=Pepe Reina y la presentaci\u00f3n de los campeones.|first=|last=Luis Sanchez|date=13 September 2008|publisher=|accessdate=21 June 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> the 2010 World Cup<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C6dINpHN6ao|title=YouTube|publisher=|accessdate=21 June 2016}}</ref> and Euro 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FeRGBk-kzEE|title=Pepe Reina Show Euro 2012 cz. 1|first=|last=DumaKataloniiPL|date=4 July 2012|publisher=|accessdate=21 June 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Reina and former [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] footballers [[Paolo Cannavaro]] and [[Salvatore Aronica]] were subject to a hearing by the [[Italian Football Federation]] over links to the [[Luigi Esposito (criminal)|Esposito brothers]], high-ranking members of the [[Camorra]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Reina faces hearing over links with trio connected to mafia|url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2018/05/21/reina-faces-hearing-over-links-with-trio-connected-to-mafia/|website=NBC SPORTS|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Reina was also accused of trying to get free tickets for the [[Lo Russo clan|Lo Russo Camorra clan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Napoli goalkeeper Pepe Reina to face disciplinary hearing over mafia links|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/napoli/story/3506491/napoli-goalkeeper-pepe-reina-to-face-disciplinary-hearing-over-mafia-links|website=ESPN|date=21 May 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, he tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/pepe-reina-coronavirus-news-aston-villa-a4403521.html|title=Reina on his coronavirus battle: 'For 25 minutes I ran out of oxygen'|date=1 April 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|the match played 9 March 2020}}<ref>{{soccerbase|24340}}</ref><ref name=\"Soccerway\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"Cup\">Includes [[Copa del Rey]], [[FA Cup]], [[Coppa Italia]], and [[DFB-Pokal]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[FC Barcelona C|Barcelona C]]\n|[[1998\u201399 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|1998\u201399]]\n|[[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u20132000]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|30||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||0\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2000\u201301]]\n|11||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!41!!0!!0!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!41!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|[[2000\u201301 FC Barcelona season|2000\u201301]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[La Liga]]\n|19||0||7||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UC\">All appearances in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup/Europa League]]</ref>\n||0||33||0\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 FC Barcelona season|2001\u201302]]\n|11||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\">All appearances in the [[UEFA Champions League]]</ref>\n||0||16||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|T